INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (41, 'PCB_History_and_Development_41', '2019-10-12 13:53:37', NULL, 69, 0, 0, '    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Pcb is an important piece of technological hardware, they make their presence felt in almost every aspect of our modern world.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While their use is widespread and generally noticed by the average population, there is another aspect to it, which is not so well known; its history and development. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Not many people know the history and development of PCBs, and it is indeed an interesting story unto itself. The history and development of PCBs goes back several decades, to the age of modern technological computing. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span></span></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-16/timg.jpg\" alt=\"timg.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To start off, there was a time when there were no PCBs, and instead, were what wired point-to-point circuits on a chassis were. These chassis in turn, were usually designed using a sheet metal frame, and which sometimes came with a wooden bottom. The various components of this primitive circuit were attached with the help of metal fixtures, soldering, and crimp connections and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as it was effective in getting the job done, the technology proved to be very rudimentary, large, bulky and heavy. In addition to this, it was also very fragile and could easily be damaged. It was partly for this reason that a newer form of circuitry was envisioned. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;One of the earliest developments of PCBs came about when a German inventor, Albert Hanson, in 1903, described a flat foil conductor laminated to an insulating board, in several layers. On the other side of the Atlantic in the United States, Thomas Edison worked on chemical based platings to create a conducting layer on linen paper in 1904. Similar experiments were carried out in other parts of the world as well. All of these served as the basis on which to build the modern PCB.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The modern PCB started to take form when an Austrian engineer named Paul Eisler invented a printed board as part of a larger radio set project in the UK. The first large scale use of this PCB technology came about during World War II, when the US military started using it to create proximity fuses in warfare. It should be noted that the technology was still in military hands at the time, with the commercial use of the technology being kept beyond the reach of this technology. After the war, the technology was released for civilian use, from when it started to really become commercialized. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>At first, they didn\'t seem like much, given that the technology was still in its infancy. With the passage of time however, things started to take off regarding PCBs, particularly with the rise of consumer electronics. Although they had widespread applications, some of the most common places where they found adoption were in the manufacture of televisions and radios. It should be noted that even during this time, there was large scale use of the more rudimentary point-to-point chassis. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The technology underwent several different changes during this stage. For example, originally, all of the electronic components used to have wire leads in the design, with the PCBs having holes drilled in them for each of the wire leads used in the circuit assembly, which in turn was inserted through the holes and then soldered to copper PCB traces. This technology eventually gave way to the one where lamination and etching would be used to create the circuits, similar to the technology used today. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The technological evolution remained largely the same at the foundational level, albeit with some minor changes in the manufacturing process. The next real change came about with the rise of multi-level circuits, wherein there were several different circuits combined and compressed on top of each other. This process began around the 1990s, and became an industry standard with the passage of time. In fact, the modern multi-layer circuits which are used in the world are very much similar to the designs of these early chips, albeit with the many improvements that have been made over the years.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most iconic developments of this era was that of HDI or ‘High Density Interconnect’ chips, using ‘Microvia’ technology, which allowed for the creation of high-density circuits on a much smaller area. In simple words, this technology allowed for the circuit chips to be created in a way that allowed for a greater number of circuits per unit area, thereby allowing the circuits to have a higher capacity than its predecessors. Today, the same HDI technology is in use, in combination with ‘multi-level’ designs to create circuits that are extremely dense, fast and efficient. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Today, the technology is still evolving, with large scale investment and research into the advancement of this circuitry technology. Among the many trends that have emerged include, among others, the adoption of artificial intelligence, automation, better materials, and improvements in manufacturing processes and so on.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And then there is the use of 3D printing, which has greatly reduced the price of the chips, while at the same time allowing for large scale production of high quality circuitry. This is one of the technologies that have been of significant interest to manufacturers and researchers, given the potential of this new emerging technology.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These are just some of the technologies that are currently being tested out, with many more in the works as well. All of these are still technologies still in the works, and which are certainly promising. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To sum up, the above is just a general idea on the way PCBs evolved in society, in terms of its general history and development. It is a brief read that should give an idea of how this iconic modern day technology came about, from its early days to its present form. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, it should be added here that many finer and ‘not so important’ details have been eliminated along the way, so as to create a brief ‘summary’ of how the technology emerged. It is in no way a conclusive and complete report, but rather an introduction to the subject. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Feel free to do your own research, if you would like to know more about how the story of this technology played out in recent times. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>      ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, ' PCB History and Development', ' PCB History,  PCB Development', 'Pcb is an important piece of technological hardware, they make their presence felt in almost every aspect of our modern world.    ', 0, '2019-10-22 14:28:33', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (42, 'PCB_Layout_Considerations_42', '2019-10-15 17:28:43', NULL, 55, 0, 0, '   <p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Introduction:</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>PCB, also known as Printed Circuit Boards, is a common name in the world of electronics. PCB works as a surface which aims to provide support and proper wiring to the components and conducting materials to the electronics. It joins various points together with the aid of pads and lines. The conducting materials used in the making of PCBs are copper, heat sinks, pads and so on. Other than this, it contains an insulating material wrapped between the conductors. Printed Circuits Boards play a key role in providing power and signals to the devices. A printed circuit board must have a well-designed layout in order to increase its reliability and effectiveness. The importance of designing it is as important as component selection, and is worth time-consuming. If your layout isn’t effective enough, it can cause issues such as weak functioning of the components, faulty board and electromagnetic interference. If a person isn’t able to design the layout correctly in the first time, it can result in increased costs. To get rid of all these issues, one has to follow a set of rules and steps to design your layout. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Composition Of PCB:</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>A PCB isn’t a simple as it looks. Its complexity lies within the layers of materials it is composed of. The lower most layer is composed of substrate. It is usually a fiberglass, which is usually FR4. It provides toughness and thickness to it. The next material to be used is a thin sheet of copper, which is usually applied to both sides of the fiberglass. It sticks to the board with the help of heat. The copper layers can range from one to sixteen layers. The copper foil is usually thin, still its thickness may vary in different PCBs.The soldermask aims to protect the copper foil from other metals or solder, hence providing insulation to it. The silkscreen layer, which is usually white in colour, is supposed to be the top most layer of the Printed Circuit Board layout. On this layer, we can find symbols, letters and numbers so that it is readable and understandable by the humans. Silkscreen is used as an indicator to tell what each LED or pin is to be used for. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-16/pcb layout.jpg\" alt=\"pcb layout.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Steps To Design A&nbsp;</span></b><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-layout\" style=\"font-weight: bold;\">PCB Layout</a><b><span>:</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>After knowing that PCB is required, one should start working on the concept of the layout. He should be able to recognize what tasks is PCB supposed to perform. Also, there should be an idea about the features, how to locate it in the product, the sizes and lengths of the board and so on. Other than this, one should have an idea about the range of temperatures on which the PCB can work best. The other step involves developing your schematic. This contains all the required details of the rating, value and name of the components. You also need to maintain the bill of materials where you will be enlisting all the components needed for the PCB. The next step involves having a board level block diagram. This gives you an idea of dimensions of the PCB. You need to identify different regions of the components which are needed to be connected electrically. Another step involves placing the components in the PCB. It is a task which requires a lot of time to be fulfilled, as placing components is not often finalised in the first take. First-Pass Routing is yet another step to be followed. As the name suggests, one should know the possible routing of the circuit. The next which is required to be done is testing. Tests are done to make sure design is completed. If it does not match your requirements, some amendments are supposed to be done in the back stages. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Design Considerations For A&nbsp;</span></b><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-layout\" style=\"font-weight: bold;\">PCB Layout</a><b><span>:</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There is a whole lot of things to be considered while designing a PCB. One of them is linked with the structure of the board, its shape and size. The PCBs are mostly are rectangular in shape. It should be considered that they aren’t shaped irregularly and must have enough space to accommodate all the desired components. One should also consider the number of layers they require. Adding more layers can make it more costly as per the production point of view, but the tracks are too raised through it. Other main consideration is regarding the manufacturing process. One needs to make use of reference holes which are supposed to be free of components on the board. When you are designing the layout of your PCB, you should know which components and materials are to be placed on the board. Some items aren’t available in the market or are too expensive to come across.Once who have all items in hand, you can startworking on the PCB. One should be aware of the order of components to be placed. There is known placement which works for most of the PCBs. The first in line are the connectors. Next comes the series of circuits including power circuits, precision circuits and critical circuits. The rest of the components are to be placed after this. Another consideration to make is placing the similar components in same direction. Thisenhances the process of soldering. Proper organization of the components is yet another important consideration to make. The costs are reduced and efficiency is increased. Other than this, the ground and power planes are to be kept inside of your board symmetrically. You should also know your track design and that it must be concise. Obtaining the correct ratio for size of pad to hole is also important. Other than this, it is prior to eliminate electrical issues from the PCB. One should also avoid thermal issues by letting heat dissipate. Plus, the process of testing should be continued from manufacturing till designing. This helps you fix your problems easily.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion: </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, Printed Circuit Boards are supposed to be made with deep consideration and must be carefully checked at every stage. It is important to make sure you are placing the right components in the right order and time, to minimise errors.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>     ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'PCB Layout Considerations', 'PCB Layout ', '   The layout of pcb must follow certain rules and order in order to make pcb play its biggest role.   ', 0, '2019-10-16 11:26:04', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (43, 'Advantages_of_Multi-Layer_PCB_43', '2019-10-16 11:51:20', NULL, 29, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing that people can find in abundance in the modern world, it is PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs, or ‘printed circuit boards’, form the basis and foundation of the modern technological society, given that they are used almost everywhere. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The technology has undergone significant changes, from their early days. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From rudimentary designs and inadequate materials, the world of PCBs has come a long way in evolving into the form that exists today. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In fact, one could say that the modern form is in fact something that is almost distinct from the early days of the technology. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of the many different forms that they have evolved into, one of the most important is that of ‘mulit-layered PCBs.’</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple words, they are the printed circuit boards, which are designed to have more than a single level in them, as it would be in the case of conventional designs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As the name would suggest, they come with multiple layers, all of which are stacked on top of one another. To be more specific, a multilayer PCB is one that has three or more conductive copper foil layers. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div><span><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-16/Multi-Layer PCB.jpg\" alt=\"Multi-Layer PCB.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several advantages when it comes to </span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Multilayer-PCBs\"><u><span class=\"15\">multi-layer PCBs</span></u></a><span>. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the most important ones around are given in the points below: </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1. Lightweight Construction</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the biggest advantages of multilayer PCBs is that they are lightweight in construction. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given that they have multiple layers of circuits on them, it is easier to compress large circuit designs onto a smaller area, without the need for any additional material as would be the case for regular PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This ‘compressed’ form allows for the manufacture of a lightweight circuitry, which works at a greater degree of efficiency, and at the same time using a lower amount of material than otherwise. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2. Smaller Sizes</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is related to the previous point, as well as one unto itself. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Since the structure of multilayer PCBs allow for large circuits to be ‘compressed’ onto a smaller area, one is able to integrate large designs onto smaller chips. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple words, it allows for the technology to get smaller, without any loss in efficiency or power. The end result is a PCB that is smaller in size with the power of much larger regular PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3. Higher Quality </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given that these PCBs have multiple layers on them, it becomes necessary to ensure a high degree of planning during the design and manufacturing stages. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is important so as to ensure that the circuits don’t fail later on, when they are put to actual use. There is a lot more going on per unit area in these circuits, in comparison to conventional ones, which makes it necessary to have a greater degree of quality than regular technology. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>What this means for multilayer PCBs in general, is that they tend to be of a higher quality than what would be the case for regular PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4. Better Durability </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another important advantage of multilayer PCBs is that they are generally more durable. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is a reason for this. It has to do with the way they are designed, as already mentioned. The PCBs are required to bear their own weight, as well as handle the heat and pressure used during the manufacturing processes to bind them together.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Furthermore, they have several layers of insulation between circuit layers which are bound using prepreg bonding agents and an assortment of various protective materials.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5. More Powerful </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Multilayer PCBs are designed with productivity in mind. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Due to the fact that they comprise of multiple layers of circuits on the same surface area, it becomes easier for one to process larger amounts of data and information on them than on regular PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This factor makes the multilayer PCBs a lot more powerful in comparison to regular PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6. A Single Connection Point </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This may not mean anything for the common man, but it is certainly something for those into electronics design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Multilayer PCBs come with a single connection point, which allows for simplicity of technology design. In addition to this, it also allows for one to shrink the size of the overall number of circuits and other designs required to keep any electronic entity functional. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7. Flexibility </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is not so much a given, but rather something which can occasionally be expected. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Many of the times, the materials used for the multilayer PCBs are designed using flexible materials, which in turn makes them flexible. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The main reason why this is done is for applications where there may be mild flexibility required on a regular basis. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It should be noted that although flexibility remains an option, the degree of it will reduce with the number of layers on the PCB. In general, the greater the number of layers on the board, the lower its flexibility is going to be. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To make a long story short, there is a chance that the PCBs that are multi-layered may be flexible in certain cases, albeit not all of them. If this is a characteristic feature required from the technology, it is something that has to be specified in advance, for it is not always a given. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>8. Cost Efficiency </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is another potential advantage when it comes to multilayer PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In general, the cost of manufacturing them will be higher in comparison to regular PCBs. At the same time however, the cost difference is offset by the fact that there are savings elsewhere. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the savings here include, among others, the decrease in the need for additional circuitry, the lowering manufacturing cost for the end user, the less amount of labor required for installing multiple circuits, the lower number of quality checks required, etc. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>All of these things add up in the end, to make the product cost efficient to the end user. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Last but not the least, it should be noted that the points listed out below are but some of the most important ones to consider, when it comes to the advantages of multi-level PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many other uses for this chemical compound than the ones mentioned above as well, which you can find out through additional and further research. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Advantages of Multi-Layer PCB', 'Multi-Layer PCB', ' Advantages of Multi-Layer PCB. ', 0, '2019-10-16 11:56:19', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (44, 'How_Can_I_Find_A_Good_PCB_Supplier_44', '2019-10-20 19:44:48', NULL, 42, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Introduction</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Printed circuit boards (PCBs) are the most basic component of all electrical appliances. You can find them in almost all devices and appliances in one way or another. Printed circuit boards are used to support the smooth flow of electricity in a device. They are used to electronically connect two or more components in a single or multiple devices. &nbsp;They basically consist of sheets and layers of cotton lamination. You can find single layer PCBs and multiple layered PCBs in the market. &nbsp;In addition to that you can find PCBs that are copper laminated on both sides and you can also find PCBs that are only laminated on the one side. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-20/003.jpg\" alt=\"003.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>How Can You Find Good PCB Supplier</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You must be wondering why anyone would need to find a PCB supplier. The answer is obvious if you run an electronic repair business but did you know that may individuals also buy printed circuit boards for DIY projects at home. &nbsp;Like all other things in the world, you have to perform extensive research before purchasing any printed circuit board. They are one of the most basic yet important component of any electrical device so it is very important to choose the best and high quality PCB for your products. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Things To Consider While Looking For A Good&nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/\" style=\"font-weight: bold;\">PCB Supplier</a></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You have to base your choice of PCB supplier on certain different factors. It can be based on your personal preferences but generally there are certain things that you have to consider no matter what. </span><span>Let’s take a look at some of the thing you have to keep in mind while looking for a good PCB supplier.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Check If The Supplier Offers Customized Printed Circuit Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Many people tend to look for printed circuit board manufactures who can offer customized PCB boards. You have to keep in mind that not all suppliers offer customized PCBs. If you are an inventor or you want to get a printed circuit board made that isn’t standardized then you will have to go to a supplier that offer customized printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Cost Of The Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There are hundreds and thousands of different PCB suppliers all over the world which means that you may find similar PCBs being sold at different prices at different stores. This is why we are putting so much emphasis on pre purchase research. You have to be very careful when you are dealing with electronics. A small short circuit may end up in to a big fire. Be wary of people who sell PCBs at a lower rate than the market price. What you should look for is cost effectiveness which does not mean that you have to buy a cheap PCB. It means that you need to buy a PCB that would give you more features and value than the money you have spent on it. &nbsp;Never compromise on quality even if it costs you more as a low cost PCB might not be as good in quality as an expensive one.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Ask If The Supplier Can Deliver In Time</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>If you are working on a DIY project at home then time might not be a problem however if you are running a business then you might need bulk order on a regular basis. You have to find a supplier that would be willing to deliver your order in time. You don’t want a supplier who isn’t reliable as that would affect your entire business supply chain. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Contact The Brands Directly</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It is very important that you contact the PCB suppliers directly. There are many brokers out in the market who take orders from you and pass your order on to different companies. There are two problems with this. The first one is that it increases your total cost and the second one is that you cannot be sure that you will be given quality product especially if your order is divided between different manufactures. This is why it is very important to contact the company directly. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Can The Supplier Manage The Order Quantity</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Not every supplier is working at a similar level. Some work on a small scale while others can manage several bulk orders at the same time. It is okay to work with small scale suppliers if you want a few boards however if you want PCBs for your business you might need a supplier who can manage relatively larger orders.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>How Impressive Is The Supplier’s Quality Assurance</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Quality assurance is very important for things like printed circuit boards. You have to be sure that the supplier can deliver quality products. For this, you should either look for suppliers that have already made a name for themselves in the market. If you are going with a local supplier or manufacturer then try to ask them questions regarding their quality assurance practices.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Study The Supply Chain</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This is very important especially if you are thinking about working with a supplier for longer period of time. Choosing a supplier that isn’t very keen on quality may result in thousands of dollars in loss for you. Try to study their supply chain. Look for the source of their raw materials. Sometimes companies tend to buy materials from cheap sources so that they can keep a huge profit margin for themselves. You should always be wary of such suppliers.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>These are just some of things you need to keep in mind when you head out to shop for printed circuit boards. At the end of the day, you are the one who is going to use it, so make sure that you are choosing the right supplier. You can select some features and qualities you want to find in the supplier and then prioritize them based on the project you are working on. This will help you find an ideal printed circuit board supplier for your project or business.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How Can I Find A Good PCB Supplier?', ' PCB Supplier', ' Steps to find a good pcb supplier. ', 0, '2019-10-21 17:09:33', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (45, 'Flexible_Printed_Circuit_Board_Application_Range_45', '2019-10-22 15:32:21', NULL, 43, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Introduction</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Printed Circuit Boards (PCB) are electronic circuits that support the flow of electricity through a device or an appliance. They are crucial for the functioning of items like mobile phones and laptops. This shows how important printed circuit boards really are. There are many different types of printed circuit boards based on their design, material and other similar features. &nbsp;Flexible printed </span><span>circuit board is one of them. It is one of the most used circuit boards in the world. In order to understand the application range of flexible printed circuit boards we should first try to understand what flexible circuit boards are.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>What Are Flexible Printed Circuit Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There are two major types of circuit boards. Rigid circuit boards and Flexible Printed Circuit Boards. When people normally talk about printed circuit boards, they are usually referring to rigid circuit boards. Flexible circuit boards are commonly known as flex circuits. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-22/1111-5.jpg\" alt=\"Flexible Printed Circuit Board Application Range\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>What Is The Application Range Of Flexible Printed Circuit Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Flexible printed circuit boards are used in variety of different electronic devices. Traditionally people preferred the rigid circuit boards however with time the flexible circuit boards are also gaining a lot of prominence. Flex circuits are being incorporated into many modern devices.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It is important to know that many technologies that were previously thought to only work with rigid circuit boards can also work with the help of flexible printed circuit boards. Flexible PCBs are relatively newer as compared to rigid circuit boards but with increasing awareness it is expected that engineers will start using flex circuits to a comparatively greater extent.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>From something as small as a calculator to larger objects like automobiles, flex circuits are used in almost all industries. Let’s take a look at some applications of flexible printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The application of flexible printed circuit boards can be categorized into two sub categories.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Dynamic Application</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Flex To Install </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Flex To Install</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Flex to install applications are those where the circuit is form during the assembly. This is the most commonly used application of flex circuits. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Dynamic Application</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>As clear from the name the dynamic applications of flex circuits means the use of flexible printed circuit boards in appliances that take full advantage of the dynamic abilities of the flex circuit. Common example of this can be the computer hard disk drive.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Applications Of Flexible Printed Circuit Boards </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>With passing time engineers and electrician are becoming more aware of the benefits and use of </span></p><p><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Flexible-PCBs\">flexible printed circuit boards</a>.</b> The range of use of these circuits is endless. From small telephones to large automobiles, flexible circuits can be used in almost all common products of daily use. Let’s take a look at few applications of flexible circuits.</p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Computer Hard Drives</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>As explained earlier, computer hard drives consist of flexible printed circuit boards. They are a complex item and require many different flexing operations throughout their life. This means that computer hard drives require a circuit that works in a very dynamic way. The flexible printed circuit boards are perfect for this type of application. In addition to the computer hard drives , flex circuits are also used in other parts of the computer as well including the CPU and even things like keyboards and LCDs. &nbsp;When we talk about keyboards, we can’t go ahead without mentioning that type writers were one of the first devices to use flex circuits however with increasing awareness flex circuit have become advanced and more widely available.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Telecommunication Sector</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The application of flex circuits in telecommunication can be seen from old and big fax machines to new and slim smart phones. Out of all telecommunication devices, the mobile phone can be seen as one device that is highly dependent on flex circuits. Without flex circuits you wouldn’t have any iphones or android smart phones. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Printers</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>From computer hard drives to printer. Printers also use flexible printed circuit boards to function. The flexible circuits work best when you have to connect two different components where one component is the functioning part and the other one is like the control module. Printers work on this principle thus using a flexible printed circuit boards makes sense.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Aeronautics And Aviation</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Did you know that an airplane has around 100 KM of wiring in it? Other flying objects like helicopters and small choppers also boast a complex wiring and electronics system. &nbsp;Most of this wiring and electronic systems are supported by flex circuits. The American aviation is considered as the pioneer for introducing the combination of rigid and flex circuit boards. However the flexible printed circuit boards without the combination with rigid PCBs are gaining a lot of popularity amongst aeronautical engineers. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Automobiles</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>If you thought flexible printed circuit boards only have use in small electronic devices then you’re wrong. Flexible printed circuit boards are used excessively in automobiles. &nbsp;These days’ flexible circuit boards are produced in large quantities just for the automobile industry. From the head lights to the dashboard and all other wiring and electrical components throughout the car, all use a combination of rigid and flexible printed circuit boards. However the use of flexible circuit boards in automobile has vastly increased in the last few years. It is believed that the use of flexible circuits in automobiles has made the driving experience less complex. It has also helped in improving the assembly of the vehicle by improving reliability and reducing issues in the assembly. A study has suggested that an upward trend can be seen in the application of flex circuits in the automobile industry. This means that in the coming years, more flex circuits will be used in the automobile industry as compared to rigid circuit boards. This trend can also be judged by the fact that the automobile industry is moving towards smart cars and smart technology is highly dependent on flex circuits.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There are just some of the main applications of flexible circuit boards. Flex circuits have hundreds of other applications as well. With time, flexible circuit boards have gained a lot of popularity and with increased awareness; their popularity trend is expected to keep on growing.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', NULL, 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Flexible Printed Circuit Board Application Range', 'Flexible Printed Circuit Board, Flexible PCB', ' Flexible Printed Circuit Board Application Range ', 0, '2019-10-22 15:35:06', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (46, 'How_Different_Technologies_Affect_the_PCB_Cost_46', '2019-10-24 09:26:30', NULL, 25, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCB is an acronym which stands for ‘printed circuit board’. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is a very common piece of hardware used in a variety of technologies today, and indeed, a very important one. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is much that can be said about PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of them all, one issue that stands out above all else, is with regard to the cost factor of the PCBs and the way in which different technologies affect it. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something very important to manufacturers as well as end users, as the cost savings on these advancements and changes can be immense. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many ways in which different technologies affect the cost of PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the most important ones are listed in the points below: </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><br></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-24/Different Technologies Affect the PCB Cost.jpg\" alt=\"Different Technologies Affect the PCB Cost.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1. The Rise of Automation</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing in the world of manufacturing that is transforming industry, it is automation. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin with, automation is the process by which human labor is replaced with the use of robots and other machinery. The reasons for this are many, ranging from simply cost-cutting initiatives to enhanced productivity and more. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the best examples of this can be seen in the case of robotics in factories, which are today almost entirely automated. The robotics used in the factories is advanced to the point, where there is almost no need for human labor. The manufacturing process is completely streamlined from the beginning to the end, to use almost no human inputs in almost all cases. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This process of automation has allowed for a higher degree of productivity in the case of PCB manufacture as well, allowing for the prices to fall considerably. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2. The Rise of A.I. </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A.I. is an acronym for ‘artificial intelligence’. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many definitions to what A.I. is, but in simple terms, it can be thought of as a form of machine intelligence, which in many ways mimics the same human thought processes in a computerized form. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although the use of A.I. has been limited to a large extent, it has started to make inroads into the world of PCB manufacturing, which has cut the need for human labor to a large extent. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has once again started to play a major role in reducing the cost of manufacturing the final product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3. General Productivity Improvements in Technology </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing that has become an industry standard in a way, is that of improved efficiency in the manufacturing processes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The exact way, in which these efficiencies come about certainly vary, ranging from better utilization of energy and raw materials, to the speed at which they process the many inputs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>All of these things help to raise efficiency and thereby lower cost, which in turn helps to reduce the price of the average PCB in the marketplace. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4. The Choice of Material </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The choice of the material will have a major impact on the final cost of the PCB. The material of choice for the average PCB has been that of FRA4 laminates, but there are newer materials coming into use in the industry, which are promising in terms of reducing the cost. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of the many such materials that are under consideration, some of them include those which are in use in the aerospace and fuel industries, with others in the lineup as well.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>&nbsp;</span></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5. Size of the PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Advancements of the PCBs have resulted in the ‘shrinking’ of the size of the average chip, allowing for a higher degree of efficiency. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something that has to do with the way in which more circuitry and other assemblies can be integrated on the same surface, which allows for increased efficiency and productivity. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the best examples of this can be found in the ‘multi-layer’ PCBs, where several different layers of circuits are stacked on top of each other, for the purpose of creating a compact and efficient circuit. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6. Hole Sizes </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To the average person, a hole in a PCB doesn’t mean much. But for those in the industry, it holds a very important position.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A hole in a PCB is exactly what it sounds like; a ‘hole’ in the board, which allows for the design of the PCB and its circuits. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to holes, their sizes can play a major role in the way that the PCB costs are influenced. Two different factors will play an influential role in the determining of PCB prices. For one thing, the size of the holes will determine the kind of technology that is required, with smaller holes requiring finer drills to do the job. Another important factor is the number of holes, as the greater the number of holes, the greater will be the cost of the final product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It should be noted that the above two factors can be greatly nullified in terms of their effect on the final price, when the PCBs are manufactured in large numbers, i.e. mass produced. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7. Minimum Trace and Space </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This might sound like a complex concept, but it isn’t. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple words, it is the distance that exists between the many different elements of the circuit. This is important because the distance affects other things like efficiency, the lifespan of the chip, susceptibility to overheating and more. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is therefore an important factor with regard to the way in which the cost of the final PCB is affected and influenced. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>8. Thickness and Aspect Ratio </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has everything to do with the physical size and dimensions of the PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Several things which influence the prices here include the length, width, thickness, etc. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The term aspect ratio is related to the previous point, with reference to the ‘ratio’ in which the different attributes are selected to manufacture the finished product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>9. Custom Designs </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is not always that the standard PCB from the market shelf can be used for a given purpose. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In many cases, there will be the need for PCBs that are specifically designed to fulfill a certain criterion or goal, which will raise the cost of the final product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, the cost of PCBs can vary drastically, on the basis of the kind of technology used, as well as a host of other factors. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>But in general, it should be known that the means of production deployed for the manufacturing process, plays a key role in the way PCBs are produced, and something which will continue to vary well into the distant future.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><br></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you want to learn more about PCB history, you can check it out&nbsp;</span><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/blog/PCB_History_and_Development_41.html\">here</a>.</b><span><br>.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>   ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How Different Technologies Affect the PCB Cost', 'PCB Cost', ' Different ways can affect the cost of PCB in many ways, we will explain in detail below. ', 0, '2019-10-24 09:35:52', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (47, 'How_to_choose_different_types_of_printed_circuit_boards_47', '2019-10-25 09:36:42', NULL, 29, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Consideration of the PCB </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>IntroCB or the printed circuit board is the traditional name that is used for the bare board. This is used for the supply of the layout data. It is used to mount the component that is required on the conductive pathways. PCB provides mechanical support along with an electrical connection for the components on the conductive pathway or track. It is etched from the copper sheet that is laminated onto one non-conductive substrate.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>A printed circuit board or the PCB can be considered as more beneficial in comparison to the older ways that were used for building the electronics. Considering the past of electronics, large wires were used for the connection. Similarly, things were placed anywhere they could be fitted. The approach of the printed circuit board is more effective, modernized, and less messy. Through the PCBs, the components are mounted with the non-conductive board. It also uses the small pathways called the traces to connect. They are usually designed through a computer. In this way, the printed circuit boards fit many components in a small amount of space. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-25/FPC-13.jpg\" alt=\"How to choose different types of printed circuit boards\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Types of printed circuit board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There are different types of printed circuit boards according to their characteristics. The design differs due to the copper rails that connect the various components. Other than that, the special tools that are required in the PCBs add to the special aspects. Here is the information that can help you in understanding the various types.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Single-sided PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This least complicated type of PCB uses only one layer of the substrate that acts as the base material. This one layer is filled with a thin and proper layer of metal because copper is an extremely efficient electricity conductor. There is another solder mask that increases the efficiency of this PCB. The additional silkscreen coat results in the complete look of the board. This one works effectively with simple electric items and costs extremely less. The electronic components are located on the single side of the board and don\'t support all electricity items. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Double-sided PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Double-sided PCBs are commonly used due to high usage properties. The two bases have the metal layers that connect to both sides. The components are spread evenly along with the holes on the whole board that makes things easier. Both the technology of surface mount and through-hole can be used. Leads which are tiny wear slides through the hole to go to the other side. Numerous small leads are soldered on in this type. It helps in increasing the functionality and efficiency of the board. However, it can be dangerous to handle in certain cases. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span><p><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/blog/Advantages_of_Multi-Layer_PCB_43.html\">Multilayer PCBs</a></p></span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The multilayer PCBs utilizes the latest technology in the double-sided boards. More than two layers of the substrate are used on the board in the multilayer PCBs. The insulating material is present on each layer. It uses the same technology of the double-sided board, however, it helps in saving more space. The addition of layers can take place in this type of PCB. They are considered technical and require professionalism. In case of the inability of understanding the technicality, it can make the whole board useless. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Rigid PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Apart from the layers and the side, the PCBs differ on other bases too. Other than the number of layers, the rigid PCBs differ based on varying the rigidness. This type of PCB is based on the usage of the solid substrate material. This substrate material is inflexible and strong. For this type of PCBs, the usage of fiberglass is highly recommended. It can be considered as it prevents the chances of damages and bending of the board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span><p><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Flexible-PCBs\">Flex PCBs</a></p> </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Flex PCBs refers to the flexibility like this type of printed circuit board. This type of PCB uses flexible plastic that is layered on the base. The usage of flexible plastic as the substrate material allows fixing in various shapes. They are highly recommended due to the usage of all the latest equipment. Other than that, they are extremely lightweight. The board can also be bent and it remains safe in all the conditions. However, it is extremely costly in comparison to the other types. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span><p><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Rigid-Flex-PCBs\">Rigid-flex PCBs</a></p></span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The last type of PCBs called the rigid-flex PCB is both rigid and flexible at the same time. The main concept behind the usage of these boards is that it can be used with an item that requires strong board assistance. The circuit board is rigid, however, it gets connected on to a single layer of the flex circuit board. This type of PCB can address the majority of the requirements and can be considered useful. However, they are extremely complex to make. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Factors to be considered </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Before selecting any particular type of circuit board, it is important to consider your requirements. Here are some of the factors that should be considered while choosing the PCBs </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Consider</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><b><span>the</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><b><span>material</span></b><span>: It is important to evaluate the material that is going to be used in designing the PCB. Buy the material before working on the PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Instrument</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><b><span>requirement</span></b><span>: Instrument plays a vital role in the designing and functionality of the PCB. Therefore, consider the instrument. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Usage</span></b><span>: Most importantly, consider where you are going to use the PCB. Does the usage require flexibility, rigidness, or both? Is the usage simple or more technical in nature? Consider all these aspects and you will be able to find the right PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Budget</span></b><span>: Evaluate the price of the various types and components associated with them. Choose the one that goes well with your budget. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Circuit</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><b><span>board</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><b><span>requirement</span></b><span>: Consider the need for the power and strength that is needed for the circuit board. Consider all the designing rules in your mind while building the board. Do not forget any element. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Lastly, recheck all the considerable factors. In this way, you will be able to attain the right printed circuit board among the six types that are compatible with your needs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to choose different types of printed circuit boards', 'printed circuit boards. pcb', 'Introduction to different types of PCB', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (48, '10_Mistakes_You_Should_Avoid_about_the_PCB_48', '2019-10-26 16:13:20', NULL, 30, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Whether you are a pro at PCB design or just an amateur still trying to figure out your way around the process, mistakes are always bound to happen at some point. Nevertheless, it does not take away the fact that taking missteps in the design process can be a real nuisance especially if you only get to realize later of the mistake that you’ve done.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>mistakes are to breeze through the de&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Most mistakes people commit when designing PCB often are little ones that often has to do with not paying much attention to the little details. It helps when you are well aware of what these common sign process.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-26/330528-1403121G91312.jpg\" alt=\"330528-1403121G91312.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1. No proper planning</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you want to make sure that your PCB design process will be a success, spend enough time envisioning how you will go through the whole thing. PCB designers today can take advantage of the presence of easy-to-use yet powerful software packages for design automation, which would immensely help the proves. Do your homework and make sure that you have gathered everything that you need ahead of time so once you start getting the work done, there won’t be unnecessary interruptions and pauses.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2. Using the wrong tools</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Every design software usually comes with numerous tools that will help you design PCB. See to it that the one you are using is appropriate for your needs. The wrong tool will not only cause you to make mistakes in designing the board, it will slow you down unnecessarily too. You’ll likely experience manufacturing problems too with the wrong tools at hand. So, get it right the first time.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3. Bad layout techniques</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCB boards often come with restrictive sizes or shapes, which requires you to use more imagination on how to get the layout pat-down.</span><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b><span>However, even those designers that have been doing this for a long can still come up with a layout that just does not work. In most cases, this can be due to improper placement of components or connections that fail.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To avoid this mistake, focus first on the design and do what you can to improve it. Be on the lookout for techniques that may possibly lead to component failure. Your experience in the design process can also help especially when you are trying to work your way around a new or unfamiliar layout.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4. Not backing up your work</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>During any PCB design process, you will be using a variety of data to come up with even more complex designs. While most PCB design software are created to ensure high flexibility and speed during the design process, it is also a fact that data and packages might get easily lose if you are not able to properly save them. The last thing you want is to make a repeat of a day’s work or more. Saving your packages regularly and creating various saving points is key towards ensuring that you will never have to deal with loss of data.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5. Wrong footprints</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is common for PCB design software to have libraries of component software. This means that you won’t have to spend a lot of time creating your own solder marks, package, silkscreen and footprint from a variety of scratch libraries that may even have errors on them. Always take the time to check your footprint and make sure that every pinout and component is correct especially if you have modified the footprint. Taking even just a few minutes to pay close attention to the footprint you are using can save you from the inconvenience of having to redo thing simply because you picked the wrong one.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6. Incorrect part substitution</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Part substitution is a crucial part of every PCB design. However, it can be the reason why yours fail too if you are not paying close attention to the substitution you are making. Selecting components outside of their acceptable range can often lead to component oscillation, which can then cause errors. Make sure to get the component datasheet updated every time you introduce a new equipment or a new replacement to avoid this.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7. Incorrect application of the solder</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The soldermask is a crucial aspect of a component footprint. However, applying too much solder can leave some of the pins unconnected in the process. Carefully applying the soldermask is important especially when using a stencil or a solder paste, as soldermasks with openings can lead to excess solder flowing to the rest of the board if the hole is large enough. It is always advisable to use modified soldermasks with 50% coverage especially in areas with high QEN and power.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>8. Not testing early prototypes</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Prototype boards are useful for proving that the PCB design works to its original specifications. Prototype testing is essential to validate the quality and functionality and the PCB and its performance. This is crucial before giving the green light for mass production. Make sure that there is a clear objective and robust test plan when conducting these tests to ensure their effectiveness.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>9. Lack of communication-</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Always make sure to keep in touch with the rest of your team especially when working in professional PCB design. A whole range of problems can be avoided when you keep an open line among each other so any concern from changes to the design to changes in deadlines will be properly communicated to everyone involved.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>10. Not holding code design reviews</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is easy to think that you are just wasting precious time on code design reviews. However, becoming a one-man island and not referring to other people in your team to get the design reviewed is one of the most common mistakes people commit about PCB. It is always easy to think that the design you are working on is flawless. It is exactly one of the reasons why it is easy to overlook details and the little things that might turn into bigger problems later. Having somebody less intimate with the work you are doing may be most helpful at spotting possible issues and valuable insights.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Being well aware of these common PCB design mistakes is one way of ensuring that you’ll never have to lose time redoing things. This is especially true if you are working against a deadline. You’ll be better at designing PCBs moving forward when you know which things to avoid and which things to incorporate in your process.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, '10 Mistakes You Should Avoid about the PCB', 'PCB', 'Whether you are a pro at PCB design or just an amateur still trying to figure out your way around the process, mistakes are always bound to happen at some point.', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (49, 'How_to_Check_a_Printed_Circuit_Board_49', '2019-10-30 15:16:21', NULL, 24, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Technology is something that we’ve been using for a very long time.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It powers our lives by powering the world. Regardless of whom you are or what you do, technology is influencing your life in some way. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of the many things that enable the technological advancements that have taken place, one which has become rather commonplace is that of the common printed circuit boards or PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As simple as they may seem, they are backbone of the modern technological era, given how they’ve made their presence felt in just about every single possible application. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Indeed, one could say that the present state of technological development couldn’t be achieved if it wasn’t for PCBs.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to manufacturing of these&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com\">PCB</a><span>s or for that matter anything else, quality control is of utmost importance. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As with any other piece of technology, it is important to know that it works as intended. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is where the many techniques to check and evaluate come into picture. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to the testing of the printed circuit board quality, there are a few strategies that are used for the same. Details of the same have been mentioned in the points below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-10-30/How to Check a Printed Circuit Board.jpg\" alt=\"How to Check a Printed Circuit Board.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Basic Design Inspection </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something that can be done with the naked eye, and doesn’t require the use of complex devices of any kind. In some cases however, some general lighting and a magnifying glass. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A general inspection of the printed circuit board is usually more than enough to know if there are any problems in it, whether it is major or minor. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the typical issues that may be found include, but are not limited to, cracks, irregular surfaces, incomplete circuitry, loose components (such as resistors, capacitors, diodes, etc), peeling layers of insulation or protective material, etc. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These are rather easy to spot with some basic inspection. At the same time however, the same may not be apparent in case the damage is fine, in which case a magnifying glass can prove to be of good use. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Physical Inspection </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In some cases, the printed circuit board may ‘appear’ to be normal, but have underlying issues. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many ways in which these problems manifest, but the most common one is by heat. It is because these damages typically result in the overheating of the components, which then discharge the heat around them.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;All that one needs to know in order to determine whether this happens to be the case, is to touch the surface of the PCBs, typically that of components such as resistors and capacitors. The presence of heated components is an indication that there may be damages lurking in them and which requires the same to be removed and replaced. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Do note that although this is a great way to detect any potential flaws in the printed circuit board, it is not a very safe one. It is advisable to only limit it to those devices which use a low amount of electricity. Additionally, one may use a thermographic camera or a similar device for the same purpose, although this may prove to be rather expensive. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The point here is to find out problematic components by detecting the heat they give of, without getting an electric shock of any kind. Also, given that the components may be damaged, the potential for an electric shock is all the greater. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Test the Capacitors</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This step applies to any printed circuit boards which have capacitors as part of their design architecture. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A capacitor can be defined as a component which allows for alternating current to pass through it. This is something that is rather common in many of the printed circuit boards around. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The way to test a capacitor is to discharge it by touching its leads together. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once this is done, they are to be tested with a voltmeter, with the resistance at its highest possible setting. The capacitor is to be probed with the power off and then again with the power back on; should the meter reading be zero, it is an indication that there are issues with the capacitor.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Test the Resistance Points </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Resistors are small components which control the flow of current through a printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To test whether the resistors are functioning as intended, one needs to begin by disconnecting any power supply that is connected to the circuit. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Turning on the power, a volt meter is to be placed on the circuit directly at the first resistor. This can be done by \'tracing\' the circuit path. One will need to check whether there is any voltage flowing through the circuit, which will be indicated by a reading in the volt meter; a reading of zero is an indication that there are issues with the resistors. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Typically, your average printed circuit board will comprise of several different resistors, spread out across the board. This means that one will have to follow the above step for all of the resistors that exist on the circuit board in the exact same way. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Checking the Other Components </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If in case one is checking a printed circuit board for damages, there is every chance that the real problem may not be with the circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On the contrary, the issue might actually have more to do with the other components in the device or gadget. In order to rule out the possibility that there is an issue with these other components of the device, it would be necessary to check them as well, in addition to that of the printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;This may seem like a rather time-consuming activity, but it is something which is absolutely necessary, if one wishes to find out the root cause of the issue on hand. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Last but not the least, it should be added that there are several other details as well, when it comes to checking the functioning of a printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The above are but some of the most important and indeed, standard ways in which the same is done across the industry level. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Depending on the needs and requirements, there is a chance that the same will vary in some cases. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to Check a Printed Circuit Board', 'Printed Circuit Board', 'How to Check a Printed Circuit Board', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (50, 'How_printed_circuit_boards_work_50', '2019-11-04 17:07:39', NULL, 23, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Our life is connected to electricity in so many ways. The reason for that is because we rely on electric power to recharge our phones, our laptops, and almost all of our home appliances need electric power to run. All electronic devices that we use have a fundamental piece in them that is called a printed circuit board or PCB. It is something on which basic electrical wiring is done. In the past, people used to do point to point wiring which resulted in frequent failures and caused a short circuit when wires were aged, messy, and cracked. But then there were advancements in the field of electronics and came wire wrappings which led to printed circuit boards (PCB). Wire wrapping involved a small gauge wire that was wrapped around a post at each connection point by creating a gas-tight connection. This type of wire wrapping was durable and easily changeable. Most of the electronic devices reduced their components by using silicon and integrated circuits instead of relays and vacuum tubes. Eventually, it led to small-sized electronic devices and ultimately it reduced the manufacturing cost of electronic goods as well. Around that time, the Printed Circuit Board was invented. Here, we are going to discuss how does a printed circuit board works. Let’s have a detailed look:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-04/2318.jpg_wh300.jpg\" alt=\"2318.jpg_wh300.jpg\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Printed circuit board formation</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The printed circuit board has basically 3 or 4 layers. The bottom layer is usually non-conductive and the middle layer is made with copper metal. This layer is laminated on the non-conductive layer with heat and adhesive. The top layer is called a solder mask. This layer gives the PCB its green color. This layer protects and insulates the copper traces and made it possible for the connections to be visible. Then silkscreen is used to mention the letter and number on it. &nbsp;Now a day electric circuits are designed on computers and then printed in factories. They use etch-resistant ink lines along the metal design to cover the conductive path. Once the various points connect together through soldering, they make a path between components to run power in a proper circuit. After testing, thousands of electronic circuits are manufactured in a factory. The printed circuit boards are relatively small so they can be fitted in any electronic device. Also, each device could have a different design of PCB, but the basic formation is the same.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Basic components of printed circuit board and their functions</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>To function properly, different components on printed circuit board work together so that the electrical device would run on electrical power. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The major components on any printed circuit board include the following:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>IC (Integrated Circuit):</span></b><span>&nbsp;A special and considerably big sized chip is called an integrated circuit (IC). This one contains many mini circuits and components that help perform a specific function. It is like the head office of the whole PCB where the important stuff happens.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Traces:</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><span>On any PCB, you will notice that a few lines are connecting various components. These are copper metal lines which are called traces and the whole PCB chip is like a base for the entire electronic function that runs in an electrical device. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>LED (Light Emitting Diode):</span></b><span>&nbsp;It is a small light on a circuit board that provides a visual signal that electricity is passing through here. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Vias:</span></b><span>&nbsp;There are silver holes on every PCB, these holes managed to create a three-dimensional electronic circuit from one side of PCB to another side.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Resistor:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Resistors manage the flow of electrical current by providing necessary resistance when the device is powered with electricity. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Capacitor: </span></b><span>These are battery-like components that store electricity and when in need it can quickly release or hold an electrical charge.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Diode:</span></b><span>&nbsp;They control electricity flow by forcing it to flow in one direction.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Transistor:</span></b><span>&nbsp;It is a kind of switch that is controlled by electrical signals. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Silkscreens: </span></b><span>If you look closely at any PCB, you will notice some kind of letters and numbers printed on it. These are called silkscreens. They help electrical engineers to navigate the pattern and its location.</span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Each of these components helps the PCB to function properly. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>How does a printed circuit board work?</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>An electrical circuit on a PCB is a loop of copper material in which electricity can run along. When this loop is closed, electricity can flow uninterrupted from any power source such as a battery or direct electric power. It will keep flowing and let the device run its function. At that time, the flow of electricity will be controlled by the components on PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It is not just the electrical current that is routed through the PCB, but there are a variety of tasks like computing, communications and data transfer all happening in a PCB through the interconnections of several components on a PCB. It insulates the safe amount of power within the electronic device and integrates the device in a compact space. The PCBs can be made with less expensive materials and are prone to last longer that is why they tend to be the engineer’s top choice while creating any new machinery. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Smart functions of printed circuit board</span></b><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Today, we could see PCB in every device. It can be found in nearly every type of electronic device in our home that we use on a daily basis. Let it be your shaving machine, your blender, your vacuum cleaner, or your smart home security system, there is some sort of PCB in every one of them. But this is not where it ends. Its functions have gone above and beyond just the electronic devices. The PCBs have been now used in various smart devices like watches, mobile phones, laptops, delivery drones, hearing implants, and prosthetic limbs. The modern engineers have modified the uses of PCB to their needs. The PCB circuit connections provide a complex yet miniature structure to route electricity in a more effective and small way in every one of these smart devices. This is not the end, but a mere possibility of more technical and mechanical advancement in the mechanical and electronic field. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You may also be interested in the&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/blog/PCB_History_and_Development_41.html\">history and development of pcb</a><span>, you can click to view.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p> ', NULL, 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How printed circuit boards work', 'printed circuit boards', '   How printed circuit boards work ', 0, '2019-11-04 17:19:15', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (51, 'What_Are_Printed_Circuit_Board_Made_Of_51', '2019-11-08 09:21:05', NULL, 19, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit boards are a standard feature of technology today. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Found in just about every single piece of electronic gizmo that one comes across, this is one piece of technology that has a universal nature unlike anything else. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as they have become ‘common place’, there is a certain ‘curiosity’ about them which many people have. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is not so much about the way they function, but rather what they are made of. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is a good reason for this. Printed circuit boards are unlike anything in the world, when it comes to electronics. With their distinct shapes, designs and coloration, it is probably the first thing that would catch the eye of anyone disassembling a piece of electronic. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This curiosity is certainly understandable. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given that humans are a ‘curious’ species by nature, it is only to be expected. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With regard to the actual components of a printed circuit board, it would be interesting to note that the technology has been fairly ‘standardized’. In other words, its construction in standard industry practices is to a large extent the same all over the world, in terms of material, design, techniques and other related aspects. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to the construction of printed circuit boards, it can be said the the technology has undergone a tremendous amount of evolution to reach the present form. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Over the years, many practices have become common place, along with the usage of several different materials that are used in the construction of your average printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Details of the same are given in the points below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-08/pcb.jpg\" alt=\"pcb.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) The Main Board </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The main board forms the backbone of the modern PCB design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is the foundation on which all of the other circuits are placed. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many different materials that have found them being used for the main board’s construction. These included everything from plastics and wood to other materials. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As time progressed, it was decided that the material of choice was standardized in favor of resins. Today, there are a wide range of resins used by the industry, the two most common being that of ‘fiberglass’ epoxy and the ‘paper reinforced phenolic’ resin. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The latter is the cheaper one to manufacture, which makes it very useful for commercial electronics. The former on the other hand, is relatively expensive but tends to be more stable, which is why it is used in general for heavy duty applications. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) The Circuitry </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The Board is one part of the equation.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;What makes the printed circuit board a ‘circuit’ at the end of the day are the many circuits that exist on its surface, in one form or another. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The standard industry practice for the creation of circuits is the use of copper foil, which is bonded to the surface of the boards. This holds true for both kinds of boards, i.e. whether the same is made using fiberglass epoxy resin or that of paper reinforced phenolic resin. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The way that the circuitry is added to the surface will depend on the industry, and the purpose that the board is used for. There are currently two ways in which the circuitry is added; plating and etching. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The term ‘plating’ refers to the ‘deposition’ process in which a thin layer of metal is deposited on the surface along a predetermined path, decided in advance during the design stage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The second process of etching is one in which a metal path is etched with the help of suitable tools, thereby creating the circuit required. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It should be added that the metal of choice is not always copper, although it has become an industry standard. Depending on the need and requirement, other metals or alloys may be used as well. In many cases, such as that of fine electronics and smart phones, the metal of choice is not copper but rather silver or gold. In fact, in a lot of these modern electronic gadgets, there is actually more gold per ton of the finished product, than there is gold in gold ore. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) The Protective Layer </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The next important component of printed circuit boards is a protective layer, typically made from either a metal or metal alloy. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The practice became standard in the industry in an effort to prevent the oxidation of the circuitry. This was especially important in the case of printed circuit boards, as they were essentially exposed metal surfaces as opposed to metal wires, which had an insulating layer which doubled up as a form of protection against corrosion. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many different materials used for this protective layer. In general, the most common material of choice is zinc, as it is both affordable as well as offers a high degree of resistance against corrosion. In other cases, alloys are used, typically those of tin and lead. The exact material of choice will vary based on industry and application requirements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These days, there has been a trend to add another layer of protection on top of the protective one, which is that of water-proofing materials, often consisting of polymers. Although this is not yet standard practice, they have become rather common in the manufacture of devices such as smart phones in an effort to make them ‘water resistant’ or ‘water proof’. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Other Additions &amp; Components </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to the above, there are other additions and components that are used in printed circuit boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These are not always a given, with certain exceptions. They are usually very application specific, meaning that the exact nature of the component, as well as the ways in which it is used, will vary. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several different components that come under this category. Some of the most common ones here include, but are not limited to, resistors, diodes, capacitors, transistors, integrated circuit chips and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to add is that these components are often used in ‘combination’ with each other, meaning that you can usually find several of them together. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To sum up, the modern printed circuit board employs the use of a wide range of materials, along with others which may be proprietary trade secrets. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>But as a whole, the materials used in their construction are fairly standard, and have been for a very long time. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And until a revolutionary new material or set of materials come about, vastly superior to the ones used today, it can be expected that this will not change in any way. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>   ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'What Are Printed Circuit Board Made Of', 'Printed Circuit Board Made', ' Printed circuit boards are a standard feature of technology today.\n\nFound in just about every single piece of electronic gizmo that one comes across, this is one piece of technology tat has a universal nature unlike anything else. ', 0, '2019-11-08 10:08:01', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (52, 'Printed_Circuit_Board_Design_52', '2019-11-11 14:25:34', NULL, 23, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to printed circuit boards, there is a lot that one can say. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Simple as they seem, they are by far one of the most ingenious and advanced pieces of scientific advancements of the present times.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Created largely as an alternative to do away with bulky wire configurations, one can find printed circuit boards in a wide range of applications, from the simple to the complex. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One could in fact say that the development of printed circuit boards played a major role in the advancement of modern electronics, among other things. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Coming to the actual functioning of these boards, it is not often clear as to their function. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While the average engineer may have an idea of their function, the common man is often in the dark as to their design and overall structure. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The details on the exact design of printed circuit boards are explained in the points given below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-11/83a0f93414d774c34179971c146f40b8.jpg\" alt=\"83a0f93414d774c34179971c146f40b8.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1. The Basic Design Never Changed </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing that is to be kept in mind, this would be it. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As ‘advanced’ as the boards are, the basic design of the circuits never really changed, as some may think. On the contrary, what happened was that the way the circuit boards worked was just made ‘more efficient’. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In other words, the circuits will still carry electricity and data the same way that they would in the case of wires, albeit in a manner that was more efficient and that’s it. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) The Various Levels of a Printed Circuit Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The average circuit board, without exception, is made up of several different layers. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is an industry standard, without any exceptions to a large extent. It is an industry-wide standard practice, and which is something that can be observed in almost any printed circuit board that one comes across. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin with, there is the main board, which acts as a foundation on which the entire circuit architecture is built. The board is typically made out of epoxy resins. This forms the primary layer of the printed circuit boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The resin boards in turn, have the circuits placed on their surface, using one of two ways; etching and plating. In the case of ‘etching’, a metal circuit is ‘etched’ from a metal foil bonded on the surface of the board. In case the same is ‘plated’, a thin layer of metal is deposited on the board along a path to create the necessary circuit. This makes the second layer of the printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The third layer comprises of the protective layers that are used to ensure that the board lasts for a long enough period of time. These include everything from the deposition of metals or alloys, to the application of waterproofing materials. This forms the final layer of the&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-layout\"><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\">printed circuit board design</font></b></a><span><br>. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to the above, there may also be the addition of components such as diodes, resistors, integrated circuits and so on, as per the requirements and needs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) The Overall Design </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something that has to do more with the overall design of the device or electronic than the actual printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A printed circuit board is really just another component in a much larger device, such as a household electronic or Smartphone. This means that the design of the printed circuit board, is something that must seamlessly fit into the larger design of the gadget that it was designed for. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This factor puts certain restrictions on the size of the circuit, and the kind of designs that can be used for the purpose. For example, larger electronics allow for the use of larger printed circuit boards than normal. But in case of small handheld electronics, there is a limit to the amount of space available, which necessitates the need for ‘multi-layered’ boards, which has multiple layers of circuits integrated into a single chip. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Likewise, there are plenty of other such constraints that exist on the final design of the printed circuit board as well, which determine how it is to be designed.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) The Manufacturing Plant </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing very unique about the way printed circuit boards are manufactured, it would be their environment. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as their architecture may be rather easy and simple to understand, the way to go about doing it is not really the case. The fact is that the manufacture of these printed circuit boards requires a very high amount of manufacturing efficiency and a very clean environment, which calls for high facility standards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;Today, printed circuit boards are typically manufactured in what are called ‘clean rooms’. They are called ‘clean rooms’ because they are, as the name would suggest, exceptionally clean, in terms of having little to no dust as well as microbes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This high degree of cleanliness and sterility is required, as even the smallest impurity can lead to imperfections in the final design of the circuits. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to add here is that in addition to the facility, there are also similar requirements on part of the workers at the plant. People are often required to wear special and protective clothing, as well as follow high standards for sanitation and cleanliness, in order to work at the plant. In addition to this, it is to be added that the facilities where these chips are manufactured, usually have access controlled production areas, which carefully regulated and monitor who is allowed in and out of the place. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is interesting to note that these are often the same standards that are also used in the manufacture of silicon chips, and other related technologies, such as that of microprocessors used in smart phones and desktops. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, the construction of printed circuit boards has undergone a dramatic change from their early days. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From the materials used to the manufacturing processes, all of them have witnessed a vast degree of transformation. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The details of the basic design, as laid out above, are but the standard practiced today in a vast majority of printed circuit board companies around the world. The exact details may certainly vary, depending on the company one is referring to, and the manufacturing process being deployed for the same.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', NULL, 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Printed Circuit Board Design', 'Printed Circuit Board Design, PCB Design', ' The details on the exact design of printed circuit boards are explained in the points given below.  ', 0, '2019-11-11 14:58:12', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (53, 'The_Difference_Between_Rigid_PCB_and_Flexible_PCB_53', '2019-11-12 14:43:18', NULL, 24, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span><p><b>Introduction</b></p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Printed Circuit Boards are an essential component of electronic appliances and gadgets. Without printed circuit boards, the functioning of electronic gadgets will be impossible. The printed circuit boards are responsible for the smooth flow of electricity within an electrical circuit. Different gadgets require different types of printed circuit boards. There are two major printed circuit board types;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Rigid Printed Circuit Board (Rigid PCB)</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Flexible Printed Circuit Board (</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Flexible-PCBs\"><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Flexible PCB</font></b></a>)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Traditionally almost all electronic devices used rigid PCBs. However, with time and increased knowledge more and more electircal engineers are moving towards using flexible printed circuit boards. All conventional devices can &nbsp;work with both types of printed circuit boards. However flexible circuit boards are ideal &nbsp;for complex electric circuits. Almost all new and modern electronic devices use flexible circuit boards or a combination of <a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Rigid-Flex-PCBs\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b>rigid and&nbsp;flexible PCBs</b></font></a>. Such circuits are known as Rigid Flex PCBs. Even though many electronic devices can work with both types of circuit and a combination &nbsp;of both circuits can be great, there are still some very significant differences between the two printed circuit boards. Let’s take a look at some of the differences between the both circuit boards.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-12/iStock-514741816.jpg\" alt=\"The Difference Between Rigid PCB and Flexible PCB.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Flexibility</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>As clear from the name the flexible printed circuit board can bend and twist however a rigid circuit board cannot. The flexibility of the flex circuit gives it a lot of advantage more the rigid printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Manufacturing Process</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>When it comes to the manufacturing of both rigid and flexible printed circuit boards, you can find a lot of differences. Whether it’s making of the design, manufacturing process and use of certain materials. The materials used to make a flex circuit are significantly different than the materials used to make a rigid circuit. The flexible printed circuit board is covered with flexible &nbsp;lamination where as a rigid printed circuit board has a solid solder mask. This also results in lower weight for the flexible printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Thickness Level Of The Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The rigid printed circuit board is thicker than flexible circuit boards. The flexible printed circuit boards can be very thin. They can get as thin as a paper. You can even &nbsp;find flexible circuit boards as thin as 0.2 mm. &nbsp;As clear from the name the flexible printed circuit boards need to be thin as some electric gadgets might want bendable printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Softness Of The Circuit Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The softness level of both the circuit boards can be judged by their second names. The rigid PCB is also known as hard board and the flexible circuit board is known as soft board. The flexible circuit board has to be soft as it needs to bend and twist.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Shape Of The Printed Circuit Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>When it comes to the shape of printed circuit boards, rigid board has a somewhat standard square and rectangle shape where as flexible printed circuit boards can vary in shape. Mostly the shape depends on the type of electronic device the circuits are going to be used in. As flexible circuits are mostly used in complex electronic equipments they have to shaped &nbsp;in ways that can fulfill each unique and customized need of each individual electronic appliance. &nbsp;This is also the reason that flexible circuit boards have a bendable shape.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Designing Of The Pad On The Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The flexible printed circuit board faces a very specific issue with pads on the circuit board. As you can bend the flexible circuit boards, it is very important to keep the pads away from the bending region. If the pads are on or near the soft bending area then it can cause problems in smooth flow of current. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>The Capacity To Carry Current</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>When it comes to carrying current, the rigid printed circuit board is better as compared to flexible printed circuit board. The flexible circuit board can have a bending shape which does not encourage smooth flow of current where as the rigid printed circuit board can have a straight line of current. This boosts the carrying capacity of the rigid printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Space Take</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>If you are looking to have complex circuits placed in a small device then the best option for printed circuit board to go for is the flexible circuit board. The flexible printed circuit board can be bent in any shape to fit the size of the respective device. &nbsp;This is why most of the smaller devices these days like mobile phones and tablets use flexible printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Cost Of The Printed Circuit Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There is no specific way to calculate the price of a circuit board as the price of the circuit board may vary with the difference in shape , size , type and design. &nbsp;Generally , the rigid circuit boards cost less as compared to the flexible circuits. However that is not always the case. The flexible circuit boards usually have lesser components which reduce the material and assembly cost of the end product. So in such cases the flexible circuits are more cost effective.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Both flexible circuit boards and rigid circuit boards have their own unique features. They both serve the same purpose but it is crucial to know which type of board would work best with your circuit. Some electronic equipment may work better with rigid circuit box while some might work better with flexible circuit boards. Most of the modern circuit boards work on a combination of both rigid and flexible circuit boards. These types of circuits are called Rigid-Flex Circuit Boards and highly skilled and knowledgeable engineers these days focus on such types of circuit boards. The Rigid-Flex circuit uses the uniqueness and differences between the two types of PCBs to create a more effective circuit board that can work with almost all types of electronic equipment and appliances.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'The Difference Between Rigid PCB and Flexible PCB', 'Rigid PCB, Flexible PCB', '  The Difference Between Rigid PCB and Flexible PCB', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (54, 'Printed_Circuit_Board_Assembly_54', '2019-11-13 10:19:59', NULL, 30, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Introduction</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Printed circuit board assembly or PCBA refers to the process of soldering or connecting electronic components to printed circuit boards. When the electronic components are not connected to the circuit board then it is known only as printed circuit board. Once the electronic components are assembled and soldered on the circuit board, it is known as Printed Circuit Board Assembly. Terms like Printed Circuit Assembly and PCB Assembly are also used to describe printed circuit board assembly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Is Printed Circuit Board Assembly Same As Printed Circuit Board Manufacturing</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It should be noted that when we talk about printed circuit board assembly, we do not mean the assembly of circuit boards during their manufacturing process. Printed circuit board assembly is actually what is done after the initial designing has been done. Once the circuit board has been manufactured, electronic components have to be connected and soldered over the board. These electronic components can be both active and passive components. &nbsp;After the electronic components have been soldered over the circuit board, only then does it become available to be used in an electronic equipment. There are three basic things that have to be kept in note during printed circuit board assembly. These things are mentioned below;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Type of electronic components</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Type of PCB</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Purpose of the printed circuit board</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>How Can You Carry Out Printed Circuit Board Assembly</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>When it comes to connecting the electronic components on the printed circuit board then there are two methods to choose from. The first one is the Thru-Hole Method and the second one is Surface Mount Method.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Thru-Hole Method</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Thru-Hole assembly method is used when you need to connect electronic components with wires on the board. These wires can be plugged through the hole and soldered on the other side of the board. This method is usually used for large sized components like coil and capacitors.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Surface Mount Technology</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>As Thru-Hole Methods is used for relatively larger components, the Surface mount technology is used for smaller items like diodes and resistors.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-13/748673.jpg\" alt=\"PCB Assembly.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>The PCB Assembly Process</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>1.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Apply Solder Paste To The Circuit Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The first step in the printed circuit board assembly is to apply solder paste to the board. A thing stencil made up of stainless steel is placed on the board. The stainless steel stencil is used so that the solder paste can be &nbsp;applied to specific parts on the board. These are the same parts where the electronic components will be attached in the end product. i.e. PCB.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Type Of Solder Paste Used</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The solder paste used in the assembly of printed circuit boards is made up of &nbsp;copper, silver and tin.</span><span>	</span><span>Tin is used in relatively higher proportions which is why the paste has a grayish color. It is very important to apply this solder paste to exactly the right place. If you apply large quantities of solder paste at the wrong place then that would waste your entire board and you will have to try again.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>2.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Surface Mount Components</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Once the solder paste has been applied on the board the next step is to add the surface mount components. Most of the components on a printed circuit board that don’t need to be connected to other components are surface mount components. Certain spots on the circuit board are fixed for these components. Once the solder paste has been applied, these components can be placed on the solder paste in their specified spots.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>3.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Reflow Soldering</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>After you have placed the components on top of the solder paste, the next step is to make those components stick to the board. This can be done by solidifying the solder paste. This process is known as reflow soldering. This is carried out by heating the board and melting the solder. The melted solder then cools down and solidify the components in their place.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>4.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Quality Assurance And Control</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Like all other products , you need to perform quality control and inspection for the circuit board. &nbsp;Once the board passes through the soldering process and the reflow process, you have to check the board for any problems. The quality inspection performed at this stage is very strict and if there are any errors then they usually get caught at this time. There are many different methods to inspect the item. Three of the major quality control methods are &nbsp;manual inspection, automated inspection and X Ray inspection. The inspection methods can vary with different manufacturers however these are three of the most common methods that most of the manufacturers use. Sometimes the manufactures use a collection of these methods or to optimize their quality control, they use all methods to check the product for any errors.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>5.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Thru-Hole Components </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>We &nbsp;have already talked about the surface mount components. At this stage, the Thru-Hole components are added to the board. Different circuit boards required different types of components. If your board requires thru-hole components then they will be added at this stage after the initial quality control.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>6.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Final and Function Inspection</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>After the complete assembly of the printed circuit boards, the last step is the final inspection. This is called the functional test where the end result is tested. The PCB is tested through different ways to see if all aspects of the circuit board are working properly or not. If there is an issue with a product then it is sent to the back of the assembly line. The PCBs that pass the test are sent forward for commercial use.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>In the old days the&nbsp;</span><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-Assembly/PCB-Assembly-Overview\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">printed circuit board assembly</font></a>&nbsp;</b>was done in a manual way. &nbsp;From start to end every step was done by humans. However with time the machines took over the assembly process. Humans could work in an efficient and effective manner but they used to get tired after a little while. Working with such small components made people tired and made their eyes hurt. The thing about using automated machine is that they are efficient and they don’t get tired. Automation has remarkable boosted the productivity of printed circuit board assembly.</p>   ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Printed Circuit Board Assembly', 'PCB Assembly', ' Printed Circuit Board Assembly ', 0, '2019-11-13 10:57:07', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (55, 'Why_Use_a_Printed_Circuit_Board_55', '2019-11-14 15:01:22', NULL, 20, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The modern era is defined by technology. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Look anywhere and rest assured that you can find some piece of technology associated with it, in one form or another. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Indeed, you could say that there is hardly an aspect of lives which are not defined by the presence of these scientific advancements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of the much such advancement that has taken place over the years, one of the most important is by far, the printed circuit board or PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Invented several decades ago, they can be described as the backbone of almost all tech gizmos around. From tiny chips to massive circuits, you can find PCBs in almost all of them. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p><span><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-14/280-opened-pads-on-a-populated--printed-circuit-board.jpg\" alt=\"280-opened-pads-on-a-populated--printed-circuit-board.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This large scale use of the technology in almost every gadget and hardware will obviously leave one question in one’s mind, as to reason for its large scale adoption. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several reasons for the above question, the details of which have been explained in the points below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1. Durability </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing that has been a major source of complaint in the industry about circuits, it had to do with their lack of structural strength. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Traditionally, circuits were designed using wires, which made them very weak and fragile. Something as fragile as minor impact was enough to ruin them, and in turn making the entire device useless. It didn’t matter how much the same was fixed, because it was a given that the circuits would break down again eventually. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The creation of these printed circuits made the possibility of damage to the circuits almost impossible in most cases. What was once a fragile piece of assembly quickly became something that was next to indestructible, at least according to the industry standards of the day. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2. Versatile &amp; Adaptive </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another great advantage of the technology was that the technology was highly versatile. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There was no real restriction on what the same could be used for, as it could be used for a wide range of applications, ranging from small toys to spacecrafts. In other words, the ability to use this technology was only limited by one’s imagination more than anything else. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Today, printed circuit boards are used for a wide variety of requirements, which range from simple household gadgets to space applications. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To make a long story short, it can be said that wherever there is a need for electrical circuits, it is possible for one to deploy the usage of this technology in a manner that is both effective as well as satisfactory in terms of outcome. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3. Cost Effective </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is a point that has to be taken in context with time, for it didn’t really apply to the technology for quite some time. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>During the early days of printed circuit board development and use, the cost of producing the same was rather expensive. This limited their use on a large scale, even though it proved to be compatible and effective for a wide range of applications.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It was only after continued research and technological advancement that the cost of producing printed circuit boards came down. Today, the manufacturing costs are next to nothing, especially when done on a large scale. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has made this piece of technological hardware a cost effective way to manufacture other appliances and devices, without compromising on their quality or effectiveness. It is in fact partly for this reason that the cost of electronics has fallen significantly in recent times, thereby making them more affordable to almost everyone. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4. Simplification of Large Designs &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The title here refers here to the fact that the circuits could be increased in complexity and function, as per the necessary requirement. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is not something that was possible to achieve in the case of early wire-based circuitry. Given that wires were bulky, it wasn’t always possible to make sleek and efficient electronic devices like they exist today. In its place were bulky pieces of hardware with bundles of wires that often confused even the manufacturer at first glance. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The emergence and use of printed circuit boards changed all of that, as it allowed for the wires to be replaced by a simple chip, which in turn could be manufactured with multiple layers; and that’s what it all comes down to. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The manufacture of multi-layer printed circuit boards were a real game changer for the industry, as the industry could now compress large circuits into a small area, thereby saving on space requirements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This in turn allowed for technologies to become smaller and as a result, more sleek and efficient. There was no more a need for one to carry around bulky pieces of hardware for any reason. One can actually notice this first hand, if they observe the way technology evolved over the decades; the size of the technologies became increasingly small as the years went by, partly because a good portion of the wires being used were replaced by printed circuit boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5. Energy Efficient </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to the usage of wires, one major problem is that of energy needs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;All electrical and electronic circuits come with the need for energy. In the case of wires, this need may exceed acceptable levels, which would certainly be a major waste of resources, especially when used on a large scale. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The exact reasons for this varied, but it ranged from the thickness and length of the wire to the efficiency of the overall layout of the wire circuits. The usage of printed circuit boards helped to eliminate this problem, by creating circuits in a manner that was highly efficient and effective. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It should be added that this point may not always hold true. In the case of ineffective or flawed designs, there is every chance that the chip may not function as expected. But these are just exceptions to the rule rather than the opposite. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to the above points, there are many other reasons as to why printed circuit boards are used. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The ones mentioned are just some of the main ones that are used, with many more also in existence depending on the exact need and requirement.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Why Use a Printed Circuit Board', 'Printed Circuit Board, PCB', 'Why Use a Printed Circuit Board', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (56, 'Printed_Circuit_Board_Tester_Features_and_Methods_of_Use_56', '2019-11-18 15:56:43', NULL, 17, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one standard component used in technology, it would be that of printed circuit boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit boards have been a major feature of technology for a very long time, and will probably do so well into the distant future. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>From toys to spacecrafts, this is one technological innovation that has found widespread use all over the world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-18/016.jpg\" alt=\"pcb test.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>Printed Circuit Board Testers</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As with just about everything else, there is a potential for the same to eventually break down. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Things break, for that’s just the nature of electronics and their components. Even if you were to use the latest in manufacturing techniques and took great care, the fact is that there will be issues down the line, sooner or later. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And when that happens, it is necessary that one knows how to figure out the source of the problem. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many ways in which to do this, which range from visual and physical inspection, to the use of specifically designed testing equipment. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to printed circuit board testers, there are quite a few around in the marketplace. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Depending on the design and purpose of these testers, the exact ways to use them will vary. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>Nature of the Printed Circuit Board Testers</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin with, it is important to note the various issues that may be addressed with the use of these devices. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These include, among others, the following:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Structural Flaws </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is by far one of the most common issues with printed circuit boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is not so much an issue with the circuit or the many components that are used on the board, but rather the board itself. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Issues such as cracks, deformities, loose components and so on, can end up making the structure non-functional. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Component Issues </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another major issue is that of the components used in printed circuit board. These components include resistors, diodes, capacitors, etc. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are a wide range of components that are used in the overall design architecture of these circuits. These may end up getting damaged overtime, whether it is due to physical impacts such as dropping, or being steadily worn out due to the constant flow of power or exposure to the elements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Either way, the damages to the many such components can lead to functionality issues in the structure of the printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are two main issues that come under this category, namely physical damage and that of voltage issues. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Miscellaneous Issues </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is the third category and includes everything that doesn’t come under the above two categories. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is to be noted that the above two categories usually include almost all of the potential issues that may exist in a fault printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is rather rare for anything to come under this category, if at all. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>The Usage and Functionality of Printed Board Testers</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Coming to the way the testers work, there are a variety of ways in which they function. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Typically, they follow a step by step process, which takes care to rule one flaw after another, until the true cause of an issue is determined. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Often, they come in two types, namely that of manual and automatic. As the name would suggest, manual testers are those which provide the features for testing the circuit boards, but don’t do any of the actual testing. The automatic testers on the other hand, will require very little physical effort on part of the technician, with the majority of the work being done by the device itself. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) The Initial Steps </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first step of the process, in addition to setting up the tester, would also include the feeding of the circuitry component into the equipment. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From here on, the steps to be taken will depend on whether the entire assembly is manual or automatic. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) The Work Flow </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The way that the process of testing a printed circuit board goes about, is usually a step by step manner. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Very rarely do the testers and related equipment do everything at the same time. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Typically, the process begins with the testing for structural issues. The most basic of testers will have nothing more than a simple light and inspection tools such as magnification equipment. But the more complex ones can come with scanning utilities to check for any potential damages. The latter tends to check for both issues with the board as well as the components. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the testers have scanners which check for damages in the circuitry itself, which is especially helpful, in the case of badly damaged PCBs. Given that they have the ability to ‘map’ out how a board works to a large extent, it is possible to locate the damage rather efficiently.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Many of the testers come with heat sensors, which detect whether there are flaws in the components. While all electronic components will give away heat when used, there is certain ‘threshold’ after which it is to be considered as an indication that there are issues with that particular part of the PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The next step is that of checking for issues with the voltage, typically with the help of a voltmeter and other such sensors. Again, the exact way that this goes about, will vary from an activity that is manually done to that which is completely automated.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the tests are completed, the tester will allow for one to deduct as to the true cause of the problem. In the case of automated designs, it is possible to also get the appropriate course of action as well, which will aid in either the repair or replacement of the board, and fix whatever gadget or device it was being used in. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, the points mentioned above gives a good idea as to the way in which printed circuit board testers work, as well as general guidelines on how to use them. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Do note that these are not fixed in any way, as they can be affected by a variety of factors, ranging from technological changes to design techniques. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If anything, they are to be considered as standard industry practices, and basic guidelines on how to go about with the entire process of checking the board’s quality and overall functionality.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Printed Circuit Board Tester Features and Methods of Use', 'Printed Circuit Board Tester', 'Printed Circuit Board Tester Features and Methods of Use', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (57, 'How_To_Repair_Printed_Circuit_Board_57', '2019-11-19 13:56:48', NULL, 20, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Introduction</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Printed Circuit Boards are the basic component of most of the electronic devices we use every day. From large screen televisions to small mobile phones, all devices use printed circuit boards. If you are an electrical engineer then chances are that you deal with printed circuit boards on a daily basis. You might need them for a new device or for updating an existing circuit.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The printed circuit boards can get damaged for many different reasons. Sometimes the PCB can be damaged beyond repair but other times the damage is quite repairable. &nbsp;Printed circuit boards are a very important component which is why it is crucial for you to repair them as perfectly as possible. A bad repair can result in electrical short circuit.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It is ideal to get the PCB fixed from a professional however if you want to learn ways to repair a printed circuit board then we are here to help.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-19/1900-11060219205846.jpg\" alt=\"How To Repair Printed Circuit Board.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Repairing Printed Circuit Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Repairing printed circuit boards can be a very challenging task. &nbsp;To repair a printed circuit board, you need to have proper knowledge and skills about the subject. Let’s take a look at ways you can repair a printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Identify The Problem</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The first thing you need to do while repairing a printed circuit board is to diagnose the issue. You have to identify what part of the printed circuit board is causing the problem. Once you identify the malfunctioning part, you have to see if you can replace it with a similar component of if you need to find the exact same part. Some component on a printed circuit board can be replaced with a similar component. However defective parts that play a specific function have to be replaced with the same type of component.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Choose A Setting</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Printed circuit boards are full of many different small components. In order to repair the board you have to be very vigilant. You need to have proper tools to repair the board but before everything else you need to find a proper platform to put your PCB on. A smooth desk surface can be an ideal platform. You can either tape the circuit to the table or use specific clippers to hold the circuit board while you work on it. This will stop the circuit from moving while you are working on it. In addition to that you need to have all the required tools and accessories with you on the desk as well.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Remove The Defective Component</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You need a hot air gun to remove the defective component from the printed circuit board. Once the hot air gun is turned on, you can then hold it a few inches above the part that needs to be replaced. This will loosen the defective component. You can then pull the loosened component out with the help of tweezers.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Time To Solder The Components</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Take a specific length of copper braids and put them on the pad on the PCB. They should be put on the same place from where the defective component was taken out. Once you have put copper braid on the pad, you can then use the tip of the soldering iron to heat the copper braid. The copper braids will absorb all the extra solder present on the PCB pad. &nbsp;Once you are done, use clean alcohol swabs to clean the pads. Do not use wet cloth or any other type of cloth material. Alcohol swabs are the best option when it comes to cleaning the pads on the printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Join The New And 100% Working Component On The Pad Of The PCB</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The next step in printed circuit board repairing is to connect the new component with the pads on the printed circuit board. This is a very important part and should be performed with great care. &nbsp;There are two things you have to keep in mind while joining the new component to the pad on the printed circuit board. The first thing to keep in mind is the positioning and orientation of the component. You have to place it in the exact same position as the old component. Changing the position and orientation of the new product may cause the printed circuit board to short circuit. The printed circuit board will not work if the connections aren’t done in the right way. Use solder and soldering iron to connect leads of all the components with the corresponding links on the pad.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>When Are PCBs Un-Repairable</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Like all other products in the world, the printed circuit boards also have a lifetime. After which the pcb becomes weak and defective. In such cases it is better to buy a new pcb instead of repairing the old one. There are many other scenarios as well where getting a new printed circuit board makes more sense that repairing the older one. Some examples of un-repairable pcb issues are given below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Burned Printed Circuit Boards</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Exposed Copper</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Lifted Pads</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>When other parts of the PCB have already been replaced multiple times</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Experts believe that 5 years is the maximum time that a printed circuit board can work to its optimum level. After that it is highly recommended to replace the PCB with a new one.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There are different types of printed circuit boards found in the market. Two of the major printed circuit boards are rigid pcb and&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Flexible-PCBs\"><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\">flexible pcb</font></b></a><span>. Some circuits are even built by combining both rigid pcb and flexible pcb. No matter the type of printed circuit board, it can be repaired using a similar process mentioned above. The repairing process mentioned above is a somewhat general process and can be used to replace components on all types of printed circuit boards. It is very important to be highly skilled and knowledgeable about the repairing of PCB. If you are not sure about the repairing process then it is best to take it to a professional. A professional can carefully replace the defective part with a working one without damaging the pad or other parts of the circuit.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How To Repair Printed Circuit Board', 'Repair Printed Circuit Board', ' How To Repair Printed Circuit Board ', 0, '2019-11-19 14:03:32', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (58, 'How_to_use_PCB_58', '2019-11-21 09:40:18', NULL, 12, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Electronic devices are a crucial part of our lives. We use electronics for almost everything from the kitchen to our phones. A Printed Circuit Board (PCB) is the heart of all these electronic devices. As the globe grows its technology and the electric industry evolves, the PCBs field also continues to advance and become more sophisticated. Each day, the functionality of PCBs increases to provide higher speed and reliable functionality. PCBs often come in green color and a strong board that contain</span><span>s</span><span>&nbsp;several parts of the electronic appliance. PCB parts use an integrated circuit that is mounted over the PCB to make it useful in many applications. Here is how to use PCB safely.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Smart Home. </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Today, most people have connected their homes to more devices than ever. Some of these appliances include speakers, switches, locks and many more. Some of us even have real-time monitoring systems in our houses. PCBs, help such systems to show the energy consumption of each of these devices. As such, PCB helps you to monitor and control the smart appliances in your home. The PCB in your smart thermostat also assists it to understand the cooling and heating tools in your home. The PCB uses data that is unique to your home energy profile and the weather on the outside. PCB allows you to use your smartphone to control your smart devices in your home. However, you need a stable internet connection to control your smart appliances.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Health.</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The growth of the electronics field has contributed to the growth of the medical industry. PCB has made it possible to create medical devices with more functionality than ever before. Experts can now mount many parts on a single PCB board with limited space to come up with a high performing medical equipment. Such PCBs are called High-Density Interconnect. Often, medical equipment need</span><span>s</span><span>&nbsp;a large space. As such, these PCBs can serve the purpose of creating these medical tools. Experts use PCB materials that cannot harm a human body. These materials must go through tests to make sure that they meet the medical regulations.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-21/DIY-Flexible-Circuit-Board.jpg\" alt=\"DIY-Flexible-Circuit-Board.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>LEDs.</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Light-emitting Diodes (LEDs) are lighting technology used to light up residential and commercial buildings. Additionally, you can use LEDs in other industries such as marketing, and medical fields. Most people prefer LEDs because they are energy-efficient, compact, and they have a long life. In these applications, PCB allows the transfer of heat away from the bulb. High temperatures reduce the life of LEDs. As such, professionals use aluminum to make&nbsp;</span><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/LED-PCB\">PCBs used for LEDs</a>&nbsp;</font></b>since aluminum transfers heat better than other metals. This strategy also excludes the need for an extra heat sink making the LED more compact.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Aerospace Equipment. </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although the equipment used in aerospace may have similar requirements to those used in automobiles, the former is exposed to more harsh conditions than the latter. PCBs are used in several aerospace applications like</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>communication systems, space shuttles, satellites, and planes. Manufactures select materials that can withstand harsh conditions such as vibrations and extreme weather conditions. Additionally, these PCBs must be durable.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Safety and Security Applications.</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Most security systems use PCB to function. PCBs in security systems play a significant role in our safety more often than most of us may realize. The type of PCB in a security system depends on the specific application. However, all PCBs used in this sector must be reliable since security teams expect them to be effective at all times. Some security systems are used for outdoor security measures. As such, these PCBs should be able to withstand harsh weather conditions.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Military Applications.</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The military also uses PCBs in its equipment such as firearms, cars, communication, and computers. The military expects its material to be reliable and durable. The military also works under extreme conditions as they protect our borders. As such, they use materials such as copper and aluminum, which can withstand such conditions. PCBs used in military equipment must meet these standards and may also improve the ability of the military as technology continues to grow.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Industrial Application.</span></b><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to industrial equipment, there is a wide area to cover. Most of the industrial machine is electric and mechatronic based. The PCBs used in the industrial field is made from rigid material and can withstand high temperatures, noise, shocks, and vibrations. Currently, most industries have atomized their processes. Atomized equipment rel</span><span>ies</span><span>&nbsp;entirely on PCB to function. The PCB used in industrial machines conducts heat to protect them from melting and other damages. Most professionals make thicker copper tracks than in conventional PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs can adapt to several conditions across a vast range of industries. Manufacturers can create cost-effective and safe PCBs to help with operations in any sector. However, every PCB in any application must be reliable and should meet your needs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to use PCB ', 'use PCB ', ' How to use PCB  ', 0, '2019-11-21 09:47:11', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (59, 'Common_problems_and_solutions_with_printed_circuit_boards_59', '2019-11-22 10:14:27', NULL, 12, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit boards are pieces of hardware made from insulating materials and coated with metal. The boards are thin and are considered “printed” because etches are made in the metal coating using acid to make pathways for electric signals to travel to different components. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One could say that these pathways are almost like nerve endings for computers. Signals are sent through these pathways, making printed circuit boards an important component in many electrical devices.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While printed circuit boards are important, they are also fragile, and they can sometimes break or malfunction. In today’s post, you will learn some of the most common problems people run across with their printed circuit boards and how you can fix them.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-22/20144181138586262698.jpg\" alt=\"20144181138586262698.jpg\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>SOLDERING ISSUES</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Soldering problems can lead to malfunctions in your circuit boards. Sometimes, technicians who assemble the boards do not heat their solder to a hot enough temperature. Because the metal isn’t as hot, it doesn’t adhere to components of the board very easily. This can cause components to break or can create issues in the pathways within the board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The introduction of moisture during the soldering process can also cause issues, potentially causing the circuit board to catch on fire. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix:</span></b><span>&nbsp;To repair issues that come about from poor soldering, reattach the disconnected joints using a solder gun along with some solder. You can tell when the solder joint or component is disconnected if you see cracks or components that are not attached to the board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>ACUTE ANGLES</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As mentioned earlier, printed circuit boards are often created using acid. The acid creates pathways for electricity to travel throughout the board. During the creation process, acid may get trapped in and angle, which can cause the acid to make pathways that cause the device not to work properly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix:</span></b><span>&nbsp;If you’re noticing that the pathways seem off on your circuit board, you may have to go ahead and replace the board. However, if you’re purchasing a board to work with, try to find circuit boards made with cupric chloride. This won’t cause acute angles in your circuit boards to begin with!</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>ENVIRONMENTAL INFLUENCES</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Unfortunately, your environment counts when it comes to printed circuit boards. This means extreme heat and cold as well as moisture and dirt can really impact how well the printed circuit board does its job. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Make sure that dust does not clog near the circuit board and try to avoid areas with extreme temperatures and moisture. If the circuit board is already damaged from these things, you will have to replace the board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>BURNT CIRCUIT BOARDS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Along these same lines, circuit boards that are clogged by dust or in extreme heat can actually catch fire and burn. This will make your device nearly unusable.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Assure that the all components are otherwise safe. Remove and replace the circuit board. To avoid this, keep your devices clean and in a mild environment.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>SLIVERS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Slivers occur during the printed circuit board creation process. At times, the slivers may occur on a part of the board that causes it to be unaffected. But in other cases, the sliver (a piece of copper that breaks during chemical etching) can land on a pathway and disrupt the proper flow for electrical signals.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This should usually be caught in the manufacturing process, but some damaged printed circuit boards slip through the cracks in the process. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix</span></b><span>: In most cases, you will have to replace the board. Slivers, however, are avoidable. During the design process, the technician must create section with minimum widths to reduce slivering.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>THERMALS DEFECTIVENESS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Thermals are pads that connect to the circuit board plane. Their sole job is to dispurse heat so that the circuit board can do its job without overheating. When a circuit board has defective thermal padding or paste, it can overheat and potentially catch the circuit board or entire device on fire. It can also cause disruption in the processes the circuit boards are helping to perform.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Replace the thermal padding or paste on the circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>AGE OF THE CIRCUIT BOARD</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Over time, circuit boards will begin to slow and break down. This can cause performance issues on the devices the circuit boards are working for! This is one issue that is simply unavoidable because, unlike a lot of things, circuit boards can’t stand the test of time.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix</span></b><span>: You can either replace some of the components on the board, or you can replace the entire board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>&nbsp;</span></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>VOIDS IN THE PLATE</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While creating a circuit board, gaps or voids can be created during the deposition process. These holes can make it difficult for electricity to pass through the board’s pathways and perform the action that was needed. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some issues that can cause voids include contamination and air bubbles.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix</span></b><span>: If you currently have a circuit board with voids that are causing interruptions, you will have to replace the circuit board. But, if you are creating a circuit board, assure that air bubbles are popped, the deposition process includes an even lay of the materials, and there is no possibility of contamination.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>BADLY MADE COMPONENTS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In some cases, the circuit board itself isn’t the issue, but the components attached to the board. This could include wires that are used to send the electrical signals throughout the board. Faulty components can cause connection issues, leaving the circuit board unable to complete its job. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>The fix:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Simply replace all of the faulty components. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>ELECTROMAGNETIC PROBLEMS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Again, issues that occur during the design process can result in unfixable problems with your circuit board. Electromagnetic issues include difficulties with electromagnetic interference and electromagnetic compatibility. Electromagnetic interference is not something you want to happen. This interference overloads the board and can open it up for the possibility of damage.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The fix: In this case, you will need to replace your circuit board.</span><span><br></span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In conclusion, these circuit board issues are easy to fix. Take a good look at your board and determine the issue before working on it.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><br></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You may also be interested in&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/blog/How_To_Repair_Printed_Circuit_Board_57.html\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b>how to repair pcb</b></font></a>, you can click to view.</p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Common problems and solutions with printed circuit boards', 'printed circuit boards', ' Common problems and solutions with printed circuit boards ', 0, '2019-11-22 10:25:28', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (60, 'How_to_Make_Printed_Circuit_Board_At_Home_60', '2019-11-23 09:28:12', NULL, 17, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Introduction</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit board is a board of very thin fiberglass which is used to connect various electronic components together with the help of transistors, sheets of copper, resistors, pads, and other conductive substances on to the board and all of these components are printed on to the board to a pathway connecting to a substrate that is non-conductive. Usually, the PCB has all the designs tracked on it already. These tracks help to reduce the number of wiring that has to be done which ultimately reduces the risk of loose connections and the risk of faults that may arise as a result of them. PCBs can easily be made at home by three popular methods which are: Iron on Paper Method, Laser cutting and edge etching method and Circuit by hand Method</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Even though these three methods are very popular to make PCB, only the first two will be discussed in detail in this article as the third one is the most used method in the industries.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-23/How to Make Printed Circuit Board At Home.jpg\" alt=\"How to Make Printed Circuit Board At Home.jpg\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>How to Make PCB At Home?</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Let’s now look at how we can make PCB at home in different steps.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 1: Create the Layout of Circuit</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>In this step, you convert your design/ diagram into the layout of PCB by making use of the software for layout. There are various packages of software for layout design and its creation. Some of the popular and useful ones are Cadsoft Eagle and PCB Wizard. To get a better quality it is important to set DPIG to 1200 in Cadsoft Eagle.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 2: You Gather All the Material that is required</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This includes magazines or brochures, Laser Printer, Iron for clothes, an Etching solution, Laminate Clad of Copper, Thinner, plastic wires, and scrubs used in the kitchen. You may also need a black marker, kitchen paper, old clothes, cutter, and sandpaper. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 3: &nbsp;A Physical Print Out Of The Layout Is Necessary</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You have to take a printout of the layout in appropriately sized paper. This will help you streamline the process. Once you familiarize yourself with the layout you would be able to work more efficiently.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 4: &nbsp;The Copper Plates Need To Be Cut</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Once you know the size of the layout. You can keep that size in mind and then cut the copper plates according to that size.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 5: Making it Smooth</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>In this step you make the use of scrub or wool made up of steel to rub on the copper. This step is done to remove the oxide and photo resistant layer of copper.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 6: The Print Is Ironed On</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>After printing it is ironed from the copper side while making sure the iron is heated up to the maximum temperature. You put everything on a wooden table and some clothes on the back of the photo. You hold the end with a towel and run the iron through it for about ten seconds then you iron the photo paper using the tip while applying the pressure for about fifteen minutes. Pressure should be applied slowly and pressing hard is better than just moving around the iron everywhere. The heat helps to melt the ink and transfer on to the copper plate.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 7: Finalize The Print On To The Copper Plate</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Method One: Iron- On Glossy Paper</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>In this step, you transfer the picture from the printout to the board. It is important to ensure the top layer is set horizontally. The copper side should be put on the layout that is printed and it should be aligned properly to the borders. A tape should be put on the remaining two sides of the board which does not have copper this will help to keep everything in position.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Method Two: Circuit by Marker</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>First, a sketch of the circuit is drawn here with a pencil and then later with permanent marker by making use of the circuit image printed on the glossy paper.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 8: Peel Off</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Once the ironing is completed you put the plate that is printed in warm water for almost ten minutes. This will eventually dissolve and remove the paper completely. Whatever is left off can be removed at low angles. Sometimes when the paper is being removed the track may get lightened, to resolve this issue we use a dark-colored black marker to high lighten the track. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 9: Etching and Disposing</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You take a box, fill it with water and dissolve 3 teaspoons of acid ferric chloride in it. You dip the PCB in this solution for almost thirty minutes until the chloride reacts with the copper and removes the excess copper from the PCB. This process is called etching and unmasked copper is removed out with the help of pliers. After this, you slowly remove the plastic box to and fro to ensure iron and copper chloride is formed. It is important to ensure that the etching solution is not touched directly without the gloves. Etching solution needs to be disposed of with proper care because it is very harmful for the fish and other water organisms; moreover, it can damage the water pipeline if poured directly in the sink. Therefore, it is important to ensure the solution is diluted well before disposed.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Step 10: You Give the Final Touch to Your PCB</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This is your last step in PCB making. You just add a final touch to it here. You add a few drops of thinner or nail polish remover on a cotton wool to act as a toner and bring back the surface of copper. It should be rinsed in the thinner very carefully and once this is done a dry cloth should be used to dry it. Then you trim the edges with the help of sandpaper and use acetone to stick he glossy paper to the rough paper. After this, you drill the hole and arrange all the components a. your PCB is all set now!</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Conclusion</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Iron on the Glossy paper method is the easiest and the most efficient method to make PCB at home with little or no hassle. The Circuit on hand method requires a little bit of skill and effort but making a complex PCB iron- on gloss method is the best and is strongly recommended.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It still takes some time to make pcb at home. If you need to buy pcb in bulk, welcome to know our&nbsp;</span><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/HowWeProduce/Capability/PCB-Capability\">pcb production capacity</a>&nbsp;</font>we can deliver a lot of fast delivery.</p>   ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to Make Printed Circuit Board At Home', 'Make Printed Circuit Board At Home', ' How to Make Printed Circuit Board At Home ', 0, '2019-11-23 10:03:38', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (61, 'Latest_News_on_PCB_61', '2019-11-25 14:27:03', NULL, 13, 0, 0, '  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Technology is today developing, evolving and affecting the world around us at a rate never seen before. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With research and development, as well as consumption underway all across the world, it is very likely that these trends are here to stay. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Today, there is a lot going on in the world of electronics, regarding their improvements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One could say that it is but a continuous process, which has been taking place since the first rudimentary circuits were created, several decades ago. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And if one were to look at the news, they can notice that there are many interesting developments happening, which will determine the future of the electronic industry.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to add here is that the developments need not always be that of technological advancements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It could be something entirely different and yet related, such as growth trends, market demands, sales forecasts and more. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given the potential for growth in the electronics industry around the world, one could say that there are a lot of sales coming up in the near future, especially in developing countries across Asia, Africa and South America. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many such developments happening around the world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given in the points below are some interesting news reports about such events, from around the world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-25/1 (3).jpg\" alt=\"PCB.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) The Rise of Flexible Circuits </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For a very long time, circuits have been a fixed thing rather than a flexible one. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With the exception of wires, the world of PCBs or Printed Circuit Boards have always been sturdy structures, with a hard substrate on which were printed the metal paths that conducted electricity and transferred information. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">One of the interesting developments that have taken place is in the field of<font color=\"#1e90ff\">&nbsp;</font><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Flexible-PCBs\">flexible printed circuits</a>.</font> While the technology is still in its infancy, it does hold potential, and is very likely to hit the markets with sufficient research.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;The concept is exactly what it sounds like; they are circuits which are ‘flexible’ in nature, rather than firm. The potential for such circuits are huge, given that they can be implemented in a wide range of electronics, especially ones where circuitry is expected to bypass moving parts. The applications of this technology have an enormous potential, from automobiles to robotics, and more. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Link:</span></b><span>&nbsp;https://semiengineering.com/test-in-new-frontiers-flexible-circuits/ </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Creative Ways of Using &amp; Disposing Used PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as the world of electronics has been progressing, there has been a growth of concern in another aspect of the economy; electronic waste.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;Technology after use has increasingly become problematic for recycling and disposal, for a variety of reasons. From the lack of infrastructure to policy issues, electronic waste, often called ‘E-Waste’ has become a major environmental challenge of the present age. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While there are many ways in which the same can be addressed, one group has started using old PCBs for manufacturing innovative products, such as models of cities and more. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It can be thought of an idea of how innovative solutions can be crafted from something as random as PCBs. There are indeed multitudes of ways in which the problem of E-Waste can be resolved, and this is something that holds true for PCBs, as well as every other gadget that will eventually be thrown away. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Link:</span></b><span>&nbsp;https://www.indiatimes.com/trending/environment/how-to-reduce-electronic-waste-378793.html</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) &nbsp;2024 Will the Year for Automotive PCB Industry</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed Circuit Boards or PCBs are used in a variety of applications.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;These range from simple toys to high tech applications, one of which is that of cars and other vehicles. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is estimated that, given the growth of the ‘smart’ car industry, there will soon be a great deal of growth in demand for PCBs in this industry. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While the exact peak of the demand varies, it is very likely that the demand will be at its highest sometime around the year 2024. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Link:</span></b><span>&nbsp;http://honestnewsly.com/2019/10/30/global-automotive-printed-circuit-boardpcb-market-2019-competitive-analysis-amitron-corp-chin-poon-industrial-cmk/</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) PCB E-Waste Will Soon Exceed 3 Million Tons</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The problem of E-Waste is a major issue in society, and is something that needs to be immediately addressed. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While there are many components to this industry, one of the contributors happens to be that of&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">PCB</font></a>s or Printed Circuit Boards.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;It is estimated that, at the current rate of consumption of PCBs around the world, it is very likely that the total amount of waste generated from scrapped PCBs will reach and exceed 3 million tons by the year 2026. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of course, it should be added that these are just estimates. It is entirely possible that the exact figures may vary, in terms of both an increase as well as decrease. The exact reason for this is many, ranging from growth of the E-waste recycling industry, to consumption patterns and everything else in between. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Link:</span></b><span>&nbsp;https://thefinancetime.com/e-scrap-and-printed-circuit-board-pcb-e-scrap-market-is-expected-to-reach-3-14-million-tons-by-2026/85499/</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) The Printed Circuit Board May Become Obsolete </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as this is not something that will happen in the near future, the fact is that the potential certainly exists. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is very likely that with the improvements in technology, something called ‘silicon-interconnect fabric’ could end up taking place of printed circuit boards across the industry. Believed to be energy efficient, effective and high-performance, they will very likely be the next step in the quest for the perfect circuitry. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This however, need not worry anyone who is in the PCB industry, given that the technology is in its infancy. It may take several years or even decades before it hits the market. For now, we will be sticking with printed circuit boards, well into the foreseeable future. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Then again, there is always the potential that something new will hit the mainstream before we expect it, as it was the case with say the internet, which became widely popular within a very short time during the 1990s. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Link:</span></b><span>&nbsp;https://www.hpcwire.com/2019/09/25/are-printed-circuit-boards-on-their-way-out/</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, the developments mentioned above, as well as others like it, are but a small sample of the many transformations being experienced across the world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And given that the process is still underway, there is a lot more that can be expected from all of this, with the passage of time. With the potential for improvement always present, it should keep tech enthusiasts and industry professionals ticking for a long time to come.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>    ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Latest News on PCB', 'PCB', '  Latest News on PCB  ', 0, '2019-11-25 14:30:33', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (62, 'How_to_Choose_Single-Layer_PCB_and_Double-Layer_PCB_62', '2019-11-26 10:26:09', NULL, 13, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The world of electronic circuitry has come a long way. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From days of rudimentary circuits to those of PCBs or Printed Circuit Boards, the pace of development and change has certainly been enormous.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These developments in general and PCBs in particular, turn have helped to create the world of electronics that one can see today. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From handheld devices to large home appliances, PCBs have played a major role in their development over the years. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of the many things manufacturers like to know about PCBs, one of the most important is selecting the right kind for the job. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is first important to know the difference between single and double layer PCBs, as that helps in figuring out what to do. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Both single and double layered PCBs have a solid substrate layer, which is the foundation on which everything else is built. The real difference lies in what is on top of this substrate layer. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the case of single-layer PCBs, the circuits are printed on one side of the board using a metal layer (typically made from etched or plated copper), while other components, such as resistors, capacitors, transistors, etc, and are present on the other. In addition to this, they also come with a protective solder mask, as well as a silk-screen for functionality and stability. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The design for double layer PCBs are pretty much the same, except for a few changes. For one thing, they contain several conducting layers rather than a single one like in single-layer PCBs. Another important difference is that while single-layer PCBs have their conducting metal layer on one side of the board, double-layered have the same on both sides. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-26/intro-inlay-700x220.jpg\" alt=\"How to Choose Single-Layer PCB and Double-Layer PCB.jpg\" style=\"\">When it comes to single-layer PCBs and double-layer ones, there are a few things to be considered.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>&nbsp;Given in the list are some of the most important things to consider, when it comes to choosing these PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Nature of the Circuit </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is by far one of the most important things to consider, when dealing with selecting a PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Not all circuits are the same. On the contrary, each has their own unique design, function and purpose. This makes choosing the right one a rather tricky process. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the main considerations that are to be looked into has to do with the nature of the circuit. In general, circuits that require a simple layout can go with single-sided PCBs, while those that are complex can go for double-sided ones. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Cost Factor </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another important difference between the two is the cost factor. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The construction of double-sided PCBs tends to be far more complex than that of single-sided ones. This makes the former more expensive than the latter. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In light of this, budgetary constraints can help to decide whether one has to go for single or double sided ones. It should be noted that picking a PCB based on the budget should also take into consideration the scope and requirements of the project as well. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) The Reputation of the Supplier </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something that holds true for both single as well as double layered PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Regardless of the requirement you may have, the fact is that you’ll need someone reliable to do the job. Without this, you might just end up having trouble down the road, in more ways than you can imagine. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is therefore important that you check the nature of the supplier, and verify their credentials. If necessary, make a visit to the factory as well, to see for yourself how the product is made. While many companies don’t allow for site visits, others do and you should take full advantage of this. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The above paragraph holds doubly true in the case of foreign suppliers, given that you’ll be getting it from a place you have no idea about. Should that be the case, you might want to go and check the place out for yourself, even if it means spending a tidy sum on flight tickets, visas and what not. If you have your entire business on the line, it doesn’t hurt to go the extra mile, quite literally, to ensure that you have a good supplier. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Aftercare Services &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This point is related to the previous one, and at the same time something unique unto itself. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You’ll need to get a supplier who has the means to address any concerns you may have, once the purchase has been made. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is because once your products have hit the market, you will be liable if something should go wrong. And if that happens to be an issue with the PCBs, you need to be in touch with the suppliers in order to correct any problems that may occur. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Lead Time &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has nothing to do with the PCBs themselves, but rather the time it would take to manufacture them.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;Even in the age of automation and mass production, the fact is that manufacturing anything will take time. It is not like the entire unit, or for that matter the lot, can be synthesized in a few moments. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is here where the issue of lead time comes into the picture. It can be understood as the amount of time it would take to manufacture or produce something. In general, single-layer PCBs tend to have shorter lead times, due to their simplicity, while double-layered ones have longer lead times given their complexity. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While the lead time is an unavoidable part of the manufacturing process, it is not something that you should allow to take longer than necessary. It is always a good idea to find a supplier who takes the shortest lead time possible, without compromising on the quality of the final product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) Timely Delivery &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The world of business is something that works like clockwork, where there a constant moment of goods and services. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The system is such that even the smallest amount of disturbances can lead to unforeseen effects later on in the business cycle, should one not be careful about this. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the case of PCBs, here is an example of how it could play out. Distributors often have contracts with manufacturers to have shipments ready by a certain date. This in turn, can only be fulfilled, if the products are manufactured on time. All of this has the potential to come to a standstill, if the supplier is unable to meet delivery deadlines on time, for whatever reason.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;It is therefore necessary that one searches for a supplier who is capable of delivering at the given date and time, or for that matter even before, at least for the sake of keeping the supply lines rolling. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, the above list of requirements gives a good idea as to the differences that exist between the two kinds of PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Based on these factors and others like it, you should be able to pick out a suitable PCB that works for you, and helps you get the job done.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to Choose Single-Layer PCB and Double-Layer PCB', 'Single-Layer PCB, Double-Layer PCB', ' How to Choose Single-Layer PCB and Double-Layer PCB ', 0, '2019-11-26 10:34:49', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (63, 'Introduction_to_PCB_Prototype_Assembly_63', '2019-11-27 11:30:31', NULL, 21, 0, 0, '    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The printed circuit board is the long-form for PCB. The PCBs are ergonomically designed boards that are usually used as the base in electronics. The boards are commonly constructed out of composite epoxy or fiberglass. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Today, we are surrounded by electronic devices, which have become an integral part of our lives. Our phones, cars, and computers are all infused with electronic components. But within these components, lies a PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs are easily recognizable. They\'re tiny green chips carefully covered in copper parts and lines, located at the heart of electronic gadgets. The copper lines, which are made of fiberglass, are held together with a solder paste- which gives it the green color. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The modern circuit board cannot be functional until all the components are held together in a process called&nbsp;</span><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-prototype\">PCB prototype</a>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-Assembly/Prototype-PCB-Assembly\">assembly</a></font></b>.<span><br>. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-03/PCB Prototype 4 (1).jpg\" alt=\"PCB Prototype 4 (1).jpg\" style=\"\"></p><h1><b><span>The Simple PCB Basics</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></h1><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The printed circuit board assembly(PCBA) process is sensitive and consists of several manual and automated steps. And for the circuit to be complete, several alternating layers are put together for the full functionality of the electronic device. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These layers include:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"15\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Copper</font></span><span>&nbsp;– Copper layer is added on both sides of the PCB if it\'s double-sided and on one side if it\'s single-sided. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"15\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Substrate</font> </span><span>– The base fabric gives PCB its firmness. It protects the board from breaking for added durability and functionality. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"15\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Solder paste</font></span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>– a solder mask is added on top of the copper layer to give the PCB its green color. The mask insulates the copper and prevents it from being in contact with other conductive fabrics. Any contact with conductive materials can result in a short.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Silkscreen</span></b><span>&nbsp;– Basically, this is the final and top layer on the PCB board. It forms the symbols and character on the board, which helps in indicating the functionality of every component. This prevents confusion and errors. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><h2><b><span>PCB Assembly Process </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></h2><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The PCB assembly is a long, critical process that involves a myriad of manual and automated steps. There are three crucial technologies used in the PCB assembly process. They are:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>1.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>THT (Through-Hole Technology) Assembly Process</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>THT involves PTH components getting inserted through holes punctured into the PCBs. The leads are attached to the pads with a molten solder on the opposite side. This is the through-hole assembly process. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This technique replaced conventional processes like point-to-point construction. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The THT involves three essential steps which include:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Placement of Components</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is a manual process that is explicitly done by professional engineers. The components are required to be placed precisely and quickly on the corresponding positions. This can only be done by highly trained experts to avoid errors.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The process is required to adhere to operation</span><span>al</span><span>&nbsp;standards and regulations of the THT mounting process to get an excellent end product.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Inspection </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>After the completion of component placements, the PCB board will get inspected to determine if the components were accurately positioned. The inspection will help to determine if there are faults and get them rectified instantly. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Soldering </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the inspection is done and every component is accurately positioned, they will be soldered on the circuit board. In this process, the board will move slowly over a liquid solder at approximately 500°F. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>2.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>SMT (Surface Mount Technology) Assembly Process</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In this process, the circuits are directly placed on the surface of PCBs using a solder paste. The components are typically smaller compared to THT counterparts because SMDs have tiny or no leads at all.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The process takes place in 3 critical stages, namely:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Solder Paste </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is where the paste is applied on the PCB board via a solder paste printer. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Mounting Components </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The components are placed on the board through reels. These reels are designed to rotate to ensure the parts are quickly stick</span><span>ing</span><span>&nbsp;onto the board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In some processes, the mounting machines add minute dots to hold the component tightly on the board. But in this process, repair of the devices becomes a taxing affair.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It’s an automated process that is quite efficient will few or no errors at all. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Soldering (Reflow)</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the components are positioned accurately, the board will pass through a furnace at 500°F. It ensures the solder paste is heated and melted down to form sturdy joints between the board and the components.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>the major concern in this process is that parts are expected to withstand high temperatures for an extended period th</span><span>en</span><span>&nbsp;it\'s needed in manual or wave soldering</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The process is accomplished through a reflow oven that helps the components get hold firmly on the board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>SMT has a high automation degree which a myriad of benefits like;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Reduction of the overall cost</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Minimize human error</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>High-quality end products</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Ideal for mass production </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the industries that utilize this automation process include aviation, wireless, telecommunication, and automotive.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Optical Inspection </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Any board that goes through a reflow cycle is sent of an inspection. The X-Rays inspection gives a clear image of the solder joints for quantitative analysis. The inspection detects any issues on the board and also helps in determining the root cause of any error. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"16\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>3.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Mixed Technology </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Due to much evolution in technology, electronic devices are becoming complicated day by day. It, therefore, means these products require sophisticated PCB boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It’s increasingly becoming impossible for PCBs assembled in a single process to perform multifaceted tasks. As a result, mixed technology is the only viable solution. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Mixed technology is a combination of THT and SMT assembly processes to form a sturdy, reliable PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Testing </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The PCB assembly can either be manual or automated or the combination of both. And since human is to err, there might have error occurred in the process. It\'s, therefore, prudent to test the electronic devices before dispatching them to the consumers.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Reliable manufacturers use various test and measurement methods to ensure the end products are of high-quality.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Typically, the PCB assembly process is loaded with complicated processes and stages, but it has been simplified in this overview. The assembly and production processes of PCBs are highly optimized to ensure there are few or no defects. The result is having durable and functional devices.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>      ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Introduction to PCB Prototype Assembly', 'PCB Prototype Assembly', ' Introduction to PCB Prototype Assembly    ', 0, '2019-12-03 09:35:47', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (64, 'How_to_choose_a_cheap_and_high_quality_PCB_prototype _64', '2019-11-28 14:48:11', NULL, 19, 0, 0, '   <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A PCB prototype is a blueprint that contains the essential components of a printed circular board, such as the thickness of the PCB, number of layers, and the width and height dimensions. The other aspects of a PCB like heat sinks, number of copper layers, circuitry, etc. are not factored in the prototype design because they do not represent the actual prototype. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Investing in PCB prototypes does not have to be an expensive affair. There are&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-prototype\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">cheap and high quality prototypes</font></a>&nbsp;that can be used and still give amazing results. This article will highlight the necessary details you need to look out for when purchasing a cheap PCB prototype that will be equally effective.</p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-03/PCB Prototype 1.jpg\" alt=\"PCB Prototype 1.jpg\"></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>1.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Budget</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is the most crucial factor to consider when purchasing a&nbsp;</span>PCB prototype. Many companies manufacture printed circular boards, but quality and pricing differ a lot. It is essential to compare different suppliers before choosing the best one.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Take time to go through the reviews on the company\'s website to ascertain whether their products are worth your money. The reviews from previous clients will help you decide on the best PCB prototype, which is within your budget.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>2.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Quality</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to PCB prototypes, it is important to note that cheap does not always mean poor quality and expensive does not always mean good quality. That said, you should be very keen on the quality of the PCB prototype you are about to purchase because it will affect the functioning of the electronic device you intend to use the printed circular board for.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Referrals from other business associates in the same industry will give you a rough idea of the different suppliers available and their products. This knowledge, coupled with the reviews from the website, will help you make an informed decision and prevent you from buying a poor quality PCB prototype that will eventually compromise your product.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>3.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Lead Time &amp; Delivery</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The time factor is very crucial in any manufacturing business. When buying a PCB prototype, settle for a company that has a proven track record of delivering their products on time. Otherwise, you might end up stranded as you wait for the printed circular board prototypes to be delivered.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The lead time should also be factored in for the next purchase. Go for a company that will ensure your prototypes are delivered right on time, and you are not inconvenienced in any way.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>4.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Reliability &amp; Function</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Strive to always maintain a balance between the turnaround time and the cost of the prototype. Most of the time, quick turnaround time in conjunction with low cost always results in some problems. The functioning and reliability of the PCB prototype will eventually get compromised, which is not a good thing.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>5.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Instant Quote Service</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Many manufacturing companies inform their clients about the total PCB prototype cost. This helps to simplify the purchasing process because there is no back and forth dialogue on the price unless there is room for negotiating.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As a client, it assists you to quickly identify the printed circular board prototypes that are within your budget. Therefore, always choose the manufacturers or suppliers who provide instant quotations on their websites. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You should also note the minimum order quantity. Some companies have a specific limit on the minimum amount of prototypes you can purchase. Make sure you enquire first from their customer service team before making the order.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>6.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Durability</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as PCB prototypes are not the real thing, they should be equally durable because they represent the actual product. They still cost money to purchase, even if they are cheap. The prototypes should be durable and long-lasting to give you a rough idea of how the product performs. &nbsp;The cost of manufacturing electronics is high, and the last thing you want is to encounter disappointments after the final product due to a defective printed circular board prototype.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Always choose a company that has a proven track record of manufacturing cheap and functional PCB prototypes. ALLPCB, Euro Circuits, Sunstone, EpecTec, and 4PCB are some of the renowned companies which are famous for producing functional PCB prototypes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>7.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Efficiency</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This point should be among the main factors to consider when purchasing a PCB prototype. The prototype should be in good condition, and it should be able to perform almost the same function as the actual prototype.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Buying a cheap PCB prototype does not mean that its efficiency should be compromised. From the reviews on the company\'s website, you should be able to ascertain whether the product is worth buying or not.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>8.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Purpose of the PCB Prototype</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are certain advanced features that a prototype is not able to handle, which is why you should know the reason for purchasing the prototype in the first place. If you are making a simple electronic, then most prototypes should work. However, for devices that required more advanced technology, buying a PCB prototype might not be the best idea.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Therefore, make an effort to find out if the prototype you intend to purchase will be suitable for the device you are preparing to avoid losses that could have been easily avoided.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>9.&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>The PCB prototype should be error-free.</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There should not be any defects on the prototype because this will interfere with the quality of the product you are making. Once the manufacturing company has delivered the prototypes, take time to inspect them, and even test them. There should not be any missing prints or small drill holes on its surface. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In Conclusion</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Making the correct printed circular board is the most critical part of any electronic product. Some manufacturing companies have experienced massive losses due to a faulty PCB, which exhibited poor performance or no performance at all after full production. PCB prototypes eliminate these kinds of problems, and that is why it is crucial to invest in them.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>However, you should also take the necessary measures to ensure you purchase a good quality product, especially if you are targeting the cheaper ones. The good thing is many companies are toeing the line and producing quality products at an affordable price; therefore, it should not be a difficult task to identify a reliable manufacturer or supplier</span><span>.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>     ', 'PCB prototype ', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to choose a cheap and high quality PCB prototype ', 'PCB prototype ', '   How to choose a cheap and high quality PCB prototype    ', 0, '2019-12-04 11:23:19', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (65, 'Advantages_of_aluminum_PCB_boards_65', '2019-11-29 10:03:36', NULL, 19, 0, 0, '  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCB boards are also known as metal</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>core printed circuits, insulated metal substrate, aluminum clad, or aluminum base. &nbsp;They are metal-based and copper-clad laminates that are used to make electronics or other devices that require a lot of cooling. Aluminum PCBs make perfect thermal conductors for devices that generate a lot of heat, power switches, and power converting electronics. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCBs became famous in the 1970s, and back then, they were used in integrated circuits or amplified hybrid integrated circuits. Many advancements have taken place since then, and aluminum PCBs are now widely used and are made as a single layer or double layer printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-11-29/aluminum-pcb-1.png\" alt=\"aluminum-pcb-1.png\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>What are some of the advantages of Aluminum PCB boards?</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>They are unique and highly effective</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCBs are made of three layers. The circuit layer made of copper, a dielectric layer made of insulating material that has low resistance and a base layer made of aluminum. The dielectric layer contributes a lot to the effectiveness of aluminum PCBs because it is 5 to 10 times more thermally conductive than the epoxy glass. This means it will be able to conduct heat away from the device being used. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Cheap and easily available</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When compared to copper, wrought iron, brass, or stainless steel, aluminum is more affordable, making it a suitable material for printed circuit boards. Manufacturing companies always put in mind the production cost of devices, and aluminum is the perfect material for making printed circular boards due to its price.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On top of that, aluminum is available in many climatic conditions globally hence easy to refine and mine. Availability of the aluminum makes it easier to manufacture a vast of printed circuit boards at an affordable cost compared to the other materials.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The availability of aluminum lowers the manufacturing cost of the printed circular boards, and in return, the overall price of the products is lower. This leads to a positive impact on consumers because the devices made from aluminum PCBs will be a bit affordable compared to products made with printed circular boards from other substrates other than aluminum.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Great heat radiator</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum dissipates a lot of heat compared to the basic FR4 based printed circuit board. This means that it is more suitable for devices that release a lot of heat since the aluminum will scatter the heat effectively. Devices that need cooling are made with aluminum PCBs to prevent them from getting damaged. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Higher Durability</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCBs are very sturdy and provide extra tenacity, which is an added advantage due to minimal breakages. Accidents do happen in the manufacturing process, but aluminum PCBs are easy to handle because they are not fragile and will not break easily compared to ceramic or fiberglass bases.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The durability makes them more convenient for everyday use in the manufacturing process. Manufacturing companies aim at lowering the production cost, and one of the ways is by ensuring the products being used are not easily damaged because it will lead to losses. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Lightweight</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Ceramic and fiberglass bases are also used for making printed circular boards. However, they are not as feathery as aluminum, and this makes aluminum to have the edge over them. Aluminum is not bulky to carry, which makes the printed circular boards more economical in the end.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum printed circular boards are a huge improvement from the first printed circular boards, which were wired end to end on a chassis. These circuits were bulky, fragile, large, and heavy. The cost of production of making these products was high, not to mention labor-intensive. This, in return, made the products expensive.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Non-toxic</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In this era of increased global warming, most of the manufacturing companies are striving to come up with products that will not harm or degrade the environment. Aluminum is environmentally friendly, and it can easily be recycled, making it the perfect material for printed circular boards. A lot of devices and electronics currently have printed circular boards, and aluminum is the most realistic material to use since it does not negatively influence the environment. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Effective thermal conductivity</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCBs conduct and transfer heat from critical areas that may damage electronics. A good example is LEDs, which produce a lot of light, creating immense heat, and the aluminum effectively directs the heat away from the device. Therefore, there is minimal circuit damage, which will intensify the lifespan of the product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Versatility</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCBs can be used to manufacture an array of products. These include but not limited to computer central processing unit boards, Switches in regulators, High-frequency amplifiers, Motor drives, electronic regulators for cars among other electronic devices. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The versatility of aluminum makes it a prominent material because it simplifies the manufacturing process. Many devices that need a printed circular board can easily be manufactured due to the availability and functionality of aluminum.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>Improved reliability</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When compared to ceramic and fiberglass bases used for making printed circular boards, aluminum is more reliable and has fewer chances of being damaged. It is not fragile, like the other bases, and it is stronger than both ceramic and glass.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to that,&nbsp;</span><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Aluminum-PCB\">aluminum PCBs</a>&nbsp;</font></b>are suitable for high-pressure devices due to their strength and ability to withstand stress. These attributes make aluminum to be the most sought after material for making printed circular boards due to its quality and reliability.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>In Conclusion</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum printed circular boards have made a notable impact in the manufacturing of electronics and other appliances that generate a lot of heat. &nbsp;Their spectacular ability to conduct heat and transmit it away from critical parts of the device is what makes them stand out.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum is also non-toxic, readily available, and can be recycled as a means of conserving the environment. Not forgetting the versatility that comes with using aluminum for manufacturing a myriad of products. These advantages continue to make aluminum the perfect choice for making printed circular boards that are durable and reliable at the same time.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>    ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Advantages of aluminum PCB boards', 'aluminum PCB boards', '  Advantages of aluminum PCB boards  ', 0, '2019-12-04 11:33:05', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (66, '5_Things_You_Need_To_Know_About_PCB_Prototypes_66', '2019-12-02 09:28:52', NULL, 12, 0, 0, '     <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs are an integral part of the modern world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Making up a major component of the technologies widely used, they have become an indispensable part of our daily lives. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Invented several decades ago, one can find PCBs in a variety of forms, suited for their unique purpose. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And indeed, there are a lot of them out there, each of them with their own set of features and characteristics. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With the world of technology ever growing and expanding across the world, one could say that PCBs will continue to be widely used, adopted and remain a part of our lives for a long time to come., </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as this technology is commonplace, there is a lot that goes on behind the scenes, when it comes to their manufacture.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;One of the most important, and earliest stages of manufacturing PCBs, is that of their initial designs. It is very rare that companies start manufacturing PCBs in large quantities. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On the contrary, what really happens is that they prepare an initial draft and prepare a model based on that design, before putting it out for mass production. This initial design is what is known as a prototype, with the stage itself known as prototyping. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-03/PCB Prototype 5.jpg\" alt=\"PCB Prototype 5.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is much that can be said about the process of prototyping PCBs, and their use in various applications. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Given in the list are five things you need to know, about<font color=\"#1e90ff\">&nbsp;</font><o:p></o:p><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-prototype\"><b><font color=\"#1e90ff\">PCB prototypes</font></b></a><span>.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Reliability of the Design </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you have ever seen the prototypes are produced, you will notice one interesting thing. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>They are always manufactured in limited quantities. This holds true for PCBs, as much as for anything else. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is a reason for this. It is because of the fact that it is a prototype. In other words, it is but an early design, and something which isn’t certain in terms of performance and reliability. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is only when the early testing stages are cleared for prototypes, that you can get started with the actual design of the product. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>What this means for the end user, is that it is important that the designs be properly inspected, tested out and scrutinized, before being approved for widespread use. In addition to this, it is also a good idea to keep an eye out for any complaints by the end user, i.e. the consumer, if there are any issues that may arise in the future. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Widespread implementation can be a risky thing </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as there is a temptation to use the latest designs for your next purpose, you’ll still need to be careful on using them on a large scale. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is certainly true that the use of newer designs offer better performance. This is one of the main reasons why prototyping is done by manufacturers in the first place; to find a ‘better’ design that can help with the application it is meant for. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>At the same time however, using these prototype designs for widespread applications comes with its own set of risks. Given that there is no guarantee as to its performance, there is every chance that they may fail during use, either in short or the long run. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) The Cost Factor</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is one of the more important issues concerning the use of PCB prototypes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as prototyping is a necessity of sorts, it should be known that there is a cost factor involved, with regard to the entire process. From the design process to the final assembly, money is a necessity at every level. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is therefore necessary that one have sufficient finances to bear the cost of prototyping, for all the many inputs that are necessary; which includes among others, facility costs, laboratory costs, material expenses, salaries, support services, etc. Often clubbed together under the title of ‘Research &amp; Development’ or ‘R &amp; D’, it can prove to be an expensive affair if it isn’t budgeted properly. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, there may be the issue of the need for additional manufacturing equipment or other related changes, if there are any new additions made to an otherwise standardized PCB design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) The Issue of Integration </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To get started with a PCB prototype is one thing. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>But to produce it in large numbers, and make it work seamlessly with existing applications without issues is another. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Most of the present day technology available is made in a standardized format, meaning that they are expected to work with one set of technologies. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This would mean that the introduction of newer PCB designs might just not agree with the existing architecture of technologies. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In turn, one may find the need for the existing architecture and construction to be changed, in order to incorporate existing designs. Also, the changes being made might extend from the basic details of construction, to the other things like assemblies, power source, peripherals and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple words, there might just be a ‘domino effect’ of sorts, when using PCB prototypes. As a result, you might just have to change the design of everything else if one small change is made to the kind of PCBs being used. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Not All Manufacturers Have The Means for Prototyping &amp; Scaling Production </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something that has to do with the ability of a manufacturer to create prototypes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you’re in search of a manufacturer to make your PCB design a reality, you might want to check the details about the business you’ll be working with.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;Although there are many PCB manufactures around who can take care of your needs, not many are equipped for the preparation of the prototypes or early drafts. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is therefore important that, if you are interested in getting your design out, that you check with the manufacturer about their ability to create the first designs, before handing out contracts or signing deals. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another concern related to this, is that of scaling up production, where the prototype is approved for mass production. While most companies are prepared for large scale manufacture, others aren’t and would find it difficult to change their manufacturing processes for your specific requirement. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, it should be added that there are many more points in addition to the above, when it comes to prototype PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The above are but an introduction to the many interesting aspects of these prototypes, rather than something exhaustive in nature.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><br></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">If you want to know more about the PCB prototype, you can<b><font color=\"#1e90ff\">&nbsp;</font><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/blog/Introduction_to_PCB_Prototype_Assembly_63.html\">click here</a>&nbsp;</font></b>for details.</p>       ', 'PCB prototype ', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, '5 Things You Need To Know About PCB Prototypes', 'PCB Prototypes', '  5 Things You Need To Know About PCB Prototypes     ', 0, '2019-12-04 11:32:48', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (67, 'How_To_Choose_Aluminum_PCB_Manufacturers_67', '2019-12-03 09:28:35', NULL, 14, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most interesting types of PCBs or Printed Circuit Boards are that make use of Aluminum. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A component of very specific technological requirements, they are rather expensive, and often rarer to come across than other more conventional ones. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to manufacturers searching for suitable suppliers of the same, it can prove to be a difficult task.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Since the product is something that is in a ‘niche’ category of PCBs, it might be a difficult task when picking out a good supplier. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given in the list are some important things to consider, when choosing&nbsp;</span><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Aluminum-PCB\" style=\"\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">aluminum PCB manufacturers</font></a><font color=\"#cc0000\">&nbsp;</font></b>in China.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-03/Aluminum base PCB   .jpg\" alt=\"Aluminum base PCB   .jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Check the Company’s Credentials </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing that will really help you out, it would be to check the company’s credentials. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is a lot that can be found, by just figuring out the company’s credentials. These include things like the registration details of the company, its governmental records in cases where they are public, and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This in turn, will allow you know if the company is legitimate or not. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Try to Get a Sampling </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A sample is a great way to know what can be expected when you get the final shipment deliveries. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once you get the sample product, you can figure out whether it suits your needs, or if there is something else that would work out. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, you can also have the same integrated into your own products, to see how your own products work, to get an even better understanding. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to be noted is that the sample you get should have sufficient number of units, for you to inspect and check, before you make the final deal for a major shipment. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Ask for Customer References </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another important strategy that can be used to know the company better is to check for customer references.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;There is a lot that can be understood from a company’s customers, which range from the general behavior of the company, to the quality and timeliness its deliveries, as well as other things such as aspects of its aftercare and customer care services. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These should include everything from a company’s local clients to international ones. If possible, try to check out the products made by the clients, in order to get an idea of the performance quality of the PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Try to Organize a Factory Visit if You Can &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as it isn’t always possible, it is a good idea to check the facility where the product of your choice is being manufactured. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This will help you to better understand the kind of business you are working with, the degree of quality and attention being given to the manufacturing process, and any other queries that you might be having about the business. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Do note that you may have to spend your own money to reach the facilities, as it is not often that companies will sponsor you for a factory visit. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Try Out a ‘Test’ Shipment &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If everything seems to be alright and likely to work out, get started with a trial shipment. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You can get started with a bundle or two, and see how everything works out. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The term ‘everything’ here refers to things like the quality of the product, cost factor, reliability of the company, communication timeliness, shipment time and duration, aftercare services, customer care quality, billing, etc. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once you are satisfied that the business you are dealing with is reliable, larger quantities can be ordered. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) Take the Help of a Third Party Opinion </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you are in doubt about the quality of the products being delivered, you can always take the help of a third party opinion. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Sending a sample or two to a neutral party will help you get an honest and unbiased opinion on the kind of product you are dealing with, as well as any issues, changes or modifications that may be necessary. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These in turn, can be communicated to the supplier, and have the necessary steps taken up. Then again, it might be a reason to make other necessary changes as well, depending on the circumstance. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As difficult as it may seem, this isn’t going to be a difficult task. There are many companies that specialize in testing out products for the exact same purpose. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7.) A ‘Specialized’ Company is Better </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as all PCBs are the same at the end of the day, there are other things to be considered as well.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is because many companies only have a ‘general’ degree of specialization, rather than something specific. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This in turn will mean that, in the case of aluminum PCBs, you are far more likely to get a quality product from one that specializes in aluminum ones alone, rather than one which manufactures all varieties of the same. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>8.) Some Equipment/Technological Requirements of Aluminum PCB Manufacturers </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several technological requirements that have to be addressed, when it comes to PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of them most important is that the manufacturer needs to have a suitable UV light imaging equipment, or at least a setup that is capable of printing a suitable image. This image in turn, can be cured later on in an oven. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another requirement is that there has to be a specialized scoring equipment, which allows for the \'scoring\' of PCBs, which is the process in which the \'grooves\' are created on them. Regular scoring equipment does not allow for scoring on aluminum, and therefore requires the use of better equipment.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Furthermore, the business would also do fine if they had a good punching press, capable of creating the slots, holes and other features on the aluminum PCBs, given their structural strength, which is stronger in comparison to regular PCBs </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also, the company will do well to have a suitable Hipot test, which is used for electrical testing of the PCBs, and their performance quality.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In all, the above list should give you an idea on how to go about with the process of finding the right kind of suppliers for the aluminum PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While there are indeed many, it should help you complete your purchases, and get started with your business within no time.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How To Choose Aluminum PCB Manufacturers', 'Aluminum PCB Manufacturer', ' How To Choose Aluminum PCB Manufacturers ', 0, '2019-12-04 11:32:34', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (68, 'What_Are_The_Advantages_Of_China\'s_PCB_Prototype_68', '2019-12-04 11:19:21', NULL, 9, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs have been used for quite some time, in the world of electronics. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From small scale technologies to large scale needs, PCBs have become an indispensable part of the modern age. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs, or printed circuit boards, are one of the most commonly used components in technologies everywhere.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And when it comes to the subject of manufacturing PCBs, one of the largest manufacturers of it all is China. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Ever since the country took off to become the manufacturing center of the world, companies have thronged to it to manufacture everything that you could possibly imagine, and that certainly holds true for PCBs as well. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-04/PCB Prototype 4 (2).jpg\" alt=\"PCB Prototype 4 (2).jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-align: center;\">There is much that can be said about the subject of PCBs made in China.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The advantages of&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-prototype\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Chinese PCB prototypes</font></a>&nbsp;are certainly plenty.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the most important ones are given in the points mentioned below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) The Cost Factor </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many reasons why China has become a manufacturing hub in the world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most important is that of the cost factor. In comparison to other parts of the world, manufacturing costs tend to be cheaper, due to the lower wages, international exchange rates, government policies that encourage businesses and so on.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>What this means for the average technology user, is that using PCBs from China will work out to be a cheaper option in comparison to those manufactured from elsewhere. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Quality of the PCBs </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing that China has got a bad rap for, it is about the quality of Chinese goods. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It has become rather common knowledge that Chinese goods are not up to the mark, for a variety of reasons. While this is certainly true in many cases, it isn’t certainly the case all the time.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In fact, many of the most reputable companies manufacture their goods in China, and ship it to the world, including those companies which engage in the manufacture of gadgets and other devices. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Depending on the company you work with, you should be able to get the best quality product in the entire world, with no ‘defect’ or other ‘quality issues’ to speak of. In addition to this, many of the companies take that extra step, by offering quality guarantees, after-sales services and more. Depending on the client you are working with, you could get something that lasts several years as well in this regard. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Research &amp; Development </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another thing which is very important in the world of technology is that of research and development. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple words, it is the kind of work that is done to ensure the quality of a product, as well as make newer advances about the same. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For a long time, China remained merely a manufacturing hub for the world, only working on assignments given by foreign companies. In recent times however, things have changed for the better, with more companies investing in research and development, for improving the quality of their products. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Connectivity &amp; Shipping </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A major issue when it comes to overseas manufacturing and suppliers is that of delivery. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has been a problem all throughout history, with a question on how to get goods from one place to another, as soon as possible. And indeed, people came up with a variety of ways to achieve these goals, ranging from horse carts to the earliest of ships. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For a very long time, shipping goods form one part of the world to another, proved to be a tremendous challenge, due to the lack of technology, infrastructure and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With these things having been changed through improvements made in recent times, there is almost no issue with regard to shipping, of the prototype as well as that of large scale production. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Likewise, improvements in communications technology, whether of satellites or the internet, has helped bridge the gap even more, with the time reduced from more than a month to less than a few minutes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>All of these things mean that you should be able to stay in touch with the manufacturers and suppliers, without any real hassles. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Flexibility of Manufacturing </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A major concern for the manufacture of PCB prototypes is that of the manufacturing facility’s flexibility. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is only when a facility has flexibility that it can fully carry out the requirements placed for the manufacture of a PCB prototype. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something which is of a major concern to companies everywhere, given that these components often come with very strict and specific requirements, in order to function the way they are expected to. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For a long time, China lacked the kind of state-of-the-art facilities required for the manufacture of these facilities. This has however changed dramatically, with facilities available that provide for the kind of customization one expects for PCB prototypes. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to note is the fact that Chinese companies have been doing businesses with a variety of customers across the world, in various sectors of the economy. This means that the companies offering PCBs in China are very likely experienced in the kind of services that they offer, and can be easily implemented for a variety of applications with ease. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) Potential for Scalability </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another important issue when it comes to the issue of manufacturing PCB prototypes is that of scalability. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is one thing to create a few pieces and have them ready for use. But it is a completely different story when one wants to have the same done on a massive scale. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is something that many Chinese companies can take care of, given that the facilities are often integrated factories, where large quantities of units can be mass produced as per the client’s requirement. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>So whether it is a small scale requirement, or something that has to be produced in large numbers, this is something that you should be able to take care of with relative ease. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To sum up, the above are some good reasons on the ways in which Chinese companies can help out, when it comes to PCB prototypes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>So if you are interested in working with a Chinese PCB prototype projects, the above are something to consider, and the starting point that you can get started with. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>   ', 'PCB prototype ', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Advantages Of China\'s PCB Prototype', 'PCB Prototype', ' Advantages Of China\'s PCB Prototype ', 0, '2019-12-04 11:22:48', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (69, 'Things_You_Need_To_Know_About_Aluminum_PCBs_69', '2019-12-05 11:39:11', NULL, 5, 0, 0, '<p><!--5f39ae17-8c62-4a45-bc43-b32064c9388a:--></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most important pieces of technology around to have ever been created is that of the PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Created in an effort to replace redundant wires, they have become an important mainstay of the technological world around us. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is much that can be said about the PCBs, or Printed Circuit Boards. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of it all, one thing that clearly stands out is the way this piece of technology has evolved, into the myriad of forms that it can be found in today. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One such kinds of PCBs which have become widespread in use, is that of Aluminum PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Called so because of the nature of the element used in their construction, they have been in use since the 1970s, and play a key role in the many technological advances that are used in our daily lives. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is a lot that can be said about aluminum PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Details of the same are listed out in the points below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-05/Aluminum PCB FOR Taiya 4000  ink .jpg\" alt=\"Aluminum PCB FOR Taiya 4000  ink .jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) The General Design is a Three or Four-Layered Structure </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most important things to know about aluminum PCBs is about their general design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although variations certainly exist, the most common design of the PCBs that can be found is made up of a four-layered structure.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These include two layers below that are made purely of aluminum, on which there is a layer of dielectric material, and finally, a layer of copper. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The aluminum layer in turn, is comprised of a ‘base membrane’, which acts as a foundation, on which there is what is called a ‘base layer’. Then again, the two might be replaced by a single surface instead. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) The Heat Dissipation Advantage</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the main reasons why aluminum PCBs are used, is because of their capacity to dissipate heat. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In many electronics, heating is a major problem, which if not treated, can have untoward consequences. This is something which the use of aluminum PCBs can resolve rather easily. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given that the material eliminates the heat quickly, there is less likelihood for damage to the circuitry, or for that matter the entire device or system. In turn, it helps to extend the lifespan of the electronics, often by several times what would be the case otherwise. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) The Dimensional Stability of Aluminum PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The heating of metals has an ‘expanding’ effect on them, in which the metal ‘expands’ on being exposed to a source of heat. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the case of electronics, there is always a great deal of heat being produced and accumulated, during use. This heat in turn, can lead to the expansion of the metal components of the PCBs, and thereby lead to their damage in the long run.</span></p><p style=\"display: inline !important;\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b>Aluminum PCBs&nbsp;</b></font></p>offer an interesting advantage in this regard, as there is almost no expansion, even at slightly higher temperatures. For example, the heating of aluminum from 30°C to 140°C, only leads to an expansion of around 2.5-3%.<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>What this means for the circuitry is that the overall structural integrity is far more likely to be safe, in comparison to those that don’t use aluminum in their construction and design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) LED Applications are One of the Biggest Users of Aluminum PCBs</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum PCBs have a variety of applications. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most important is that of LED lighting, which makes up a significant source of demand for aluminum PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These include everything from traffic signals and street lights to home lighting, and even the circuits inside monitors and televisions. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple words, they can and are used for just about any applications, where the primary purpose is lighting via the use of LEDs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Of course, there are other applications as well for aluminum PCBs, such as high power scanners, power converters, general circuitry, etc.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Manufacturing Aluminum PCBs can Prove to be a Challenge</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As advantageous as PCBs may be, there are issues with regard to their manufacture. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is because the construction of PCBs tends to require a greater degree of effort, in comparison to other designs. To be more specific, there are two main challenges, when it comes to the manufacture of aluminum PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most important of all is that aluminum PCBs have very thick copper layers, meaning that the degree of etching and other finishes are much more intense, than it is in the case of other PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) They may be Expensive to Use </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although they are widespread in terms of applications, you may have to deal with higher prices, especially with regard to specific uses. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7.) It is not Always Pure Aluminum Being Used </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as the name may suggest, it is not always pure aluminum being used. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On the contrary, the actual material being used may be an alloy of aluminum. While there are certainly a variety of alloys that are used, one of the most important is that of aluminum, magnesium and silumin, the latter of which is an alloy of silicon and aluminum. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This however may not always be the case. Whether the material being used is pure aluminum or an alloy, is usually dependent on the exact nature of the application, its requirement, and the budget of the clientele and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>8.) Aluminum PCBs are Relatively Eco-Friendly </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A very good advantage of aluminum PCBs is that they are eco-friendly, in comparison to other PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is because, in addition to requiring lower levels of energy to manufacture, they are easier to recycle and dispose. It is in simple words, a lot easier to recycle a metal like aluminum, in comparison to many of the other materials that are in use today. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>9.) Aluminum PCBs are Cheaper to Manufacture </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given that one of the primary materials used for their manufacture, aluminum, is available in the earth’s crust in abundance, the cost of manufacturing the same is quite less. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This makes them quite affordable in general, although depending on the applications and specific requirements, this may not always be the case. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Last but not the least, it should be added that there are indeed many more things in addition to the above, when it comes to aluminum PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The above are to be considered as a starting point on getting to know the basics about aluminum PCBs, its strengths and limitations, and nothing more.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Things You Need To Know About Aluminum PCBs', 'Aluminum PCBs', '  Things You Need To Know About Aluminum PCBs', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (70, 'What_Is_an_Aluminum_PCB_70', '2019-12-06 09:53:05', NULL, 8, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs or Printed Circuit Boards have been around for a quite some time. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Ever since the technological revolution began a few decades ago, there has been a marked use of PCBs everywhere. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This rise has certainly been something of a leap for electronics. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Rather than having inefficient wires do the work, it was found that using printed circuit proved to be a better alternative. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And indeed, PCBs are today being used for a variety of technological applications, ranging from toys to satellites, and everything in between. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is understandable as to why they are popular. The lack of wires, complex designs and general sturdiness makes for a very desirable technological option. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the early days of PCBs, the technology was still evolving, with no clear understanding on the ‘right way’ to design it all. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With the passage of time however, things started to become better, with changes being applied to everything from construction to the materials of choice. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The process is certainly continuing right now, given the amount of research and development going on around the world. &nbsp;One interesting PCB design that came out of works like these, and others, was that of the aluminum PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As the name would suggest, aluminum PCBs have their basic constructions around the element Aluminum. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The reason for the usage of Aluminum is several, which makes them far more useful that PCBs made using other materials. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although they may sound like revolutionary pieces of technology, they are really old, and have been around for decades. One of the earliest uses of Aluminum PCBs was in the 1970s, when the element started to be used for PCB applications.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;The metal was chosen because it was found to be very efficient for conducting electricity, easy to work with and had great thermal conductivity. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-06/multilayer Aluminum    (1).jpg\" alt=\"multilayer Aluminum    (1).jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">There is much that can be said about<font color=\"#1e90ff\">&nbsp;</font><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Aluminum-PCB\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">aluminum PCBs</font></a></b>.Of it all, some of the most important details about the same, are explained in the points below.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) The Name Suggests the Nature of the Design </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As the name would suggest, aluminum PCBs are made using aluminum. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The material is in fact used for a variety of reasons, which will be explained further below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to be added here is that the material used need not always be pure aluminum. On the contrary, the material of choice is often that of an alloy of aluminum, often containing materials such as magnesium and silicon.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>But it is to be understood that the many properties of the metal is the reason why it is chosen for the purpose. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, it should also be known that there are other materials that are used as well in the manufacture of this variety of PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) The Common Design is a Three or Four Layered One </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While this is not always the case, the fact is that aluminum PCBs tend to come in a design characterized by three or four layers. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>At the bottom, one can find one or two layers of aluminum, on top of which there is a layer of dielectric material. On the top of it all, is a layer of copper. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As already mentioned, this is but the general design that is used for aluminum PCBs. There may be applications in which the exact structure may be changed, in favor of something else. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) The Main Reasons for Using Aluminum </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several reasons for the usage of aluminum in these PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most important of all is the fact that the metal has a good potential for conducting electricity, has the ability to dissipate heat quickly, and a relatively low degree of expansion on exposure to heat. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first advantage, i.e. of having a high degree of conductivity, is great given that it helps to make the circuit energy efficient, and therefore faster.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The ability to dissipate heat on the other hand, allows for the circuits to last longer, given that the heat is lost from the assembly fast enough as to not cause any damage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The low degree of expansion on the other hand, allows for the circuit to last longer, as there is little to no structural damage, caused by long term use of the same. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) The Cost Factor </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While the use of aluminum PCBs may be expensive, the more general designs tend to be cheaper to manufacture and design.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A key reason for this is that the material being used, aluminum is fairly cheap in comparison to other metals in the marketplace. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As a whole however, the pricing of aluminum PCBs in most cases tend to be relatively cheap, making them an economic choice to go for. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) They are Durable &amp; Lightweight </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another reason why aluminum PCBs make for a great pick, is because they are lightweight and durable, both of which are the characteristics of aluminum. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Aluminum is generally known as a lightweight material, which is why it has found large scale applications in the manufacture of aircrafts and helicopter. In addition to this, it also offers a high degree of structural strength, making it an ideal choice for applications that require structural integrity and strength. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The two characteristics in turn, mean that this variety of PCBs, are excellent for a variety of uses. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) The Applications for Aluminum PCBs are Very Specific </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although aluminum PCBs can and are used for a variety of applications, one of the most important uses of the same is in the case of LEDs and other lighting applications.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In fact, almost all technologies that use LED based lighting technologies are made possible because of aluminum PCBs in their assemblies. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The exact usage of the same includes everything from traffic lights to surgical lights, and indeed even the latest LED monitors and televisions. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><br></span><span>To sum up, aluminum PCBs are one of the more specialized forms of PCBs, used for very specific applications.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is indeed a lot more that can be said about this technology in addition to that which is mentioned above. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Think of the above as a rough introduction to this concept, and feel free to look up on the same for further understanding about this interesting piece of technology.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'What Is an Aluminum PCB', 'Aluminum PCB', '   What Is an Aluminum PCB ', 0, '2019-12-06 10:04:47', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (71, 'PCB_LAYOUT_AND_PCB_LAYOUT_SOFTWARE_71', '2019-12-07 15:43:07', NULL, 9, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit boards are small components that are used in our everyday electronics to help them function correctly. Without printed circuit boards, you couldn’t watch television, play your favorite video game, or even call or text your friends on your phone.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although circuit boards are small, they play an important role. In this post, you will learn why the layout of a printed circuit board is important, why you should use a PCB software to layout your design, and a few good PCB layout software features as well as a few software options that are available for purchase now.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-07/Standard PCB LAYOUT.jpg\" alt=\"Standard PCB LAYOUT.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHY YOUR LAYOUT IS IMPORTANT</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs are incredibly small and fragile. Because of this, there are a number of reasons why the layout of a PCB is so important.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Heat distribution is one of the most important aspects of PCB design. Printed circuit boards are a lot like the human nervous system. Signals are sent throughout the printed circuit board using electricity. When a PCB is poorly designed, it can lead to a number of heat distribution problems.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several problems that can lead to problems with overheating. First, if the lines or pathways are too small for the amount of energy being pushed through them, it can cause the PCB to overheat. This is because the PCB is forcing a lot of energy through a very small space. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Secondly, component placement can influence the heat distribution within the PCB. If one side of the PCB has a lot more components than the other side, a lot of energy is flowing to that side. This means that this side of the board is overloaded and can cause heating issues.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Heating issues are often solved by the inclusion of a fan to keep PCBs cool.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Wiring is another issue when it comes to the importance of<b>&nbsp;</b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-layout\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b>PCB layout</b></font></a>. Without properly laying out your components, it can be nearly impossible to have space to attach wires. That’s why creating a mock layout and laying out your components is so important. You don’t want to realize that you don’t have room for your wires when you’re halfway done placing and soldering your components.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, the signal integrity is an important reason why care should be taken in designing a PCB. What good is the circuit board if there are electrical problems that interfere with sending signals to the device?</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Routing the traces in a certain way is important to avoiding this issue. Basically, traces should be routed parallel and close to one another. This reduces the amount of noise and interference, so the PCB can operate to its fullest potential.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although these three are not the only reasons why PCB layout is important, they are among the most important reasons. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHY YOU SHOULD USE A PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you know why PCB layout is so important to the integrity of the printed circuit board and the device it helps power; you need to know why a PCB layout software can be beneficial.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first reason is that using a software can remove some human error that occurs during the design process. When you design something on your own, you have to rely on your own math and your own vision. Software can take the guesswork out of the process and can help to make sure that measurements and calculations are accurate. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another reason is that the software can give you a schematic that you can work off of during the design process. This will give you a roadmap to creating a perfect printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, some design software can actually simulate what it would be like to have your design work in a certain environment. This can help you determine what changes you may need to make in order to create the best PCB for the device you’re making it for.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>GOOD PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE FEATURES AND SOME SUGGESTIONS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are a ton of options out there when it comes to PCB layout software. The options are nearly limitless. That is why it is important to make sure that the design software that you purchase or use is one that has the following features:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>An easy-to-use interface:</span></b><span>&nbsp;You don’t need to pay a ton of money for a software that has a difficult interface. Find one that is easy to use and won’t take long to understand.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Contains a large library of components:</span></b><span>&nbsp;As a technician, you don’t necessarily know what components a customer will need before they order. That is why your software should have the ability for you to add various components to your design. This can help you to know where the component should be soldered and how to best lay out the components for optimal heat distribution.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Design automation:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Sometimes, it helps to have an automated design that is available with the click of a button. This can take out a ton of work and can save you time. If need be, you should be able to move around these automated components in your software to fit your need.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Cost effective:</span></b><span>&nbsp;As you can imagine, software used to design anything can be pretty expensive. Software options available now range from free to nearly $7,000. You must compare the features and benefits of each software to determine what the best option is for you.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you know some key features you should look for, here are some of the top PCB design software on the market and some of their specifications:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>DipTrace Full:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $995 and has no limits in what you can do.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Eagle:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $65 a month or $500 a year and has no limits.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Altium Designer:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $7,245 and has no limits. This one is often heralded as the best PCB design software available today.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>DipTrace Starter:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $75 and has a 300 pin and two signal layer limit.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>EasyEDA:</span></b><span>&nbsp;This is a free software with no limits.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now you know all you need to know about PCB layouts and the best layout software available!</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'PCB LAYOUT AND PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE', 'PCB LAYOUT', '  PCB LAYOUT AND PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (72, 'How_to_use_PCB_safely_72', '2019-12-10 15:57:19', NULL, 5, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the old days, when technology was not accessible, many technicians fixed all parts of an electronic device by soldering them to each other. Today, Printed Circuit Boards have changed the game, making it easier and cheaper. PCBs are thin boards that connect electric components in an electronic device. The board contains insulating material, which has a metal-coated surface. Electricians mount multiple parts into the PCB using solder. However, you must use acid to make etches in the metal so that electric power can travel through the parts of the electronic appliance. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-10/BGA PCB.jpg\" alt=\"BGA PCB.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>This article gives you essential tips on how to use&nbsp;</span></i></b><font color=\"#1e90ff\" style=\"font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com\">PCB</a>&nbsp;</font><b><i>safely.</i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>1. Keep everything organized. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>People who are new to wiring find it challenging to work with Printed Circuit Boards. However, if you are can organize your work correctly, the process will be easy. Each electronic project has different kits that you need to put together. These kits come with a checklist showing the parts you need to connect. During the designing process, you should tick off each step you complete as you go through the process. Besides, you should audit every part in the kit before you begin your project. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Sometimes the process may seem to be sophisticated due to the tiny pieces and several solder joints that you need to lay onto an over squeezed PCB. Take your time to set up your PCB project, and follow all the instructions to avoid complications. If you properly plan your work, you will avoid facing problems in your project.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>2. Keep your Board Clean. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Many people may wonder how and why you need to clean your circuit. Nevertheless, to make your PCB safe to work on, always include cleaning in your work plan. For better results, clean your PCB before and after you populate the board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Well-scrubbed copper requires less heat when applying solder, and hence before soldering, you must first scrub or de-oxidize your PCB. An abrasive provides good results; you may try a Scotch Brite and isopropyl Alcohol. You may also use a glass fiber pen for lousy corrosion. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>3. Low-High Populating. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Overpopulating PCBs may leave you with little or no room for soldering the parts on the board. The best way to make the process more effective is to have a prior plan on how you will populate your board. Arrange your components, starting with the low parts in ascending order. This formula prevents the more massive parts from blocking the way when installing low-lying ones next to each other. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>4. Use Tweezers to hold small items. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you want to make the process perfect and avoid hurting your fingers when soldering, you need to have some tweezers with you. The use of tweezers saves the time you need to install the components. Surface-mount parts are often tiny, and you may not be able to add them to the board with your fingers. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>5. Use a bending Tool. &nbsp;</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The bending tools are often given as a complimentary when you purchase the electronics kitty, so you may not need to pay an extra cost. &nbsp;Using a component lead tool will ensure that you have the right lead width. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>6. Use a Magnifying Glass. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A magnifying or a loupe glass is a crucial tool in the electronic field. &nbsp;You need this equipment to help you identify problems such as solder bridges. You may not be able to identify some issues using your naked eyes, so the loupe glass comes in handy. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>7. Use Poster Putty. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A poster putty helps you in holding small pieces together when working with them. This device makes it easier when assembling small components rather than doing it with your hands. You may use the device to press PCBs on it without leaving any residue. You may always clean the board after the process. This tool will help you in many situations when working with PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>8. Fasten your headers on the Breadboard. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A breadboard helps you fix the header pins perfectly on your PCB. The Breadboard enables you to hold the items intact as you set them on the board. By inserting the pins on the Breadboard, and putting the PCB on the top, you can then fit the pins through your circuit board holes and fill them with solder. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>9. Glue your Standoffs. </span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You need to glue your standoffs inside the box to hold your PCB firmly. &nbsp;However, make sure not to screw the aluminum stands through the board. Glue them in such a way that in case you need to swap the board, you can unscrew the board. The glue holds the standoffs strong enough to function permanently. However, in case you need to change the box, you can rub alcohol on the glued areas to remove the glue. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Currently, PCBs are everywhere. Almost every electronic appliance has a PCB. As such, electricians need to create PCBs that are safe for end-users.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'How to use PCB safely', 'PCB', '  How to use PCB safely', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (73, 'Flexible_printed_circuit_boards:_TYPES,_BENEFITS,_AND_THEIR_APPLICATIONS_73', '2019-12-11 15:38:04', NULL, 7, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>&nbsp;are a subset of printed circuit boards that are bendable. This allows them to conform to various spaces.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In this article, you will learn everything you need to know about </span><span>Flexible printed circuit board</span><span>s, including the various types of designs, the benefits of using them, and how they are used in devices today.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>TYPES OF </span></b><b><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are five main types of </span><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>&nbsp;desi</span><span>a</span><span>gns. Each have their own use and application.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first type of </span><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>&nbsp;is the single-sided flexible circuit. This design has one conductor layer that is composed of metal or some other conductive material. It is created on a dielectric film to make it flexible. Although single-sided flexible circuits can be made with or without a protective coating, most manufacturers opt to add one. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Next, there is the double-sided flexible circuits. These circuits have two layers made of a conductive material. At times, these circuits contain holes where components can be placed and soldered. Since the components are laying within the material, it maintains its flexibility.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The third type is a sculptured flexible circuit. Much as the name implies, these are sculpted in a more unusual fashion, but they still remain flexible. The thickness of the conductive material will vary in this type of flexible circuit.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Next is the multilayer flexible circuit. As the name suggests, this type has multiple layers of conductive material, usually about three extra layers. In many cases, areas that don’t contain holes for components are laminated. This is meant to allow areas that do need to bend to stay bent while attempting to keep other areas more rigid.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, there is the rigid-flex circuit. This design is more of a hybrid of sorts, as it has parts that are flexible as well as a part that looks much like a traditional printed circuit board. These flexible, but stiff, circuits usually have extra conductor layers.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Those are the five main types of<font color=\"#1e90ff\">&nbsp;</font><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Flexible-PCBs\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Flexible printed circuit&nbsp;boards</font></a></b>. I’m sure you are wondering how these flexible circuits are used in today’s electronics, but you will learn about that later. First, you need to know why it is beneficial to use Flexible printed circuit boards.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-11/Flexible PCBs.jpg\" alt=\"Flexible PCBs.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>BENEFITS OF USING A </span></b><b><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin, there are far fewer assembly issues when it comes to creating </span><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>&nbsp;and implementing them into the device they will help to power. This is because a lot of the processes for creating the flexible circuits are automated, leaving little room for human error. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is also much cheaper and faster to created </span><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>. This is because assembly is automated, so it is quicker, and it costs less to have a software do this rather than hiring someone to do this.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As the name implies, flexibility matters in a lot of devices. Many complex devices such as laptops and gaming systems must house a number of components inside a compact plastic shell. The flexibility of these circuits allow them to fold into corners and around other components so they can fit in compact areas.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The flexible circuits are also able to absorb vibration and impact a lot better than a traditional printed circuit board. Because these circuits are laminated and flexible, unlike their more rigid counterparts, falls and hits don’t impact them as badly. This means that they are less likely to break and cause further issues down the line.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Because they are laminated and flexible, these circuits are also able to withstand environmental threats. This means that they are less likely to be damaged by extreme heat or water damage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another benefit is that, in pretty much every case, the components that would traditionally go on a printed circuit board are actually embedded into the flexible circuits so they can maintain their flexibility and still do the job. This means that you are less likely to have an issue relating to bad soldering of a component.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, flexible circuits are super thin. These circuits can be as thin as 0.004 inches. Because of their thin nature, they are able to withstand high temperatures and are also designed to help with spacing issues inside of larger devices.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>HOW </span><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>&nbsp;ARE USED</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Before you learn about how some of these </span><span>Flexible printed circuit board</span><span>s are used in various products, you should know that there are two main types of applications for </span><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first is static application. This means that the circuit is installed to fit into a specific area. The circuit is bent one time. This process is called “flex to fit.”</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The second type of application is dynamic flexing application. This means that the circuit is bent many times to be applied to the device it will power. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you know the types of application, it is time to learn where many of these flexible circuits end up. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Everyday electronics:</span></b><span>&nbsp;These include things like your LED television, your laptop and computer keyboard, printers, cell phones and smartphones, and cameras.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Need-specific electronics:</span></b><span>&nbsp;These are electronics that you reach for when you need them. These can include calculators and GPS systems.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Medical electronics:</span></b><span>&nbsp;These are electronic devices that are used to improve or even remedy medical various medical conditions that a patient may be experiencing. Some of the common ones include hearing aids and pacemakers. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Military electronics:</span></b><span>&nbsp;The military has specific electronic equipment that is optimized for military service. They are designed to be compact and easily transportable. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These are only a few of the several items that use </span><span>Flexible printed circuit board</span><span>s. Without these types of circuits, many electronic devices would be bulky and fragile.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>CONCLUSION</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Flexible printed circuit boards</span><span>&nbsp;are small components that make a big impact on the capabilities of many everyday electronic devices. Their flexibility and thinness makes them a viable option for smaller, more compact devices, as they can easily bend to fit the space and can withstand a large amount of heat without becoming defective.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Flexible printed circuit boards: TYPES, BENEFITS, AND THEIR APPLICATIONS', 'Flexible printed circuit boards', ' Flexible printed circuit boards: TYPES, BENEFITS, AND THEIR APPLICATIONS ', 0, '2019-12-11 15:56:53', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (74, 'Printed_Circuit_Board_Guide_74', '2019-12-13 09:52:50', NULL, 5, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Have you ever thought of making your own robot, computer or other form of electronic devices, the first thing you need is to create a Printed Circuit Board</span><span>? </span><span>Paul Eisle invented PCB in 1936. Today, technology has become the linchpin for almost all the wired devices we use, e.g., cars, computers, cell phones, and so on. In any electronic device whose work involves computation, there are high chances that PCB is used. The technology coordinates all the electronic signals to meet the intended purpose of that device. The technology plays the role of the brain in most of the electronic devices we use today.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs contain a unique glass-reinforced epoxy laminate material. They are green in color, but may also contain other colors too. The board is physically smooth and decorated, but it has some other built-in parts.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-13/High Density PCBs .jpg\" alt=\"High Density PCBs .jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>Here are some of the things you need when making the PCB</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Design Schematics</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is the initial step; before creating a CPB, you must first have a clear idea of how you want to use it. The schematic will be your framework on the PCB layout. You may either borrow a readily designed schematics diagram or create one from scratch. The first thing is to draw the circuit on a paper, then create it on a design tool, e.g., Cadsoft eagle.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Board&nbsp;</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-layout\" style=\"font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">Layout</font></a></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you have the schematics drawn in your design tool, you need to draw the circuit board. You need to create a structure of the wires that connect different parts. The process is something like a game of “connecting-the-dots,” you may have enjoyed sometimes in your life.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When creating the diagram circuit, you have already set the different parts that need to connect. You now need to join all the dots to connect different parts that need to work together, and the program will then show if everything is working correctly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Getting the board done</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>After drawing the structure, it is now time to create the board. You may create it from your diagram or look for a professional manufacturer to create it for you.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>Manufacturing Printed Circuit Board</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If you are wondering how you can make a custom PCB, the first step is to have CAD software installed </span><span>on</span><span>&nbsp;your computer. You then need to come up with the PCB prototype.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Then you need to print the circuit diagram on the board using a photosensitive coating. After this step, you need to etch out the undesired copper from the board to form copper traces. This process is known as photoengraving.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are two other methods for making traces. Silkscreen printing uses etch-resistant paint to cover the areas where the copper traces will be applied. The other way is PCB milling, which uses CNC machines to remove the unwanted copper.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>After applying the copper track on the board, drill the holes to create a path for assembling the electronic parts. Special Tungsten Carbide drill bits are the most appropriate for drilling the holes. You must then coat the holes to create a connection between different layers.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Coating</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Here you need to cover the board entirely, leaving the holes and pads. You can use materials like lead solder or cop</span><span>p</span><span>er. The last step is screen-printing, which involves printing the text on the PCB.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Testing Of PCB</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Before joining the parts or delivering the circuit boards, you need to do a thorough test to look for shorts or opens that may result in malfunction. A short indicates that there are some undesired connections, while an open indicates a disconnection between two parts that ought to have been connected. Ensure that such errors are rectified before the PCB assembly. Please note that not all shops test their boards before shipping them. Although it may increase the costs, testing is important, because it confirms that the board is fully functional before adding other components.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span><p><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-Assembly/PCB-Assembly-Overview\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">PCB Assembly</font></a></p></span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the board is complete, you can assemble the parts to match the circuit diagram. The mostly used assembly methods include through-hole construction and surface-mount construction. You may apply a combination of the two methods for assembly</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><span>Types of Printed Circuit Boards</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Single-Sided Board</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is one of the simple PCBs, which contain only a single substrate. All the components are attached on one side while the copper traces are fixed on the other side.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Double-Sided Board</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is the most common type of PCB, which has parts attached on both sides of the substrate. &nbsp;The two-sided PCBs use through-hole model for the assembly of parts</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><i><span>Multi-Layered Board</span></i></b><b><i><span><o:p></o:p></span></i></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has different layers of substrate divided by insulation. The&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Multilayer-PCBs\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">multilayered boards</font></a>&nbsp;are rarely used unless for very complex electronic circuits.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs may contain between two layers to forty-two layers, for electronics with more sophisticated technology. It is important to do a thorough analysis and understand the role that the PCB is intended to perform in a device before determining the number of layers to use.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Printed Circuit Board Guide', 'Printed Circuit Board', 'Printed Circuit Board Guide', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (75, 'Why_Are_Circuit_Boards_Usually_Green_75', '2019-12-16 11:34:42', NULL, 7, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>You might have noticed that almost all circuit boards are green in color. Have you ever wondered why that is so? Why is it that all the circuit boards come in green color and not in some other color? Well, green is the signature color of the circuits board, and there are a huge science and logic behind this color. Those who work with circuit boards very often do ponder about the soldier-green coating on them. Therefore, there is not one single reason behind the logic of the circuit board being green in color. Many experts have given their logical explanation about these having green color. These reasons are discussed below.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-16/telecommunication PCB.jpg\" alt=\"telecommunication PCB.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Background History of Deciding the Green Color:</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There is a little background history as well that why green color is the standard color of the Circuit boards. This is because the green color seemed considerable and acceptable for the eyes of the assemblers. It looked effective to the assemblers when they say the tracks of the circuit board. Before green color, the original color of it was in shades of brownish-yellow and the hardener was a darker shade of brown. When the shade was mixed it gave a shade of honey brown that did not seem acceptable to the assemblers. Then they tried to add a little bit of red color but it made the shade look more dark brown. Then they tried adding more yellow which turned into this shade of dark green. It seems acceptable to everyone and successfully became the standard color. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Reasons to why Circuit Boards Green in Color:</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>There are multiple reasons told by different experts that why the circuit boards are usually green in color. These different reasons are discussed below:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>The Glass Epoxy Material: </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Glass Epoxy is a material that was used in manufacturing the solder mask of the circuit boards. This material used to come in a green color that became the standard color for all the assemblers in the industries to use the same Glass Epoxy. By the time, there were also some colors introduced for Glass Epoxy but the assemblers always considered using the green color one. This trend of green color, due to it being so common, became cost-effective too. That is why some experts say that the Glass Epoxy is one of the reasons why the circuit boards are always green in color.</span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>The Contrast of Green Color with the White printed text: </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Assemblers often find it easy and less time-consuming in scanning the green circuit boards because they are already habitual and pretty familiar with this color. They say that takes a lot of time to scan circuit boards of some different color. Another reason is that the green color creates less strain on the eyes while scanning as compared to other colors. The green color is used because it also contrasts the text printed in white on the routing of the circuit board. That is why the line workers prefer using green color while scanning the circuit board</span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>The Color Green used for Military Purpose: </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Some researches were based on this that how military standards were a great influence in the green color of the circuit boards. This all started in the USA that the military of the USA considered this green color to be highly effective in the circuit boards that were also used for military purposes. The military demanded the green circuit boards form the suppliers who also supplied to other customers. These circuit boards were becoming a surplus for the suppliers form the military eventually. So not only the assemblers, line workers or other clients consider the green color, the military forces also accept the green color of the circuit boards.</span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>The Rate of Exposure with the Solder Mask: </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>A higher solder rate is required for the circuit boards. There are other colors too but they do not provide a higher solder mask for the circuit board. Those colors which have dark shades like blue, white or brown have high pigmentation and therefore they have dark-colored solder masks. Mostly the white and black solder masks are high in exposure rate. But the green color provides a dark shade for the exposure rate to the workers and high tolerance in the design. </span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span>Some Other Colors of the Circuit Boards: </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Circuit boards come in different colors and have different colors of solder masks as well. The colors mostly differentiate between multiple popular brands and companies that produce and manufacture them. The colors are decided during the production process, once it is observed that the colors meet all the criteria, and are acceptable by the assemblers. Many manufacturers and assemblers also use other dark colors as an alternative to green colored solder masks. Some alternative colors that are considered are as follows:</span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>The white-colored solder masks are also created by some companies due to the shade and appearance. They are used especially for models to be shown. Now the question arises that how can the print of the white text be visible. Well, for this to be visible the black color is used for the silkscreen as it stands out boldly and perfectly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>The black&nbsp;</span><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"www.pcbonline.com\">print circuit boards</a>&nbsp;</font>are also used as they make it easy to see the labeling. The black color also absorbs heat big time.</p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Some assemblers also go for the red colored circuit boards because of the appealing color. The color gives a fresh vibe and due to this, they consider red color as an alternative to green color.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>The high rate of exposure to contrast is found in the blue-colored circuit boards. These circuit boards handle the applications well and that is why they are considered as an alternative label.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"justify\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The above-mentioned reasons were given by different experts and even the assemblers who manufacture the circuit boards. There is therefore not one main reason as to why the circuit boards are usually green in color. These reasons, however, have logic and scientific reasons why most customers and manufacturers consider green color.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'Why Are Circuit Boards Usually Green', 'Circuit Boards', '  Why Are Circuit Boards Usually Green', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (76, 'LED_PCB_-The_Most_Useful_Introduction_76', '2019-12-17 13:57:38', NULL, 8, 0, 0, '  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>LED PCBs play a major role in modern society. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Used in a wide range of applications, it could be said that they help run the present era to a large extent, whether we realize it or not. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin with, it is important to understand the meaning of&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/LED-PCB\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">LED PCBs</font></a>, and their true nature.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For one thing, they are exactly what they sound like, which is that they are LEDs or ‘Light Emitting Diodes’, integrated into a PCB or ‘Printed Circuit Board’. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>They are commonly used for a wide range of applications, ranging from simple electronics such as toys to large scale applications such as street lights. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-17/led-pcb-2.png\" alt=\"led-pcb-2.png\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is much that can be said about these LED PCBs, which can serve as a useful introduction. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Some of the most important details are given in the points below. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Low Heat Emission </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is by far one of the most important reasons for the usage of LED PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Most traditional source of light in a circuit or otherwise, have always had a problem with heat emission. This was because the emission of heat is an inevitable thing, since it is an intrinsic property of electricity. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the case of LED PCBs however, this isn’t much of a problem, since the problem is greatly diminished. It should be noted that the key point here is diminished and not nullified, for the heat is still generated, albeit so miniscule in comparison to that of traditional sources of lighting. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Furthermore, many of the emerging technologies come coupled with heat sinks, which allow for even the minuscule amount of heat to be eliminated. This in turn makes the entire circuitry and other components run at a relatively very low temperature. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Low Power Consumption </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another important advantage of LED PCBs is that they have very low power consumption, in every single case. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;It is for this reason that LED bulbs have started to become the new CFLs, and therefore are being widely promoted everywhere. In general, the need for power is cut down by as much as ten times, when one uses an LED in comparison to other sources of lighting. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The lowering of power consumption in turn will have a large scale impact on the overall energy efficiency, and eventually add up to cost savings. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The cost savings in turn may not be so apparent in small units, but when used on a large scale such as that of street lights or large buildings, it quickly becomes apparent. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also to be added is that the reduction in power consumption rarely comes at the cost of brightness. In nearly every case, the degree of brightness available is about the same or even more than traditional forms of lighting. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Lightweight Construction </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>LED PCBs tend to be lightweight in design and construction, compared to traditional forms of circuitry and design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This in turn helps out in the larger design aspect of technology, from the aesthetics and ergonomics, to overall production efficiency. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>An added advantage of being lightweight is that it allows for complex designs, large scale deployment, etc. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Easy to Manufacture &amp; Integrate &nbsp;</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The manufacturing of technology is never easy. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With a multitude of components, arrays and so on, your average piece of technology has a lot going on in the background before it reaches the end user. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While this is something that will never go away, what is clear is that the manufacturing process of LED PCBs is fairly simple and easy. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The end result of this is that the manufacturing process is simpler, while at the same time adding up to cost savings for the manufacturer. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) They are Largely Resistant to Dust &amp; Moisture </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While this is not an absolute per se, it is in comparison to the more traditional forms of circuits and lighting sources, far more resistant and durable. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This makes LED PCBs an excellent pick for both general purpose as well as heavy duty applications. More specifically, they make for ideal outdoor use, where there is frequent exposure to both dust and moisture, on an almost regular basis. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, the construction can be made further durable, through the design of proper protection, sealing systems, safety features and more, all of which can help to extend its resistance to the elements. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) Available in a Range of Colors &amp; Designs </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This has more to do with consumer choice and application necessity more than anything else. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The needs of the market are never the same, and that certainly holds true for LED PCBs. Given that there is always a wide range of needs for this technology, there will inevitably be a need for widespread customization, to suit that purpose. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The technological principles of LED PCBs, coupled with existing materials and advancements, allow for it to be used for a wide range of purposes, through the use of a wide range of colors, designs and more. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7.) Long-Lasting in Nature </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Last but not the least, LED PCBs are long lasting in nature. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>While this is once again use-dependent rather than an absolute, they do last longer than traditional or otherwise legacy technological systems. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several reasons for this, one of the most important being the construction. Traditional circuits were made from wires, which were prone to snapping and other kinds of breakage. It was in fact this aspect of early technologies, which made them unreliable. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>LED PCBs on the other hand, don’t have this problem for the simple reason that the circuits are printed onto the board, rather than wires connected at the edges. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Indeed, the same construction design of the board, also applies to the LEDs. Given that LEDs are essentially made up of a few components in a fairly solid form of construction, even this aspect of the technology is relatively rugged and durable. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This in turn, provides a wide range of benefits, which range from the lack of frequent maintenance, to overall cost savings, and the resulting increase of reliability. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><br></span><span>In all, the above list of points about LED PCBs should help you get a better understanding about the technology and its concepts. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There is indeed plenty more to this it than the points above, which you will come across, as you delve deeper into the world of electronics and technology.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>    ', 'PCB Technology', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'LED PCB -The Most Useful Introduction', 'LED PCB', '  LED PCB -The Most Useful Introduction  ', 0, '2019-12-17 14:03:33', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (77, 'EVERYTHING_YOU_NEED_TO_KNOW_ABOUT_HDI_PCB_77', '2019-12-19 14:08:36', NULL, 6, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit boards are essential to the correct operation of several different devices. Traditional PCBs are created using acid or some other form of etching that creates pathways in the board that lead to different components.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">These pathways are used for energy transfer. When the energy is transferred through the pathway, it causes the device that contains the<font color=\"#1e90ff\">&nbsp;</font><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">PCB</font></a>&nbsp;to perform a task or function. When there are issues with a device, the printed circuit board may be the problem. This, however, is only how a regular printed circuit board performs.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are different types of circuit boards that are used for different things. In today’s post, you will learn more about High Density Interconnector printed circuit boards, also known as HDI PCBs. Specifically, you will learn what an HDI PCB is, how they are made, and some of the devices that use HDI PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-19/HDI PCB.jpg\" alt=\"HDI PCB.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHAT IS AN HDI PCB</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>An&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/HDI-PCB\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">HDI PCB</font></a>&nbsp;is a printed circuit board that has a higher writing density per area than a regular printed circuit board. This means that the board contains more components with finer pathways and connection pads with higher densities.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are six main types of HDI PCBs:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Passive substrate with no electrical connection</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Alternate constructions of coreless constructions using layer pairs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Coreless construction using layer pairs</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Vias from surface to surface</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Buried vias through vias</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Two or more HDI layer with through vias</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>HOW THEY ARE MADE</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Creating HDI PCBs requires a lot of technician specialization, careful processes, and special equipment. Special equipment used in the HDI PCB manufacturing process includes plugging, laser drills, laser imaging, and sequential lamination cycles.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Laser drilling technology is very important in the creation of HDI PCBs. Traditional PCBs are typically created using acid. Some contact imaging processes are still being used today simply because the laser imaging process is costly. However, since the pathways to other components must be thin and compact, lasers are the best option for the creation process. This means that some of the traditional issues technicians may face with PCBs, such as acute angles, will not be an issue in HDI PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The beam of light used in this process is 20 microns, or 1 Mil in diameter, and is able to cut slightly through the metal and glass on the board to make tiny paths. The metal and glass used for HDI PCBs have a higher heat resistance, which makes this process possible.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Because there are thinner pathways to the components, careful work is a must. This means that the process often takes a lot longer than making a traditional PCB. Since the pathways are much finer and there are an increased number of components on the board and more electrical signals being sent, some precautions must be taken in the manufacturing process. The technician must include high-frequency transmission capabilities, impedance control, and establish a way to reduce unnecessary radiation. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To accomplish this, many manufacturers use a multi-layered design using insulating material. This makes different pathways on thinner HDI PCBs that are then layered to allow for the full functioning of the device that the HDI PCB will power. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>After the HDI PCBs are etched, they are put together through a lamination process. The layers are laid on top of one another and a heated roller method is used. The materials are preheated so that there is a consistent stable exit temperature in each board that is created. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHAT THEY ARE USED FOR</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are a number of items that HDI PCBs are used for. Perhaps the most popular thing HDI PCBs are used for is probably sitting in your hands at this very moment: smartphones. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Due to the complex tasks that smartphones must achieve, HDI PCBs are the best choice as they have a higher surface area for smaller pathways that can send and receive electrical signals quickly and easily. For example, the HDI PCB in a cellphone is considered the brain of the cell phone. This means the electrical signals sent through the circuit board help to perform function such as key recognition and display.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Next, gaming consoles typically use HDI PCBs. Gaming consoles such as PlayStation, Xbox, Switch, and even the older Nintendo consoles each perform complex interactions to allow a player to play through a game. In this case, an HDI PCB in a gaming console might communicate with the game controller and display to be sure the gaming process is smooth and enjoyable.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another popular device that contains HDI PCBs are personal computers or laptop computers. These compact devices allow for working on the go, surfing the web, or even video gaming. The HDI PCBs in this device are used to connect with the display, recognize keystrokes, and even connect with the mouse. Without a properly working HDI PCB, the laptop would be defunct.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Digital cameras also use HDI PCBs to perform difficult tasks that result in lasting memories. Digital cameras have a lot of functions and options when it comes to capturing something in the moment. From ISO and F-stop settings, to color balance and exposure, the HDI PCBs in digital cameras and DSLRs are important for their function.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, HDI PCBs are typically the type of printed circuit boards used in MP3s or other music devices. This is because of complex and multiple interaction options from choosing a song, playing the song, pausing a song, skipping a song, and so forth.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>CONCLUSION</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>High Density Interconnector printed circuit boards are so important for the use of some of our favorite devices. In addition, they have made the capabilities of these devices increase throughout the years.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For example, cellphones used to be heavy and clunky and really only gave us the ability to talk and text. But now, we can have an entire computer and personal assistant in the tips of our fingers thanks to the development of HDI PCBs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This article taught you a lot about the creation process and uses of the HDI PCB.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'EVERYTHING YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT HDI PCB', 'HDI PCB', '   EVERYTHING YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT HDI PCB ', 0, '2019-12-19 14:12:11', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (78, 'What_Do_I_Need_To_Pay_Attention_To_When_Ordering_PCB_Online_78', '2019-12-20 10:19:48', NULL, 5, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs or Printed Circuit Boards have become an indispensable part of our daily lives. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A concept that began several decades ago, has today become an almost every day necessity, and found in everything from toys to spacecrafts and everything in between. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is not without reason. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>From space management and efficiency to durability and low cost, a whole host of factors have played a key role in making this piece of technology an important part of modern society. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>And it is very likely that they will make their presence felt well into the future, albeit with better designs and features. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For manufacturers and primary users of&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">PCBs</font></a>, getting the right ones can prove to be quite a challenge, whether online or offline.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given in the steps below, are some important strategies to look into, when getting PCBs online. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-20/3.jpg\" alt=\"pcb.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Get a Suitable Supplier </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is by far one of the most important things worth paying attention to. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One mistake here will end up causing a cascading effect down the road, all the way until the final fabrication level. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given the widespread use of PCBs, it isn’t hard to find a suitable supplier for the same. At the same time however, it is going to be a difficult task trying to get the right people to do the job, give that not all companies or individuals have the kind of skillset and means to deliver what you need. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It would therefore be a good idea for one to take some time and verify the suppliers, before signing on the dotted line for the shipments. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) Check the Credentials &amp; Other Details </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the company has been identified, a little background information would prove to be of great help. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are many ways to do this. One of the most important would be that of checking with local business registries, government records, and if one is really into background checks, to get some testimonies from former clients. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, it would also be a good idea to check out the manufacturing facilities of the supplier, wherever possible, so as to get a first hand glimpse of where the PCBs will be assembled and manufactured. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Try to Use an Escrow Service </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>An escrow service is a company that acts as a financial mediator, between two or more parties. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>They are usually used as a ‘trust’ of sorts, where they hold money in the name of their clients, until a certain assignment or project is completed. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The usage of escrow services are often done for the sake of promoting trust and preventing cheating, and have become an important part of the modern day world.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Widespread in use across the business world, it would be a good idea to get in touch with them, so as to enjoy peace of mind and stable business dealing. They will charge a certain percentage as commission but it’s all worth it in the end. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Figure out Your Design </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the suppliers have been confirmed, the next thing to do would be the design stage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The average PCB can be designed in any number of ways, depending on the size of the board and the need of the client. This in turn necessitates a design that is efficient, simple and at the same time cost effective. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Previously done manually, it is today a largely computerized process, where the design process from the beginning until the end is managed by specialized software. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Furthermore, the design process itself may be done either with the help of designers working for the company, or have the project outsourced to a third party supplier. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) Complete the Necessary Registrations </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>With the final designs ready, the next step would be to get busy with the registrations. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Quite often, PCB manufacturers will request that one registers themselves with the business, before they make any transaction. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This stage will require you to provide a lot of information, ranging from the name and address of your company, to payment details, identification documents, etc. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>All of these details are necessary for a range of reasons, such as the verification of the buyer, legal requirements, and the need for a shipping address and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) Submit Your PCB Board Layout</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the design has been finalized, the next step would be the submission of the same to the PCB supplier. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Done electronically, the process should take only a few minutes at most, and help begin with the manufacturing process. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In addition to this, it would be a good idea to request for a sample shipment first, before going in for a large batch. It should ensure that there aren’t any problems down the line with the PCB quality, final layout, final design or anything else. Should there be any issues with this sample batch, one can take steps to have the necessary changes made before continuing the PCB production.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Once the production is complete, you should be able to expect the shipment from the supplier. Larger orders are typically delivered in batches, over several days or sometimes even weeks and months. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7.) Prepare Paperwork When Necessary </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is not so much a guaranteed requirement, but a fairly common one. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In cases where the supplier is overseas, there may be the need to fill out a bit of paperwork, such as those concerning shipping, customs, duties, etc, at the port of entry. Similar ones may exist with banks, with regard to clearance of foreign payments. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Also worth pointing out here, is that one will need to keep in constant touch with the shipping companies. Quite often, international shipping companies give a certain ‘tracking number’ which can be used to identify the location of one’s delivery, often in real time. As much as it isn’t necessary, keeping a close eye on things will help keep things running smoothly. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It should be noted that the clearance of these papers may take some time, depending on the typical time needed, to the existing workload of the competent authorities. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If one wishes to avoid this little step, it would be a good idea to go for a local supplier, as much of the hassles can be avoided by both the parties. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To sum it up, steps like these and others like it should help you get the ideal PCB for your projects. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are indeed many more such strategies that can be used as well, all of which will go a long way in making things easier and efficient, and speeding up your work in the long run.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'What Do I Need To Pay Attention To When Ordering PCB Online', 'Order PCB Online', 'What Do I Need To Pay Attention To When Ordering PCB Online ', 0, '2019-12-20 10:20:19', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (79, 'DOES_CHINESE_PCB_ASSEMBLY_HAVE_ITS_UNIQUE_ADVANTAGES_79', '2019-12-21 10:17:27', NULL, 4, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>China is known for being an outsourcing post for the manufacturing of several items used in different countries around the world. Printed circuit boards are valuable pieces of technology that are found in many of the devices and products we use daily. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Because printed circuit boards are used so often and important to the proper function of products that companies need to make sure that they’re getting the best quality possible for the money they are able to invest. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>So, to answer the question posed in the title: yes.&nbsp;</span><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-Assembly/PCB-Assembly-Overview\">Chinese PCB assembly</a>&nbsp;</font>has several unique advantages to printed circuit board assembly in other countries.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In this article, you will learn why it is important to invest your money in a good PCB assembly and the four main reasons why Chinese PCB assembly has unique advantages to other countries and their own PCB assemblies.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-21/017.jpg\" alt=\"china pcb assembly.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>THE IMPORTANCE OF INVESTING YOUR MONEY WISELY</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes time to find a PCB assembly that works best for your product and your budget, you need to make sure you’re investing your money wisely. However, there are many options that can meet your needs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>But, above all, there are several things you need to consider before investing your money in a company to do printed circuit board assembly for you and your product.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>First, you need to make sure that the assembly you use takes advantage of the best and most up-to-date technology for printed circuit board assembly. The interesting thing about PCBs is that pretty much anyone can try and make one on their own at home. However, this usually leads to a number of human errors that can render the board unusable. This can end up wasting your money and taking up a lot of your valuable time.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The assembly company you use should have access to software that can help design and create your PCB. This ensures that all of your components and pathways are disbursed well for heat and will all connect correctly so the PCB can perform the task your product needs it to perform. Without an assembly that uses these things, you may end up with a number of defective boards that are a waste of your money and can set back the production of your product.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Next, you need to check into labor costs and the costs of manufacturing your printed circuit boards. In many countries like the U.K. and the U.S., it is entirely possible to create quality boards. However, due to the cost of labor and manufacturing, it could be more expensive than exploring other options for your assembly needs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is also very important to ensure that the assembly company that you hire has a number of highly qualified technicians on hand to meet the manufacturing demands that you have or expect to have. Qualified technicians and manpower will usually cost more depending on the assembly company you choose to hire.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another important factor is how the defective or old printed circuit boards will be disposed of after the manufacturing process. Many countries have strict laws against improper disposal of toxic waste and chemicals that may be used in the process of created the PCBs. You don’t want your company’s name attached to a printed circuit board assembly team that does not properly dispose of chemicals. This can lead to the loss of clients and even legal action against you, which is why you must make the right choice for your company!</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You should also be checking into customer experience as a way to gauge how valuable your investment into a particular PCB assembly will be. If you see that the PCB assembly you wanted to work with has a lower rating and a high rate of customer dissatisfaction, you may want to consider putting your investment elsewhere. There is no use in paying a company who will not do the job well a ton of money when you could find a better alternative that will value your partnership.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>All of these are reasons why you need to look deeper into the company you are investing your money into. As previously mentioned, many companies in the U.S. and U.K. may be able to help in some of these areas, but this next section will cover all of the reasons why Chinese printed circuit board assemblies are the best option for you and your company.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHY CHINESE PCB ASSEMBLY HAS UNIQUE ADVANTAGES</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin, much of the technology that is used in the design and manufacture of PCBs comes out of China. That is to say that much of the knowledge for best practices originated there. This means that you can bet that your PCBs will be effective and high quality due to the amount of expertise on PCBs in China.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another reason why Chinese printed circuit board assembly has unique advantages is the lower labor costs. Because labor in creating PCBs is less expensive in China, that means that the final product will be high quality at a lower cost than what you will find in America or similar countries. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Additionally, because these costs are so low, there is plenty of opportunity to have more technicians on hand to observe and participate in the manufacturing process. This means that there will be fewer mistakes and defective PCBs can be identified and disposed of so that they don’t make it into the final product.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, a major advantage to using Chinese printed circuit board assembly is how the China deals with the disposal of toxic waste. There are a number of elements, including lead, that is used in the manufacture of printed circuit boards. China has a strict recycling and waste system that makes the disposal of products and obsolete boards better for the environment and more affordable for the manufacturer and company using the printed circuit boards.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As you can see, there are a number of advantages to working with Chinese PCB assemblies to manufacture your printed circuit boards.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'DOES CHINESE PCB ASSEMBLY HAVE ITS UNIQUE ADVANTAGES', 'china pcb assembly', '  DOES CHINESE PCB ASSEMBLY HAVE ITS UNIQUE ADVANTAGES', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (80, 'PCB_LAYOUT_AND_PCB_LAYOUT_SOFTWARE_80', '2019-12-23 10:26:02', NULL, 8, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Printed circuit boards are small components that are used in our everyday electronics to help them function correctly. Without printed circuit boards, you couldn’t watch television, play your favorite video game, or even call or text your friends on your phone.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although circuit boards are small, they play an important role. In this post, you will learn why the layout of a printed circuit board is important, why you should use a PCB software to layout your design, and a few good PCB layout software features as well as a few software options that are available for purchase now.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-23/OSP pcb.jpg\" alt=\"OSP pcb.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHY YOUR LAYOUT IS IMPORTANT</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs are incredibly small and fragile. Because of this, there are a number of reasons why the layout of a PCB is so important.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Heat distribution is one of the most important aspects of PCB design. Printed circuit boards are a lot like the human nervous system. Signals are sent throughout the printed circuit board using electricity. When a PCB is poorly designed, it can lead to a number of heat distribution problems.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several problems that can lead to problems with overheating. First, if the lines or pathways are too small for the amount of energy being pushed through them, it can cause the PCB to overheat. This is because the PCB is forcing a lot of energy through a very small space. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Secondly, component placement can influence the heat distribution within the PCB. If one side of the PCB has a lot more components than the other side, a lot of energy is flowing to that side. This means that this side of the board is overloaded and can cause heating issues.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Heating issues are often solved by the inclusion of a fan to keep PCBs cool.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Wiring is another issue when it comes to the importance of PCB layout. Without properly laying out your components, it can be nearly impossible to have space to attach wires. That’s why creating a mock layout and laying out your components is so important. You don’t want to realize that you don’t have room for your wires when you’re halfway done placing and soldering your components.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, the signal integrity is an important reason why care should be taken in designing a PCB. What good is the circuit board if there are electrical problems that interfere with sending signals to the device?</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Routing the traces in a certain way is important to avoiding this issue. Basically, traces should be routed parallel and close to one another. This reduces the amount of noise and interference, so the PCB can operate to its fullest potential.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Although these three are not the only reasons why PCB layout is important, they are among the most important reasons. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHY YOU SHOULD USE A PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you know why PCB layout is so important to the integrity of the printed circuit board and the device it helps power; you need to know why a PCB layout software can be beneficial.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first reason is that using a software can remove some human error that occurs during the design process. When you design something on your own, you have to rely on your own math and your own vision. Software can take the guesswork out of the process and can help to make sure that measurements and calculations are accurate. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another reason is that the software can give you a schematic that you can work off of during the design process. This will give you a roadmap to creating a perfect printed circuit board. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, some design software can actually simulate what it would be like to have your design work in a certain environment. This can help you determine what changes you may need to make in order to create the best PCB for the device you’re making it for.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>GOOD PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE FEATURES AND SOME SUGGESTIONS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are a ton of options out there when it comes to PCB layout software. The options are nearly limitless. That is why it is important to make sure that the design software that you purchase or use is one that has the following features:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>An easy-to-use interface:</span></b><span>&nbsp;You don’t need to pay a ton of money for a software that has a difficult interface. Find one that is easy to use and won’t take long to understand.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Contains a large library of components:</span></b><span>&nbsp;As a technician, you don’t necessarily know what components a customer will need before they order. That is why your software should have the ability for you to add various components to your design. This can help you to know where the component should be soldered and how to best lay out the components for optimal heat distribution.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Design automation:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Sometimes, it helps to have an automated design that is available with the click of a button. This can take out a ton of work and can save you time. If need be, you should be able to move around these automated components in your software to fit your need.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Cost effective:</span></b><span>&nbsp;As you can imagine, software used to design anything can be pretty expensive. Software options available now range from free to nearly $7,000. You must compare the features and benefits of each software to determine what the best option is for you.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you know some key features you should look for, here are some of the top PCB design software on the market and some of their specifications:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>DipTrace Full:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $995 and has no limits in what you can do.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Eagle:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $65 a month or $500 a year and has no limits.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>Altium Designer:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $7,245 and has no limits. This one is often heralded as the best PCB design software available today.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>DipTrace Starter:</span></b><span>&nbsp;Costs $75 and has a 300 pin and two signal layer limit.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><b><span>EasyEDA:</span></b><span>&nbsp;This is a free software with no limits.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Now you know all you need to know about<b>&nbsp;</b><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/PCB-layout\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\">PCB layouts</font></a>&nbsp;</b>and the best layout software available!</p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'PCB LAYOUT AND PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE', 'PCB LAYOUT', 'PCB LAYOUT AND PCB LAYOUT SOFTWARE', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (81, '10_Key_Tactics_the_Pros_Use_For_Printed_Circuit_Board_81', '2019-12-27 14:58:13', NULL, 8, 0, 0, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>If there is one thing about the modern world of electronics that is widespread, it would be PCBs </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>PCBs, an acronym for ‘Printed Circuit Boards’, are today found wherever there is a need for electrical connections, making them an integral part of the modern technological world. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin with, PCB technology was an innovation that came about several decades ago. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Developed to replace inefficient wires, they quickly became highly sought after for a host of benefits, including but not limited to structural strength, efficiency, lower energy needs, etc. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Today, the usage of PCBs has only continued, and given the current trends, very likely to continue well into the near future. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When it comes to the design aspect of the PCBs, there is a lot that can be said. One of the most important, and also interesting, would be the many steps used by professionals to make these technological marvels. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Given in the list below, are ten key tactics used by the pros for&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com\"><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b>manufacturing printed circuit boards</b></font></a><span>. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-27/Immersion Tin PCB .jpg\" alt=\"Immersion Tin PCB .jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>1.) Management of Resistance </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The design of PCBs needs to take into consideration the amount of thickness, length and width to control the PCB trace resistance. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For those wondering what resistance is, it is a term used to define the property of a metal, where there is a certain ‘resistance’ to the flow of electricity through a wire or other such object made from it. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the ways in which the trace is made, is through the measuring of the amount of copper used, typically in ounces. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In simple terms, the variability of the thickness of the trace can provide for a range of different resistances, in turn allowing for a range of possibilities to be achieved during the design phase of the PCB circuit. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>2.) The Management of Heat </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>An important issue with almost any electronic in the world, is heat. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Electricity has the property of heat generation, which can be a good or bad thing, depending on how you look at it. In the case of bathroom components such as geysers or boilers, it can be great. But in the case of electronics such as computer components or PCBs in general, it can be a real nightmare. This is because excess heat can damage the components and in some cases even prove to be a fire hazard. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>One of the most common ways in which the heat has been traditionally dealt with is with the help of a heatsink. In general, a heat sink can be thought of as a metal plate, which has a large surface area to allow for the heat to flow through it and into the air around it. The heat sink often comes together with a cooling fan, as in the case of the cooling system on top of a computer processor. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In many cases, the PCB mounted heatsinks tend to connect to heat sources, as well as vast areas of the board itself, so as to allow for the maximum dispersal of heat from the system.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>3.) Using Smaller Loops </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A loop can be understood as a circuit that goes in a ‘loop’ manner from one part of the circuit board to another. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It is very easy to observe in a typical board, where the circuit starts off as a straight line from one end to another, after which it turns at a certain angle, and then once more until the direction of the circuit is changed entirely. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is done for a variety of reasons such as creating enough space for components, providing for the necessary resistance and so on. Smaller loops are preferred because they have ea lower inductance and resistance in comparison to larger ones. In addition to this, there is also a marked reduction of high frequency voltage spikes during usage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>4.) Decoupling the Placement of Capacitors </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A good idea for the placement of capacitors would be to have them as close as possible to the power and ground pins of the PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The reason for this is that it helps to prevent issues associated with inductance and radiation. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>5.) The Management of Via Size &amp; Number </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Vias have a certain inductance and resistance to them, which play a key role in the design and function of PCBs. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When routing a trace from one part of the PCB to another and there exists the need for a low inductance or resistance, it would e a good idea for one to use multiple vias. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Likewise, the usage of large vias is a good strategy in cases where there is a need for lower resistance. This is particularly good when it comes to the use of grounding filter capacitors and other high current nodes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>6.) The Placement of Heat Sensitive Components </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several components on a PCB which are heat sensitive. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Even in cases where they are ‘shielded’ from the heat through physical barriers, there is still a certain potential for heat damage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The components which come under this category include, among others, MOSFETs, diodes, bridge rectifiers, inductors and resistors. All of these components tend to have a very low degree of heat tolerance, and can be negatively affected when exposed to the same. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These components must therefore be placed as far away from sources of heat as possible. The use of heatsinks is another good way to protect these delicate components from heat-related damage. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>7.) Preventing Damage during the Drilling of Holes </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The average PCB comes with a range of holes, which serve a variety of purposes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>These holes are typically drilled using mechanical means, and the process itself is a standard industry practice. The holes in turn, after being drilled, become the base for vias, and other circuitry. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The major concern is not so much the hole, but rather the board’s integrity. Drilling a hole through the board can result in damage, especially through spinning, in cases where the board isn’t secured. It should therefore be ensured that the board is properly secured, before any drilling is begun. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Likewise, the same holds true for the drilling process itself, where the correct drilling location is confirmed, so as to avoid damaging any nearby circuitry or design. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>8.) Leave Room between Copper Traces &amp; Fills </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is important because the lack of space can result in a short circuit, or other shock hazard. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Always ensure that a certain amount of space exists between the copper traces at all times. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>9.) Keep Noise &amp; Analog Traces Away from Each Other </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This is an important thing to remember, as the two tend to get in the way of each other, resulting in a ‘doubling’ of the signal on the traces. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The consequence of this can range from interference to short-circuits, both of which are bad for the PCB. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>10.) A Second Opinion Is a Good Thing </span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As much as you may be confident with your design, it is a good idea to get a second opinion. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A neutral third-party review of the design can go a long way in giving you another perspective of things, and help you make any necessary changes. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>This will help in everything from the overall design improvement to raising efficiency and so on. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In summary, there are indeed many ways in which the manufacturing of PCBs can be done. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>At the same time however, some strategies and tips are much better in comparison to others, for a wide range of factors. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The points mentioned above, as well as others like them are a great way to know about the many unique ways that experts go about with the design process, ultimately making the technology efficient, safe and reliable for everyone.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, '10 Key Tactics the Pros Use For Printed Circuit Board', 'Printed Circuit Board', '  10 Key Tactics the Pros Use For Printed Circuit Board', 0, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (82, 'WHAT_IS_A_HEAVY_COPPER_PCB_82', '2019-12-29 16:31:47', NULL, 13, 0, 0, ' <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Regular printed circuit boards are used in a number of low-voltage and low-power appliances and devices to help them function properly. However, what kind of printed circuit board is used for appliances and devices that need more voltage and power? Heavy copper PCB.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In this post, you are going to learn everything you need to know about heavy copper PCBs. This will include a more in-depth description of heavy copper PCBs, a few examples of where they can be found, and characteristics that make heavy copper PCBs different from the traditional ones.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>HEAVY COPPER PCBS</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Heavy copper PCBs are specifically printed circuit boards that are thicker and heavier for the sake of handling higher voltage and power. To help you understand, a traditional printed coper board will have a weight ranging between ½ oz/ft</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>&nbsp;to 3 oz/ft</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>. But, heavy copper PCBs usually weights between 4 oz/ft</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>to 20 oz/ft</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As you can see, this weight is a significant gain from the traditional printed circuit board. Because this weighs more, it also is thicker. This means that it can stand up the high power it was created for.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;<p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-29/copper pcb.jpg\" alt=\"copper pcb.jpg\" style=\"\"></p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHAT DEVICES CONTAIN HEAVY COPPER PCBS?</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>You will mainly find heavy copper PCBs in larger pieces of electronics. These will include things like transformers and power convertors. These are mainly used to divert or direct power to certain sources. As previously mentioned, they are built to handle high volumes of electricity.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Hybrid and electric cars have become an ideal mode of transportation for many. With the emphasis many are putting on protecting the environment through a reduce use of fuel, electric cards have become a popular choice. Did you know that electrical cars are usually homes to heavy copper PCBs? It takes a lot of power to charge and run a full car off of a battery!</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Solar batteries and solar panels are also frequent users of heavy copper printed circuit boards. They allow for the mass movement of energy collected from the sun. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>BENEFITS OF USING A HEAVY COPPER PCB</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>A lot of the benefits of&nbsp;</span><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-FAB/Thick-Copper-PCBs\">heavy copper PCB</a>&nbsp;</b></font>deal with thermal rates.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Firstly, there is less thermal strain when using a heavy copper PCB. This is because copper itself has a high thermal and electrical conductivity level, so it can take the heat and the extra electrical power that is thrown its way.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Because these PCBs are made with extra copper, they can also survive through several thermal cycles. Some other PCBs will wear down more quickly or even burn if put through the amount of heat heavy copper PCBs go through.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Not only do heavy copper PCBs do a great job of keeping the temperature in check, they also do a great job of providing an uninterrupted flow of energy. This is because copper itself is a natural conductor. Heavy copper PCBs also tend to be smaller in size because they are usually layered. This means that they are made to be compact and to fit into devices that will require extra power.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Lastly, copper is a very affordable resource, so these types of PCBs are not too costly to create. This is a benefit because more expensive materials can start to get too costly for some companies.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>DISADVANTAGES OF USING A HEAVY COPPER PCB</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>When there is good, there is also bad. Unfortunately, the manufacturing of heavy copper printed circuit boards can result in a few issues.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin, there can be an issue in the etching process. Because the heavy copper PCB weighs more and is thicker, it might be difficult to accurately etch the pathways into the PCB. This can cause a ton of issues. One major issue it can cause is noise, which is the disruption or interference of an electrical signal. This happens when pathways are not deep or long enough, resulting in a spilling over of electricity. &nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another issue with the creation of a heavy copper PCB is inner layer alignment. Heavy copper PCBs are layered, but there can be some issues in aligning these layers so that each pathway and component can perform the proper function when an electrical signal is created. This can cause issues with the product the heavy copper PCB is in and can keep it from performing correctly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Next is the issue of delamination. When putting a number of layers together, a technician creating a heavy copper PCB must use a lamination process. The laminate is used to also fill voids. But, improper application of the laminate can cause issues on the board and can cause the board to fall apart. This will obviously lead to issues that are hard to fix. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>HOW THE CREATION PROCESS IS DIFFERENT</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now that you know the advantages and disadvantages of creating a heavy copper PCB, it is time to learn more about how the creation process for a heavy copper printed circuit board is different from the creation process of a traditional printed circuit board.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Obviously, the amount of copper used is greatly increased. This is a given! But the increased amount of copper also means an increased amount of time in production. Because these PCBs will come out more thick and heavier, it will take more time to accurately cut into the pieces of copper. If a company were to do this too quickly, it could result in a number of issues that could render the product the heavy copper PCB will go into utterly useless. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The layering is also a bit different. Because differential etching is used, it can sometimes be difficult to align the layers of copper for the best fit. The layering, however, makes for the creation of a more compact and powerful printed circuit board that is ready to take on high voltage and power needs.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>CONCLUSION</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As you can see, there is a lot to know about heavy copper printed circuit boards. These boards are designed with power in mind. Now you know the important aspects of the design and manufacturing of these PCBs.&nbsp;</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>   ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'WHAT IS A HEAVY COPPER PCB', 'COPPER PCB', '  WHAT IS A HEAVY COPPER PCB ', 0, '2019-12-29 16:34:53', NULL);
INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (83, 'EVERYTHING_YOU_WANT_TO_KNOW_ABOUT_LOW_VOLUME_PCB_ASSEMBLY_83', '2019-12-30 08:52:49', NULL, 9, 0, 0, '  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Low volume printed circuit board assembly may seem simple to understand, but there are different uses and benefits to this manufacturing service.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>1. In this article, you will learn more about what low volume PCB assembly is, the benefits of low volume PCB assembly, and TKTKKTKTKTK.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHAT IS LOW VOLUME PCB ASSEMBLY?</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>2. The name is a good indication of what low volume PCB assembly is. This is basically when a small number of printed circuit boards, usually between 25 and 5,000, are manufactured. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>3. There are two main types of low volume PCB assembly services that most manufacturers offer. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The first is design for manufacturing, or DFM. This service usually consists of quality checks on the design such as the assembly files, bill of materials, and circuit diagrams. Checks like these are a great way to avoid issues during a larger manufacturing process and places deeper scrutiny on the components that are used in the manufacturing process.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The other type is design for testing, or DTM. This type of service can help manufacturers and clients get an in-depth knowledge on the test points around the printed circuit board. During this process, most manufacturers will be able to do performance testing and come up with troubleshooting instructions. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><img src=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/file/2019-12-30/014.jpg\" alt=\"014.jpg\" style=\"\"></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>WHAT ARE THE BENEFITS OF A LOW VOLUME PCB ASSEMBLY?</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>There are several different benefits to choosing a&nbsp;</span><font color=\"#1e90ff\"><b><a href=\"https://www.pcbonline.com/PCB-Assembly/Low-Volume-PCB-Assembly\">low volume PCB assembly</a></b></font>.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>To begin, using this method can save a lot of money. Manufacturing can be expensive. If you or your company is manufacturing a new device that needs a PCB, you will want to make sure that all of the bugs are worked out before manufacturing on a more intense scale. Because you can use the PCBs from the low volume PCB assembly process, you will be able to learn about the issues within the device and how to solve them. In addition, if you work with a company that provides your low volume PCB assembly, you will find that they often wave fees and do their best to keep you from extra charges. This is because these companies work with smaller companies and like to keep their business.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Another major benefit of a low volume PCB assembly is the testing capabilities you will have with a low volume PCB assembly. As previously mentioned, low volume PCB assembly companies will put your PCBs through a string of important tests to make sure that your PCB is doing the right job. This is vitally important because some larger manufacturers will not take the time to test your boards to make sure they are working properly. This could lead to defective products that will cost you money in the future.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Low volume PCB assembly processes also make it possible for you to change your designs. This process is believed to be the best option for prototypes, so a lot of low volume PCB assembly lines will allow you to make the needed changes to your circuit board so that it does its job without causing additional issues.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>POTENTIAL ISSUES YOU CAN AVOID WITH LOW VOLUME PCB ASSEMBLY</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>As with any electronic device, PCBs can come with glitches or issues that can render the boards unusable. Here are some of the major issues that low volume PCB assembly can help you avoid:</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Overheating. When it comes to the design of your PCB, you should work to ensure that all of the components of your board are spaced in a way that allows for the even distribution of heat around the board. When products are not designed with this in mind, they can overheat, catch fire, and render a product unusable, which can end up being a public relations nightmare, especially if it is a widespread issue. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Using a low volume PCB assembly method can reduce the possibility of this because you will be able to identify potential heat issues and solve them in the manufacturing process.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Bad soldering. Soldering is the process by which the components of your printed circuit board are attached to the main board. This is usually done by melting metal over the part to attach it. However, due to issues that can occur such as a soldering gun that is not at a high enough temperature, components of the board can become dislodged and can cause the board to function improperly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>During the low volume PCB assembly process, careful consideration and time is put into the manufacturing process. This means that all PCBs get a good amount of attention, so soldering issues are much less likely to occur.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"15\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·&nbsp;</span><!--[endif]--><span>Improper spacing. PCBs work because they create small pathways through which energy can travel to various other components. It is this energy that can cause a certain action to happen. For example, if you hit a button on your telephone, the result of that number registering is due to the travel of energy from one part of the PCB to another. However, if you don’t take time to really look at your design and its potential flaws, you may see that the pathways or components are not spaced out properly.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Low volume PCB assembly can address this issue by allowing you to take a look at a real version of your PCB design. During testing phases, you will be able to know if your pathways and your components are properly spaced. If they aren’t, this can lead to overheating and a confusion that can cause one thing to register as another. </span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>All of these potential hazards can impact your business and cause issues in your growth. You can instead choose to use a low volume PCB assembly process to work out these issues before you manufacture your PCBs on a grander scale.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span>CONCLUSION</span></b><b><span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Now you know everything you need to know about low volume PCB assembly. Not only is it more cost effective and gives you a chance to change your designs, it also helps to stop potential issues such as overheating, bad soldering, and improper spacing.</span><span><o:p></o:p></span></p>    ', 'PCB News', 1, 37, 2, 'seo', NULL, 'EVERYTHING YOU WANT TO KNOW ABOUT LOW VOLUME PCB ASSEMBLY', 'LOW VOLUME PCB ASSEMBLY', '    tydrt', 0, '2020-04-26 16:10:29', '  ');
